{"title_page": "Wazirabad\u2013Narowal Branch Line", "text_new": "{{Use Pakistani English|date=May 2019}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2019}}\n{{more citations needed|date=January 2017}}\n{{Infobox rail line\n| box_width     = 350px\n| name          = Wazirabad\u2013Narowal Branch Line<br>{{Nastaliq|'''\u0648\u0632\u0650\u064a\u0631\u0622\u0628\u0627\u062f-\u0646\u0627\u0631\u0648\u0648\u0627\u0644 \u0641\u0631\u0639\u06cc \u0631\u06cc\u0644\u0648\u06d2 \u062e\u0637'''}}\n| other_name    = \n| native_name   = \n| native_name_lang = ur\n| color         = \n| logo          =\n| logo_width    = \n| logo_alt      = \n| image         = \n| image_width   = \n| image_alt     = \n| caption       =\n| type          = \n| system        = \n| status        = \n| locale        = \n| start         = [[Wazirabad Junction railway station|Wazirabad Junction]]\n| end           = [[Narowal Junction railway station|Narowal Junction]]\n| stations      = 15\n| routes        =\n\n| ridership2    = \n| open          = {{Start date|1915|07|22|df=y}}\n| event1label   = \n| event1        = \n| event2label   = \n| event2        = \n| event3label   = \n| event3        = \n| close         = \n| owner         = [[Pakistan Railways]]\n| operator      = [[Pakistan Railways]]\n| character     = \n| depot         = \n| stock         = \n| linelength_km = {{convert|132.3|km|mi|sp=us}}\n| linelength_mi =  \n| linelength    =  \n| tracklength_km=  \n| tracklength_mi=  \n| tracklength   =\n\n| gauge         = {{RailGauge|1676mm|lk=on}}\n\n| minradius     = \n| racksystem    = \n| routenumber   = \n| linenumber    =\n\n| speed_km/h    = \n| speed_mph     = \n| speed         = {{convert|110|km/h|mph|abbr=on}} ('''Current''')<br/> {{convert|150|km/h|mph|abbr=on}} (''Proposed'')<ref>{{cite book|title=Pakistan Railways: A Performance Analysis -  Citizens\u2019 Periodic Reports on the Performance of State Institutions|date=December 2015|publisher=PILDAT|location=Islamabad|isbn=978-969-558-589-4|page=21|url=http://www.pildat.org/publications/publication/QualityofGovernance/PerformanceAnalysisofPakistanRailways.pdf|accessdate=18 August 2016|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160124213207/http://pildat.org/Publications/publication/QualityofGovernance/PerformanceAnalysisofPakistanRailways.pdf|archivedate=24 January 2016|language=en}}</ref>\n| elevation_m   = \n| elevation_ft  = \n| elevation     = \n| website       = \n| map           = \n}}\n\n'''Wazirabad\u2013Narowal Branch Line''' ({{lang-ur|{{Nastaliq|'''\u0648\u0632\u0650\u064a\u0631\u0622\u0628\u0627\u062f-\u0646\u0627\u0631\u0648\u0648\u0627\u0644 \u0641\u0631\u0639\u06cc \u0631\u06cc\u0644\u0648\u06d2 \u062e\u0637'''}}}}) is one of several [[Railway lines in Pakistan|branch lines in Pakistan]], operated and maintained by [[Pakistan Railways]]. The line originally runs from [[Wazirabad Junction railway station|Wazirabad Junction station]] to [[Narowal Junction railway station|Narowal Junction station]]. The total length of this railway line is {{convert|132.3|km|mi|sp=us}}. There are 15 railway stations from Wazirabad Junction to Narowal Junction.<ref>{{cite book|title=Pakistan Railways Time & Fare Table 2015|publisher=National Book Foundation|location=Pakistan|pages=94\u201399|edition=October 2015|url=http://pakrail.com/images/musafir/musafirTT2015.pdf|accessdate=18 August 2016|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160818174648/http://pakrail.com/images/musafir/musafirTT2015.pdf|archivedate=18 August 2016|language=English, Urdu}}</ref> Before partition of [[India]] & before creation of [[Pakistan ]] in 1947, this line used to ran {{convert|36.7|km|mi|sp=us}} up to [[Dera Baba Nanak]], which is Indian Side of \" The Kartarpur Corridor\" with a {{convert|56.9|km|mi|sp=us}} Branch line connecting [[Chak Amru]], [[Shakargarh]] & [[Kartarpur]] from [[Jassar Junction]].  Furthermore {{convert|39.1|km|mi|sp=us}} length of this line which was being constructed to connect [[Gurudaspur]] of Indian [[Punjab]] state was shelved & the line was dismantled completely. \n\n==History==\nThe Wazirabad\u2013Narowal Branch Line was built by the [[North Western State Railway]] in 1915 and originally named as the ''Sialkot\u2013Narowal Railway''.<ref>[https://archive.org/stream/BombayBarodaAndCentralIndiaRailwaySystem/Bombay_Baroda_And_Central_India_Railway_System#page/n127/mode/2up \" Administration Report on the Railways in India \u2013 corrected up to 31st March 1918\"; Superintendent of Government  Printing,  Calcutta;  page 119]; Retrieved 21 Dec 2015</ref>\n\n==Stations==\nThe railway stations on this railway line are:\n* [[Wazirabad Junction railway station|'''Wazirabad Junction''']]\n* [[Sodhra Kopra railway station|Sodhra Kopra]]\n* [[Begowala Ghartal railway Station|Begowala Ghartal]]\n* [[Sambrial railway station|Sambrial]]\n* [[Sahowala railway station|Sahowala]]\n* [[Ugoki railway station|Ugoki]]\n* [[Sialkot Junction railway station|'''Sialkot Junction''']]\n* [[Tasirabad Halt railway station|Tasirabad Halt]]\n* [[Gunna Kalan railway station|Gunna Kalan]]\n* [[Alhar railway station|Alhar]]\n* [[Chawinda railway station|Chawinda]]\n* [[Pasrur railway station|Pasrur]]\n* [[Qila Sobha Singh railway station|Qila Sobha Singh]]\n* [[Alipur Sayadan Sharif railway station|Alipur Sayadan Sharif]]\n* [[Domala railway station|Domala]]\n* [[Narowal Junction railway station|'''Narowal Junction''']]\n\n==See also==\n*[[Pakistan Railways]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Wazirabad\u2013Narowal Branch Line}}\n{{Railway lines in Pakistan}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Wazirabad-Narowal railway line}}\n[[Category:Railway stations on Wazirabad\u2013Narowal Branch Line]]\n[[Category:Railway lines opened in 1915]]\n[[Category:5 ft 6 in gauge railways in Pakistan]]\n\n\n{{Pakistan-rail-transport-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Use Pakistani English|date=May 2019}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2019}}\n{{more citations needed|date=January 2017}}\n{{Infobox rail line\n| box_width     = 350px\n| name          = Wazirabad\u2013Narowal Branch Line<br>{{Nastaliq|'''\u0648\u0632\u0650\u064a\u0631\u0622\u0628\u0627\u062f-\u0646\u0627\u0631\u0648\u0648\u0627\u0644 \u0641\u0631\u0639\u06cc \u0631\u06cc\u0644\u0648\u06d2 \u062e\u0637'''}}\n| other_name    = \n| native_name   = \n| native_name_lang = ur\n| color         = \n| logo          =\n| logo_width    = \n| logo_alt      = \n| image         = \n| image_width   = \n| image_alt     = \n| caption       =\n| type          = \n| system        = \n| status        = \n| locale        = \n| start         = [[Wazirabad Junction railway station|Wazirabad Junction]]\n| end           = [[Narowal Junction railway station|Narowal Junction]]\n| stations      = 15\n| routes        =\n\n| ridership2    = \n| open          = {{Start date|1915|07|22|df=y}}\n| event1label   = \n| event1        = \n| event2label   = \n| event2        = \n| event3label   = \n| event3        = \n| close         = \n| owner         = [[Pakistan Railways]]\n| operator      = [[Pakistan Railways]]\n| character     = \n| depot         = \n| stock         = \n| linelength_km = 91\n| linelength_mi =  \n| linelength    =  \n| tracklength_km=  \n| tracklength_mi=  \n| tracklength   =\n\n| gauge         = {{RailGauge|1676mm|lk=on}}\n\n| minradius     = \n| racksystem    = \n| routenumber   = \n| linenumber    =\n\n| speed_km/h    = \n| speed_mph     = \n| speed         = {{convert|105|km/h|mph|abbr=on}} ('''Current''')<br/> {{convert|160|km/h|mph|abbr=on}} (''Proposed'')<ref>{{cite book|title=Pakistan Railways: A Performance Analysis -  Citizens\u2019 Periodic Reports on the Performance of State Institutions|date=December 2015|publisher=PILDAT|location=Islamabad|isbn=978-969-558-589-4|page=21|url=http://www.pildat.org/publications/publication/QualityofGovernance/PerformanceAnalysisofPakistanRailways.pdf|accessdate=18 August 2016|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160124213207/http://pildat.org/Publications/publication/QualityofGovernance/PerformanceAnalysisofPakistanRailways.pdf|archivedate=24 January 2016|language=en}}</ref>\n| elevation_m   = \n| elevation_ft  = \n| elevation     = \n| website       = \n| map           = \n}}\n\n'''Wazirabad\u2013Narowal Branch Line''' ({{lang-ur|{{Nastaliq|'''\u0648\u0632\u0650\u064a\u0631\u0622\u0628\u0627\u062f-\u0646\u0627\u0631\u0648\u0648\u0627\u0644 \u0641\u0631\u0639\u06cc \u0631\u06cc\u0644\u0648\u06d2 \u062e\u0637'''}}}}) is one of several [[Railway lines in Pakistan|branch lines in Pakistan]], operated and maintained by [[Pakistan Railways]]. The line originally runs from [[Wazirabad Junction railway station|Wazirabad Junction station]] to [[Narowal Junction railway station|Narowal Junction station]]. The total length of this railway line is {{convert|105|km|mi|sp=us}}. There are 15 railway stations from Wazirabad Junction to Narowal Junction.<ref>{{cite book|title=Pakistan Railways Time & Fare Table 2015|publisher=National Book Foundation|location=Pakistan|pages=94\u201399|edition=October 2015|url=http://pakrail.com/images/musafir/musafirTT2015.pdf|accessdate=18 August 2016|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160818174648/http://pakrail.com/images/musafir/musafirTT2015.pdf|archivedate=18 August 2016|language=English, Urdu}}</ref>\n\n==History==\nThe Wazirabad\u2013Narowal Branch Line was built by the [[North Western State Railway]] in 1915 and originally named as the ''Sialkot\u2013Narowal Railway''.<ref>[https://archive.org/stream/BombayBarodaAndCentralIndiaRailwaySystem/Bombay_Baroda_And_Central_India_Railway_System#page/n127/mode/2up \" Administration Report on the Railways in India \u2013 corrected up to 31st March 1918\"; Superintendent of Government  Printing,  Calcutta;  page 119]; Retrieved 21 Dec 2015</ref>\n\n==Stations==\nThe railway stations on this railway line are:\n* [[Wazirabad Junction railway station|'''Wazirabad Junction''']]\n* [[Sodhra Kopra railway station|Sodhra Kopra]]\n* [[Begowala Ghartal railway Station|Begowala Ghartal]]\n* [[Sambrial railway station|Sambrial]]\n* [[Sahowala railway station|Sahowala]]\n* [[Ugoki railway station|Ugoki]]\n* [[Sialkot Junction railway station|'''Sialkot Junction''']]\n* [[Tasirabad Halt railway station|Tasirabad Halt]]\n* [[Gunna Kalan railway station|Gunna Kalan]]\n* [[Alhar railway station|Alhar]]\n* [[Chawinda railway station|Chawinda]]\n* [[Pasrur railway station|Pasrur]]\n* [[Qila Sobha Singh railway station|Qila Sobha Singh]]\n* [[Alipur Sayadan Sharif railway station|Alipur Sayadan Sharif]]\n* [[Domala railway station|Domala]]\n* [[Narowal Junction railway station|'''Narowal Junction''']]\n\n==See also==\n*[[Pakistan Railways]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Wazirabad\u2013Narowal Branch Line}}\n{{Railway lines in Pakistan}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Wazirabad-Narowal railway line}}\n[[Category:Railway stations on Wazirabad\u2013Narowal Branch Line]]\n[[Category:Railway lines opened in 1915]]\n[[Category:5 ft 6 in gauge railways in Pakistan]]\n\n\n{{Pakistan-rail-transport-stub}}\n", "name_user": "RailwayFan", "label": "safe", "comment": "brief railway history.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wazirabad%E2%80%93Narowal_Branch_Line"}
{"title_page": "Spartanburg Day School", "text_new": "{{Infobox School\n|name= Spartanburg Day School\n|image=\n|imagesize= \n| caption =Presnell, the high-school building\n|location= 1701 Skylyn Drive \n|city= [[Spartanburg]] \n|state= [[South Carolina]] \n|zipcode= 29307 \n|country= United States\n|grades= 2K\u201312\n|headmaster = Rachel S. Deems<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.spartanburgdayschool.org/about/our-leaders |title=Our Leaders: Welcome, from the Head of School |year=2018 |accessdate=10 April 2018}}</ref>\n|type= [[Private school|Private]], [[Independent School]] \n|enrollment= 450 \n|established= 1957\n|faculty= 100 \n|gender= [[Co-Educational]] \n|colors= Red and Blue {{colorbox|red}} {{colorbox|blue}}\n|mascot= Griffin \n|nickname= Griffins\n|conference= [[South Carolina Independent School Association]] (SCISA) \n|endowment= $19 million\n|newspaper= The Talon \n|accreditation= [[Southern Association of Colleges and Schools]]\n|information= phone: (864) 582-7539\nfax: (864) 582-7530\n|website=http://www.spartanburgdayschool.org\n}}\n\n'''Spartanburger Day School''' is an independent, college preparatory [[pre-kindergarten|2K]]-12 school, located in Spartanburg County, South Carolina, United States, in the Greenville-Spartanburg area. It consists of a lower school for [[pre-kindergarten|2K]]-4th graders, a middle school for 5th-8th graders, and an upper school for 9th-12th graders.\n\n== History ==\nSpartanburg Day School was established on September 12, 1957 at the Drayton Mill Community Building, with 35 students in 1st\u20135th grades. As more upper-level grades were needed, a new location for SDS was established on Skylyn Drive, where the school is currently located. In October 1962, the new campus was officially opened. The lower school did not move to the current campus until 1993.{{citation needed|date=July 2017}}\n\nWhen the families of foreign expatriates began moving to the Greenville-Spartanburg area in the 20th century, most of the children attended Spartanburg Country Day School.<ref name=Kanter>Kanter, Rosabeth Moss. ''World Class''. [[Simon & Schuster]], January 3, 1997. {{ISBN|0684825228}}, 9780684825229. p. [https://books.google.com/books?id=cz9wbkBrMF8C&pg=PA265 265].</ref>\n\n== Athletics ==\nEach student from grades 7 to 12 is required to participate in one athletic team each academic year. SDS offers [[cross country running|cross country]], [[volleyball]], [[soccer]], [[physical education]], [[tennis]], [[basketball]], [[swimming (sport)|swimming]], [[cheerleading]], [[baseball]], [[lacrosse]], [[golf]], and [[track and field]].<ref>[http://www.spartanburgdayschool.org/athletics/teams_and_schedules.asp List of athletic programs]</ref> The school does not deny students from participating in its athletic programs due to inexperience or ability.<ref>[http://www.spartanburgdayschool.org/athletics/overview.asp Overview of SDS athletics]</ref> SDS has enjoyed much athletic success in recent years, including back-to-back baseball state championships in 2001 and 2002, as well as state championship teams in men's and women's tennis.{{citation needed|date=July 2017}}\n\n== Events ==\n{{citations needed|date=July 2017}}\nSpartanburg Day School provides students with a number of after-school programs throughout the year.\n\n=== Fall Festival ===\nThe activities at the Fall Festival are aimed towards lower school students, although all students are welcome to attend. Games and prizes motivate the students to come. Juniors are required to attend Fall Festival because it is a main fundraiser for the Junior-Senior prom.{{citation needed|date=July 2017}}\n\n=== Special studies ===\nBeginning in 1996, one week out of every year in March, upper school students are able to \"engage in a non-traditional learning activity\". Examples of special studies activities include trips to [[Puerto Rico]], [[Italy]], and [[Toronto]], and working with [[Habitat for Humanity]]. Activities located on campus include Independent Women, The Art of Movies, and [[Photoshop]]. Each student is required to either attend a special studies activity or come up with their own.{{citation needed|date=July 2017}}\n\n== Bands ==\nSpartanburg Day School currently has five bands, all directed by Dick Barnes. He also teaches ballroom dance to the 6th grade and teaches the 5th grade to play the recorder. The bands are the Middle School Concert Band, the Middle School Honor Band, the Middle School Jazz Band, the Upper School Band, the Upper School Jazz Band. Several of these require an audition, but not all. \n\nThe bands have done consistently well at all-state festivals. The High school Jazz band has earned Superiors at the past seven state festivals. Recently, The Highschool Jass band and Concert band have won the grand champion awards at both the Orlando festival event and the Virginia Festival event competing against Hundreds of other schools from across the nation. On March 3, 2007, the Middle School Jazz Band earned a Superior at the State Jazz festival. This was the first time the Middle School had ever earned a Superior at any state festival. The SDS Middle School Honors Band was awarded the Outstanding Performance Award in the spring of 2007 after receiving enough Superiors at the state Solo and Ensemble festival. In 2009, all 6th-grade students signed up for Beginning Band, even though the course was completely optional.{{citation needed|date=May 2019}}\n\n== Seniors ==\nSeniors at Spartanburg Day School have special privileges, which include a special area that only they can enter, called the Senior Lounge. Seniors are also the only students who may leave the campus, and they are not required to attend their study halls. Senior Privileges can be revoked at any time, by any faculty member.{{citation needed|date=July 2017}}\n\n== School songs ==\n\n=== Alma mater ===\nWe with zeal pursue our studies<br />\nToward a happy mind fulfilled<br />\nRecognizing sound achievement<br />\nAs the rock on which we build.\n\nFinis Coronat Opus<br />\nThe end crowns the work<br />\nIs our steadfast rule.<br />\nFinis Coronat Opus<br />\nThe motto of the Spartanburg Day School.\n\nFor our goal we build a spirit<br />\nGreat in power and clear in form<br />\nBending not to moral whirlwind<br />\nStanding fast in every storm.\n\nFinis Coronat Opus<br />\nThe end crowns the work<br />\nIs our steadfast rule.<br />\nFinis Coronat Opus<br />\nThe motto of the Spartanburg Day School.<ref name=\"history\">http://www.spartanburgdayschool.org/about_sds/history.asp</ref>\n\n=== Fight song ===\nSDS is marching on<br />\nWe are proud and we are strong<br />\nLet us wave our colors red and blue<br />\nLet us cheer for students brave and true<br />\nWe will fight and we will win<br />\nNever ever giving in<br />\nNo matter where you go<br />\nYou will always know<br />\nOur SDS team is marching on!<ref name=\"history\"/>\n\n== Notable alumni ==\n* [[Zion Williamson]] (class of 2018), basketball player for the [[New Orleans Pelicans]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.espn.com/mens-college-basketball/story/_/id/26406892/the-education-zion-williamson|title=The education of Zion Williamson|last=|first=|date=|work=www.espn.com|access-date=April 12, 2019}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|1}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://www.spartanburgdayschool.org Spartanburg Day School website]\n* [https://maps.google.com/maps?f=q&hl=en&q=1701+Skylyn+Drive,+Spartanburg,+South+Carolina&sll=37.0625,-95.677068&sspn=47.751524,82.265625&layer=&ie=UTF8&z=16&ll=34.978903,-81.893206&spn=0.012149,0.027122&t=k&om=1 Satellite view from Google Maps]\n\n{{Coord|34.9765121|-81.8928816|display=title}}\n\n[[Category:Private high schools in South Carolina]]\n[[Category:Schools in Spartanburg County, South Carolina]]\n[[Category:Private middle schools in South Carolina]]\n[[Category:Private elementary schools in South Carolina]]\n[[Category:Educational institutions established in 1957]]\n[[Category:1957 establishments in South Carolina]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox School\n|name= Spartanburg Day School\n|image=\n|imagesize= \n| caption =Presnell, the high-school building\n|location= 1701 Skylyn Drive \n|city= [[Spartanburg]] \n|state= [[South Carolina]] \n|zipcode= 29307 \n|country= United States\n|grades= 2K\u201312\n|headmaster = Rachel S. Deems<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.spartanburgdayschool.org/about/our-leaders |title=Our Leaders: Welcome, from the Head of School |year=2018 |accessdate=10 April 2018}}</ref>\n|type= [[Private school|Private]], [[Independent School]] \n|enrollment= 450 \n|established= 1957\n|faculty= 100 \n|gender= [[Co-Educational]] \n|colors= Red and Blue {{colorbox|red}} {{colorbox|blue}}\n|mascot= Griffin \n|nickname= Griffins\n|conference= [[South Carolina Independent School Association]] (SCISA) \n|endowment= $19 million\n|newspaper= The Talon \n|accreditation= [[Southern Association of Colleges and Schools]]\n|information= phone: (864) 582-7539\nfax: (864) 582-7530\n|website=http://www.spartanburgdayschool.org\n}}\n\n'''Spartanburg Day School''' is an independent, college preparatory [[pre-kindergarten|2K]]-12 school, located in Spartanburg County, South Carolina, United States, in the Greenville-Spartanburg area. It consists of a lower school for [[pre-kindergarten|2K]]-4th graders, a middle school for 5th-8th graders, and an upper school for 9th-12th graders.\n\n== History ==\nSpartanburg Day School was established on September 12, 1957 at the Drayton Mill Community Building, with 35 students in 1st\u20135th grades. As more upper-level grades were needed, a new location for SDS was established on Skylyn Drive, where the school is currently located. In October 1962, the new campus was officially opened. The lower school did not move to the current campus until 1993.{{citation needed|date=July 2017}}\n\nWhen the families of foreign expatriates began moving to the Greenville-Spartanburg area in the 20th century, most of the children attended Spartanburg Country Day School.<ref name=Kanter>Kanter, Rosabeth Moss. ''World Class''. [[Simon & Schuster]], January 3, 1997. {{ISBN|0684825228}}, 9780684825229. p. [https://books.google.com/books?id=cz9wbkBrMF8C&pg=PA265 265].</ref>\n\n== Athletics ==\nEach student from grades 7 to 12 is required to participate in one athletic team each academic year. SDS offers [[cross country running|cross country]], [[volleyball]], [[soccer]], [[physical education]], [[tennis]], [[basketball]], [[swimming (sport)|swimming]], [[cheerleading]], [[baseball]], [[lacrosse]], [[golf]], and [[track and field]].<ref>[http://www.spartanburgdayschool.org/athletics/teams_and_schedules.asp List of athletic programs]</ref> The school does not deny students from participating in its athletic programs due to inexperience or ability.<ref>[http://www.spartanburgdayschool.org/athletics/overview.asp Overview of SDS athletics]</ref> SDS has enjoyed much athletic success in recent years, including back-to-back baseball state championships in 2001 and 2002, as well as state championship teams in men's and women's tennis.{{citation needed|date=July 2017}}\n\n== Events ==\n{{citations needed|date=July 2017}}\nSpartanburg Day School provides students with a number of after-school programs throughout the year.\n\n=== Fall Festival ===\nThe activities at the Fall Festival are aimed towards lower school students, although all students are welcome to attend. Games and prizes motivate the students to come. Juniors are required to attend Fall Festival because it is a main fundraiser for the Junior-Senior prom.{{citation needed|date=July 2017}}\n\n=== Special studies ===\nBeginning in 1996, one week out of every year in March, upper school students are able to \"engage in a non-traditional learning activity\". Examples of special studies activities include trips to [[Puerto Rico]], [[Italy]], and [[Toronto]], and working with [[Habitat for Humanity]]. Activities located on campus include Independent Women, The Ar