ductores de M\u00fasica de Espa\u00f1a|PROMUSICAE]])<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.promusicae.es/listas/semana/4170-%C3%81lbumes-semana-37-2019 |title=Top 100 Albumes \u2013 Semana 37: del 6 September 2019 al 12.9.2019 |publisher=[[Productores de M\u00fasica de Espa\u00f1a]] |language=Spanish |accessdate=September 18, 2019}}</ref>\n| 15\n|-\n{{album chart|Switzerland|16|artist=Soundtrack|album=Quentin Tarantino's Once Upon a Time in Hollywood|rowheader=true|accessdate=August 28, 2019}}\n|}\n\n=== Additional music ===\nOther songs in the film include \"[[The Letter (Box Tops song)|The Letter]]\" by [[Joe Cocker]], \"[[Summertime (George Gershwin song)|Summertime]]\" by [[Billy Stewart]], \"Victorville Blues\" by The Harley Hatcher Combo, \"Ready for Action\" by [[Syd Dale]], \"[[Funky Fanfare]]\" by [[Keith Mansfield]], \"[[The House That Jack Built (song)|The House That Jack Built]]\" by [[Aretha Franklin]], \"Time for Livin'\" by [[The Association]], \"[[I Can't Turn You Loose]]\" by [[Otis Redding]], \"[[Soul Serenade (King Curtis song)|Soul Serenade]]\" by [[Willie Mitchell (musician)|Willie Mitchell]], \"[[Out of Time (The Rolling Stones song)|Out of Time]]\" by [[the Rolling Stones]], \"[[Twelve Thirty (Young Girls Are Coming to the Canyon)]]\" by [[the Mamas and the Papas]], \"[[Snoopy vs. the Red Baron (song)|Snoopy vs. the Red Baron]]\" by [[The Royal Guardsmen]], \"Straight Shooter\" by the Mamas and the Papas, also performed by [[Samantha Robinson (American actress)|Samantha Robinson]] as [[Abigail Folger]], and \"[[The Green Door]]\" performed by [[Leonardo DiCaprio]] as Rick Dalton.<ref name=every-song>{{cite news |last=Moran |first=Sarah |url=https://screenrant.com/once-upon-time-hollywood-movie-soundtrack-songs/ |title=Every Song in Once Upon a Time in Hollywood |website=[[Screen Rant]] |access-date=August 25, 2019 |date=July 26, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190727133005/https://screenrant.com/once-upon-time-hollywood-movie-soundtrack-songs/ |archive-date=July 27, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=soundtrack/>\n\nMusic by [[Bernard Herrmann]] created for ''[[Torn Curtain]]'' is used in the Spahn Ranch scene.<ref>{{cite web |last=Chow |first=Andrew R. |url=https://time.com/5637336/once-upon-a-time-in-hollywood-soundtrack/ |title=Breaking Down the Hidden Meanings and Historical References in the Once Upon a Time... in Hollywood Soundtrack |website=Time |access-date=September 2, 2019 |date=July 29, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190731021716/https://time.com/5637336/once-upon-a-time-in-hollywood-soundtrack/ |archive-date=July 31, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref> Herrman's music from that film included in ''Once Upon a Time in Hollywood'' is \"The Killing\", and \"The Radiogram\". Other music of his used is \"The Rocks\", and \"The Return\" (from ''[[Have Gun Will Travel]]''). Also used are the themes from ''[[Hell River]]'' by Vojislav Borisavljevic, ''[[Against a Crooked Sky]]'' by Alexis de Azevedo, ''[[:it: Un uomo chiamato Apocalisse Joe|Apocalypse Joe]]'' by [[Bruno Nicolai]], and ''[[Mannix]]'' by [[Lalo Schifrin]]. Also, \"Paxton Quigley's Had the Course\" (from ''[[Three in the Attic]]''), \"The Bed\" by [[Ennio Morricone]] (from ''[[Danger: Diabolik]]''), \"Ecce Homo\" (from ''[[:it: Sartana non perdona|Sartana Does Not Forgive]]'') and \"Mexican Western\" (from ''[[Any Gun Can Play]]'') by [[Francesco De Masi]], \"Cooler\" by [[Elmer Bernstein]] (from ''[[The Great Escape (film)|The Great Escape]]''), \"Freya Bangs\", \"Freya\", \"Karate Dance\", and \"TV Screen\" (from ''[[The Wrecking Crew (1968 film)|The Wrecking Crew]]''), \"Theme from ''[[It's Happening]]''\" by [[Paul Revere & the Raiders]], \"Dalton Gang Ride Entrance\" performed by Tom Slocum, John Bird, and the Cattle Annie Band (from ''[[Cattle Annie and Little Britches]]''), the \"Batman Theme\" (from ''[[Batman (TV series)|Batman]])'', the \"FBI Theme and Score Cues\" (from ''[[The F.B.I. (TV series)|The F.B.I.]]''), and \"Miss Lilly Langtry\" and \"Judge Roy Bean's Theme\" by [[Maurice Jarre]] (from ''[[The Life and Times of Judge Roy Bean]]'').<ref name=soundtrack>{{cite web |last=Gorber |first=Jason |url=https://www.slashfilm.com/once-upon-a-time-in-hollywood-soundtrack-deep-dive/3/ |title=How the 'Once Upon a Time in Hollywood' Soundtrack Helps Quentin Tarantino Shape His Version of 1969 Los Angeles |website=[[/Film]] |access-date=September 4, 2019 |date=August 1, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190802231046/https://www.slashfilm.com/once-upon-a-time-in-hollywood-soundtrack-deep-dive/3/ |archive-date=August 2, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n== Release ==\n[[File:Tarantino and Robbie at 2019 Cannes (cropped).jpg|thumb|upright=0.8|Tarantino and Robbie at the [[2019 Cannes Film Festival]]]]\n''Once Upon a Time in Hollywood'' premiered at the [[Cannes Film Festival]] on May 21, 2019.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://variety.com/2019/film/news/once-upon-a-time-in-hollywood-cannes-competition-quentin-tarantino-1203201142/ |title='Once Upon a Time in Hollywood' Joins Cannes' Competition Roster |date=May 2, 2019 |website=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] |accessdate=May 2, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190502132152/https://variety.com/2019/film/news/once-upon-a-time-in-hollywood-cannes-competition-quentin-tarantino-1203201142/|archive-date=May 2, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.festival-cannes.com/en/press/press-articles/communique/articles/the-screenings-guide-2019 |title=The Screenings Guide 2019 |date=May 9, 2019 |website=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] |accessdate=May 9, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190509101313/https://www.festival-cannes.com/en/press/press-articles/communique/articles/the-screenings-guide-2019|archive-date=May 9, 2019}}</ref> It was released theatrically in the United States on July 26, 2019 by [[Sony Pictures Releasing]] under its [[Columbia Pictures]] label.<ref>{{cite web |last1=McClintock |first1=Pamela |title=Quentin Tarantino's Manson Movie Shifts Off Sharon Tate Murder Anniversary Date |url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/quentin-tarantinos-manson-movie-will-hit-theaters-two-weeks-early-1128206 |website=[[The Hollywood Reporter]] |accessdate=July 18, 2018 |date=July 18, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180719024659/https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/quentin-tarantinos-manson-movie-will-hit-theaters-two-weeks-early-1128206|archive-date=July 19, 2018}}</ref> The film was originally scheduled for release on August 9 to coincide with the 50th anniversary of the [[Tate\u2013LaBianca murders]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://deadline.com/2017/12/sony-dates-quentin-tarantinos-9-for-1202218496/ |title=Quentin Tarantino's Manson Movie Set For Release on 50th Anniversary of Sharon Tate's Death |last=D'Alessandro |first=Anthony |date=December 1, 2017 |website=[[Deadline Hollywood]] |accessdate=June 18, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180618175501/https://deadline.com/2017/12/sony-dates-quentin-tarantinos-9-for-1202218496/|archive-date=June 18, 2018}}</ref>\n\nA [[teaser campaign|teaser trailer]] was released on March 20, 2019, featuring 1960s music by [[the Mamas and the Papas]] (\"Straight Shooter\") and by [[Los Bravos]] (\"[[Bring a Little Lovin']]\").<ref>{{cite news |last1=Singer |first1=Matt |title=What Are the Songs in the Once Upon a Time in Hollywood Trailer? |url=https://screencrush.com/what-are-the-songs-in-the-once-upon-a-time-in-hollywood-trailer/ |accessdate=March 21, 2019 |website=[[Townsquare Media#Web publications and services|ScreenCrush]] |date=March 20, 2019 |language=en |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190321175233/https://screencrush.com/what-are-the-songs-in-the-once-upon-a-time-in-hollywood-trailer/ |archive-date=March 21, 2019}}</ref> The official trailer was released on May 21, 2019 featuring the songs \"[[Good Thing (Paul Revere & The Raiders song)|Good Thing]]\" by [[Paul Revere & the Raiders]], and \"[[Brother Love's Travelling Salvation Show (song)|Brother Love's Travelling Salvation Show]]\" by [[Neil Diamond]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.tunefind.com/movie/once-upon-a-time-in-hollywood-2019 |title=Songs and music featured in Once Upon a Time in Hollywood |last= |first= |date=July 2019 |website=[[Tunefind]] |access-date= |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190724142756/https://www.tunefind.com/movie/once-upon-a-time-in-hollywood-2019 |archive-date=July 24, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref> The studio spent around $110 million marketing the film.<ref name=opening/>\n\nAn extended cut of the film featuring four additional scenes was released in theaters on October 25, 2019.<ref name=extended-cut>{{cite news| url=https://www.rollingstone.com/movies/movie-news/quentin-tarantino-once-upon-a-time-in-hollywood-rerelease-new-footage-902715/| title=Quentin Tarantino Re-Releasing \"Once Upon a Time in Hollywood\" With Unseen Footage| last=Reed| first=Ryan| website=RollingStone| access-date=October 24, 2019| date=October 23, 2019| url-status=live| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191024011955/https://www.rollingstone.com/movies/movie-news/quentin-tarantino-once-upon-a-time-in-hollywood-rerelease-new-footage-902715/| archive-date=October 24, 2019}}</ref>\n\n=== Home media ===\nThe film was released on digital and [[Movies Anywhere]] on November 22, 2019, and on [[Blu-ray]], [[Ultra HD Blu-ray|4K Ultra HD]], and [[DVD-Video|DVD]] on December 10. The 4K version is available as a regular version and collector's edition.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Evangelista |first1=Chris |title='Once Upon a Time in Hollywood' Blu-ray Releasing in December With Special Collector's Edition |url=https://www.slashfilm.com/once-upon-a-time-in-hollywood-blu-ray/ |accessdate=October 28, 2019 |work=[[/Film]] |date=October 28, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191029003843/https://www.slashfilm.com/once-upon-a-time-in-hollywood-blu-ray/ |archive-date=October 29, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n== Reception ==\n=== Box office ===\n{{As of|2020|2|13|df=US}}, ''Once Upon a Time in Hollywood'' has grossed $142.5 million in the United States and Canada, and $231.8 million in other territories, for a worldwide total of $374.3 million.<ref name=\"BOM\"/> By some estimates, the film needed to gross around $250 million worldwide in order to [[break-even]],<ref>{{cite web |last=Lee |first=Chris |url=https://www.vulture.com/2019/08/once-upon-a-time-in-hollywood-box-office-bet-pays-off.html |title=The Bet on ''Once Upon a Time in Hollywood'' Is Paying Off |website=[[New York (magazine)#Digital expansion and blogs|Vulture]] |access-date=September 6, 2019 |date=August 5, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190805145753/https://www.vulture.com/2019/08/once-upon-a-time-in-hollywood-box-office-bet-pays-off.html |archive-date=August 5, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref> with others estimating it would need to make $400 million in order to turn a profit.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/heat-vision/once-a-time-hollywood-debut-doesnt-guarantee-a-happy-ending-1227512 |title=Box Office: Why 'Once Upon a Time in Hollywood's' $40M Debut Doesn't Guarantee a Fairy Tale Ending |date=July 29, 2019 |first=Pamela|last= McClintock |work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]] |accessdate=August 28, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190809094907/https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/heat-vision/once-a-time-hollywood-debut-doesnt-guarantee-a-happy-ending-1227512 |archive-date=August 9, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn the United States and Canada, the film was projected to gross $30\u201340 million from 3,659 theaters in its opening weekend, with some projections having it as high as $50 million or as low as $25 million.<ref name=EarlyProjections>{{Cite web |url=https://deadline.com/2019/07/quentin-tarantinos-once-upon-a-time-in-hollywood-eyes-30m-opening-1202641601/ |title=Quentin Tarantino's 'Once Upon A Time In Hollywood' Eyes $30M Opening |last=D'Alessandro |first=Anthony |website=[[Deadline Hollywood]] |date=July 3, 2019 |access-date=July 3, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190703161646/https://deadline.com/2019/07/quentin-tarantinos-once-upon-a-time-in-hollywood-eyes-30m-opening-1202641601/ |archive-date=July 3, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.thewrap.com/once-upon-a-time-in-hollywood-quentin-tarantino-box-office/ |title=Once Upon a Time in Hollywood': Will Sony's Bet on Quentin Tarantino Pay Off? |last=Fuster |first=Jeremy |website=[[TheWrap]] |date=July 23, 2019 |access-date=July 24, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190724035722/https://www.thewrap.com/once-upon-a-time-in-hollywood-quentin-tarantino-box-office/ |archive-date=July 24, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref> The week of its release, [[Fandango (company)|Fandango]] reported the film was the highest pre-seller of any Tarantino film.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://deadline.com/2019/07/once-upon-a-time-in-hollywood-quentin-tarantino-biggest-fandango-preseller-1202652829/ |title='Once Upon A Time In Hollywood' Is Quentin Tarantino's Biggest Preseller On Fandango |last=D'Alessandro |first=Anthony |website=[[Deadline Hollywood]] |date=July 24, 2019 |access-date=July 24, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190724202322/https://deadline.com/2019/07/once-upon-a-time-in-hollywood-quentin-tarantino-biggest-fandango-preseller-1202652829/ |archive-date=July 24, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref> The film made $16.9 million on its first day, including $5.8 million from Thursday night previews (the highest total of Tarantino's career). It went on to debut to $41.1 million, finishing second behind holdover ''[[The Lion King (2019 film)|The Lion King]]'' and marking Tarantino's largest opening. [[Comscore]] reported that 47% of audience members went to see the film because of who the director was (compared to the typical 7%) and 37% went because of the cast (compared to normally 18%).<ref name=opening>{{Cite web |url=https://deadline.com/2019/07/once-upon-a-time-in-hollywood-quentin-tarantino-box-office-lion-king-weekend-1202654606/ |title=Hooray For 'Hollywood': Quentin Tarantino Sees His Biggest B.O. Opening Of All-Time With $40M+ As 'Lion King' Still Lords With $76M+ \u2013 Sunday Update |last=D'Alessandro |first=Anthony |website=[[Deadline Hollywood]] |date=July 27, 2019 |access-date=July 27, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190726232213/https://deadline.com/2019/07/once-upon-a-time-in-hollywood-quentin-tarantino-box-office-lion-king-weekend-1202654606/ |archive-date=July 26, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref> The film grossed $20 million in its second weekend, representing a \"nice\" drop of just 51% and finishing third, and then made $11.6 million and $7.6 million the subsequent weekends.<ref>{{cite news |last1=D'Alessandro |first1=Anthony |title='Hobbs & Shaw' West Coast Business Driving Pic To $60M, But Looks To Overseas For More Muscle |url=https://deadline.com/2019/08/hobbs-shaw-targeting-4-5m-thursday-night-early-b-o-read-1202659422/ |accessdate=August 4, 2019 |website=[[Deadline Hollywood]] |date=August 4, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190803004918/https://deadline.com/2019/08/hobbs-shaw-targeting-4-5m-thursday-night-early-b-o-read-1202659422/ |archive-date=August 3, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://deadline.com/2019/08/dora-and-the-lost-city-of-gold-hobbs-shaw-the-kitchen-box-office-weekend-1202665153/ |title='Hobbs' Hauls $25M; 'Scary Stories' Frighten 'Dora'; 'Kitchen' Sinks Melissa McCarthy & Tiffany Haddish To Career B.O. Lows \u2013 Saturday AM Update |last=D'Alessandro |first=Anthony |website=[[Deadline Hollywood]] |date=August 11, 2019 |access-date=August 11, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190810145835/https://deadline.com/2019/08/dora-and-the-lost-city-of-gold-hobbs-shaw-the-kitchen-box-office-weekend-1202665153/ |archive-date=August 10, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://deadline.com/2019/08/good-boys-hobbs-shaw-47-meters-down-uncaged-scary-stories-weekend-box-office-1202669605/ |title=How Universal Is Reviving The R-Rated Comedy & Making 'Good Boys' Great At The B.O. With A $21M Opening |last=D'Alessandro |first=Anthony |website=[[Deadline Hollywood]] |date=August 18, 2019 |access-date=August 18, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190816181043/https://deadline.com/2019/08/good-boys-hobbs-shaw-47-meters-down-uncaged-scary-stories-weekend-box-office-1202669605/ |archive-date=August 16, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref> In its fourth weekend the film made $5 million, bringing its running domestic total to $123.1 million, becoming the second-highest of Tarantino's career behind ''[[Django Unchained]]''.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://deadline.com/2019/08/ready-or-not-angel-has-fallen-good-boys-box-office-weekend-1202701545/ |title='Angel Has Fallen' Still Ascending Close To 'London' With $20M; Tarantino's 'Hollywood' Beating 'Basterds' \u2013 Saturday AM B.O. |last=D'Alessandro |first=Anthony |website=[[Deadline Hollywood]] |date=August 25, 2019 |access-date=August 28, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190822231242/https://deadline.com/2019/08/ready-or-not-angel-has-fallen-good-boys-box-office-weekend-1202701545/ |archive-date=August 22, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref> In its ninth weekend, its global total earnings reached $329.4 million, surpassing ''[[Inglourious Basterds]]'' to become Tarantino's second-highest global grosser behind ''Django Unchained''.<ref>{{cite news |last=Mendelson |first=Scott |url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/scottmendelson/2019/09/15/box-office-quentin-tarantino-leonardo-dicaprio-brad-pitt-margot-robbie-dwayne-johnson-jason-statham-john-wick-keanu-reeves-peanut-butter-falcon-shia-labeouf-dakota-johnson-farwell-awkwafina-lion-king-rogue-one-dark-knight/ |title=Box Office: 'Hollywood' Tops 'Basterds' As 'Lion King' Nears 'Dark Knight' And 'Hobbs & Shaw' Nears 'John Wick 3' |website=[[Forbes]] |access-date=September 15, 2019 |date=September 15, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190916044551/https://www.forbes.com/sites/scottmendelson/2019/09/15/box-office-quentin-tarantino-leonardo-dicaprio-brad-pitt-margot-robbie-dwayne-johnson-jason-statham-john-wick-keanu-reeves-peanut-butter-falcon-shia-labeouf-dakota-johnson-farwell-awkwafina-lion-king-rogue-one-dark-knight/ |archive-date=September 16, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n=== Critical response ===\nOn [[Rotten Tomatoes]], the film holds an approval rating of 85% based on 515 reviews, with an [[Weighted arithmetic mean|average rating]] of 7.83/10. The site's critical consensus reads, \"Thrillingly unrestrained yet solidly crafted, ''Once Upon a Time in Hollywood'' tempers Tarantino's provocative impulses with the clarity of a mature filmmaker's vision.\"<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/once_upon_a_time_in_hollywood |title=Once Upon a Time in Hollywood (2019) |website=[[Rotten Tomatoes]] |accessdate=December 12, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190330050307/https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/once_upon_a_time_in_hollywood |archive-date=March 30, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref> [[Metacritic]] assigned the film a [[weighted average]] score of 83 out of 100, based on 61 critics, indicating \"universal acclaim.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.metacritic.com/movie/once-upon-a-time-in-hollywood |title=Once Upon a Time in Hollywood Reviews |website=[[Metacritic]] |accessdate=September 28, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190722083158/https://www.metacritic.com/movie/once-upon-a-time-in-hollywood |archive-date=July 22, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> Audiences polled by [[CinemaScore]] gave it an average grade of \"B\" on an A+ to F scale, while those at [[PostTrak]] gave it an average of 4 out of 5 stars and a 58% \"definite recommend.\"<ref name=\"opening\"/>\n\n''[[The Hollywood Reporter]]'' said critics had \"an overall positive view,\" with some calling it \"Tarantino's love letter to '60s L.A.,\" praising its cast and setting, while others were \"divided on its ending.\"<ref name=\"beresford\">{{cite web |url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/heat-vision/once-a-time-hollywood-reviews-what-critics-are-saying-1212670 |first1=Trilby |last1=Beresford |first2=Katie |last2=Kilkenny |title='Once Upon a Time in Hollywood': What the Critics Are Saying |website=[[The Hollywood Reporter]] |date=May 21, 2019 |accessdate=May 21, 2019}}</ref> ReelViews' [[James Berardinelli]] awarded the film 3.5 stars out of 4, saying it was \"made by a movie-lover for movie-lovers. And even those who don't qualify may still enjoy the hell out of it.\"<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.reelviews.net/reelviews/once-upon-a-time-in-hollywood |title=Once Upon a Time in Hollywood (United States, 2019) |first=James |last=Berardinelli |website=reelviews.com |date=July 24, 2019 |access-date=August 18, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190818104043/http://www.reelviews.net/reelviews/once-upon-a-time-in-hollywood |archive-date=August 18, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref> [[RogerEbert.com]]'s Brian Tallerico gave it four out of four stars, calling it \"layered and ambitious, the product of a confident filmmaker working with collaborators completely in tune with his vision\".<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.rogerebert.com/reviews/once-upon-a-time-in--hollywood-2019 |title=Once Upon a Time ... in Hollywood Movie Review (2019) |last=Tallerico |first=Brian |work=[[RogerEbert.com]] |date=July 23, 2019 |accessdate=August 19, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190814182022/https://www.rogerebert.com/reviews/once-upon-a-time-in--hollywood-2019 |archive-date=August 14, 2019 |url-status=live}} {{Rating|4|4}}</ref> The ''[[Chicago Sun-Times]]'', [[Richard Roeper]] described it as \"a brilliant and sometimes outrageously fantastic mash-up of real-life events and characters with pure fiction,\" giving it full marks.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://chicago.suntimes.com/2019/7/22/20706094/once-upon-time-hollywood-review-movie-quentin-tarantino-brad-pitt-leonardo-dicaprio-richard-roeper |title='Once Upon a Time in Hollywood' review: Quentin Tarantino's colorful snapshot of an era |first=Richard |last=Roeper |author-link=Richard Roeper |work=[[Chicago Sun-Times]] |date=July 22, 2019 |accessdate=September 3, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190904035133/https://chicago.suntimes.com/2019/7/22/20706094/once-upon-time-hollywood-review-movie-quentin-tarantino-brad-pitt-leonardo-dicaprio-richard-roeper |archive-date=September 4, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref> Writing for ''[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]'', [[Owen Gleiberman]] called it a \"heady engrossing collage of a film\u2014but not, in the end, a masterpiece.\"<ref>{{cite news |url=https://variety.com/2019/film/reviews/once-upon-a-time-in-hollywood-review-quentin-tarantino-brad-pitt-leonardo-dicaprio-cannes-film-1203222012/ |title=Cannes Film Review: 'Once Upon a Time...in Hollywood' |first=Owen |last=Gleiberman |date=May 21, 2019 |access-date=July 4, 2019 |magazine=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] |publisher=[[Penske Business Media, LLC.]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190614092258/https://variety.com/2019/film/reviews/once-upon-a-time-in-hollywood-review-quentin-tarantino-brad-pitt-leonardo-dicaprio-cannes-film-1203222012/ |archive-date=June 14, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref> [[Peter Bradshaw]] of ''[[The Guardian]]'' gave it five out of five stars, praising Pitt and DiCaprio's performances and calling it \"Tarantino's dazzling LA redemption song.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/2019/may/21/once-upon-a-time-in-hollywood-review-tarantino-dazzling-dicaprio-pitt |title=Once Upon a Time ... in Hollywood review \u2013 Tarantino's dazzling LA redemption song |first=Peter |last=Bradshaw |website=[[The Guardian]] |date=May 21, 2019 |accessdate=July 4, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190703222104/https://www.theguardian.com/film/2019/may/21/once-upon-a-time-in-hollywood-review-tarantino-dazzling-dicaprio-pitt |archive-date=July 3, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref> Steve Pond of ''[[TheWrap]]'' said: \"Big, brash, ridiculous, too long, and in the end invigorating, the film is a grand playground for its director to fetishize old pop culture and bring his gleeful perversity to the craft of moviemaking.\"<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.thewrap.com/once-upon-a-time-in-hollywood-film-review-a-contemplative-quentin-tarantino-still-blows-the-roof-off-cannes/ |title='Once Upon a Time ... in Hollywood' Film Review: A Contemplative Quentin Tarantino Still Blows the Roof Off Cannes |last=Pond |first=Steve |website=[[TheWrap]] |date=May 21, 2019 |accessdate=July 4, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190704173107/https://www.thewrap.com/once-upon-a-time-in-hollywood-film-review-a-contemplative-quentin-tarantino-still-blows-the-roof-off-cannes/ |archive-date=July 4, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref> [[Peter Travers]] of ''[[Rolling Stone]]'' awarded the film 4.5 out of 5 stars, remarking that \"All the actors, in roles large and small, bring their A games to the film. Two hours and 40 minutes can feel long for some. I wouldn't change a frame.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/movies/movie-reviews/once-upon-a-time-in-hollywood-movie-review-quentin-tarantino-861778/ |title='Once Upon a Time in Hollywood' Review: Tarantino's Violent Tinseltown Valentine |authorlink=Peter Travers |last=Travers |first=Peter |work=[[Rolling Stone]] |date=July 22, 2019 |accessdate=September 10, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190907183059/https://www.rollingstone.com/movies/movie-reviews/once-upon-a-time-in-hollywood-movie-review-quentin-tarantino-861778/ |archive-date=September 7, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nKatie Rife of ''[[The A.V. Club]]'' gave it a B+, calling it Tarantino's \"wistful midlife crisis movie.\"<ref name=\"avc\">{{Cite web |url=https://film.avclub.com/once-upon-a-time-in-hollywood-is-quentin-tarantino-s-1836636382 |title='Once Upon a Time...In Hollywood' Is Quentin Tarantino's Wistful Midlife Crisis Movie |last=Rife |first=Katie |date=July 24, 2019 |accessdate=July 24, 2019 |website=[[The A.V. Club]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190724151612/https://film.avclub.com/once-upon-a-time-in-hollywood-is-quentin-tarantino-s-1836636382 |archive-date=July 24, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref> [[Richard Brody]] of ''[[The New Yorker]]'' called it an \"obscenely regressive vision of the sixties\" that \"celebrates white-male stardom (and behind-the-scenes command) at the expense of everyone else.\"<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.newyorker.com/culture/the-front-row/review-quentin-tarantinos-obscenely-regressive-vision-of-the-sixties-in-once-upon-a-time-in-hollywood |title=Review: Quentin Tarantino's Obscenely Regressive Vision of the Sixties in 'Once Upon a Time . . . in Hollywood' |last=Brody |first=Richard |date=July 27, 2019 |website=[[The New Yorker]] |access-date=August 17, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190816141803/https://www.newyorker.com/culture/the-front-row/review-quentin-tarantinos-obscenely-regressive-vision-of-the-sixties-in-once-upon-a-time-in-hollywood |archive-date=August 16, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref> In [[Little White Lies (magazine)|''Little White Lies'']], [[Christopher Hooton]] described it as \"occasionally tedious\" but \"constantly awe-inspiring,\" noting it did not seem to be a \"love letter to Hollywood\" but an \"obituary for a moment in culture that looks unlikely to ever be resurrected.\"<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://lwlies.com/articles/once-upon-a-time-in-hollywood-quentin-tarantino-love-letter-obituary/ |title=Once Upon a Time in Hollywood isn't a love letter, it's an obituary |last=Hooton |first=Christopher |date=August 26, 2019 |website=[[Little White Lies (magazine)|Little White Lies]] |access-date= |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190826112553/https://lwlies.com/articles/once-upon-a-time-in-hollywood-quentin-tarantino-love-letter-obituary/ |archive-date=August 26, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nThe film also garnered moral and theological praise. The Los Angeles Catholic Bishop [[Robert Barron]] praised the character of Cliff Booth as embodying the four [[cardinal virtues]],<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.wordonfire.org/resources/video/bishop-barron-on-once-upon-a-time-in-hollywood/24840/|title=Bishop Barron on \u201cOnce Upon A Time In Hollywood\u201d |last=Barron |first=Robert |date=August 8, 2019 |website=Wordonfire.org}}</ref> while the theologian [[David Bentley Hart]] wrote that the film \"exhibit[s] a genuine ethical pathos, one that actually brought tears to my eyes\" for its portrayal of \"cosmic justice.\" Specifically, Hart praised the revisionism when \"Tarantino's version of the story unexpectedly veered away into some other, dreamlike, better world, where the monsters inadvertently passed through the wrong door and met the end they deserved\" that \"gave glorious expression to a perfectly righteous rage\" in \"some other order of reality, if only an imaginary one, where ethereal sweetness had survived and horror had perished.\"<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/08/06/opinion/quentin-tarantino.html|title=Quentin Tarantino's Cosmic Justice|last=Hart |first=David Bentley |date=August 6, 2019 |website=[[New York Times]]}}</ref>\n\n=== Accolades ===\n{{Main|List of accolades received by Once Upon a Time in Hollywood}}\nThe film premiered at the [[2019 Cannes Film Festival]] where it won the [[Palm Dog Award]] and was nominated for the [[Palme d'Or]].<ref>{{cite web |last=Sharf |first=Zack |url=https://www.indiewire.com/2019/05/2019-cannes-winners-palme-dor-1202144785/ |title=Cannes 2019 Full Winners List: Bong Joon-ho Wins Palme d'Or for \"Parasite\" |website=indiewire |access-date=September 1, 2019 |date=May 25, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190604171148/https://www.indiewire.com/2019/05/2019-cannes-winners-palme-dor-1202144785/ |archive-date=June 4, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last=Utichi |first=Joe |url=https://deadline.com/2019/05/quentin-tarantino-wins-palm-dog-award-cannes-1202621869/ |title=Quentin Tarantino Accepts Palm Dog Award For Best Cannes Canine Performance In 'Once Upon A Time In Hollywood' |work=[[Deadline Hollywood]] |date=May 24, 2019 |access-date=August 20, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190823203020/https://deadline.com/2019/05/quentin-tarantino-wins-palm-dog-award-cannes-1202621869/ |archive-date=August 23, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref> The film received 10 nominations at the [[92nd Academy Awards]], including [[Academy Award for Best Picture|Best Picture]], [[Academy Award for Best Actor|Best Actor]], [[Academy Award for Best Supporting Actor|Best Supporting Actor]], and [[Academy Award for Best Director|Best Director]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.gq.com/story/academy-awards-oscar-nominations-2020-full-list|title=Oscar Nominations Are Here, and Yes, There Are Snubs|last=Grebey|first=James|website=[[GQ]]|language=en|access-date=2020-01-13|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200113190408/https://www.gq.com/story/academy-awards-oscar-nominations-2020-full-list|archive-date=January 13, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> It received five nominations at the [[77th Golden Globe Awards]], winning for [[Golden Globe Award for Best Motion Picture \u2013 Musical or Comedy|Best Motion Picture \u2013 Musical or Comedy]], [[Golden Globe Award for Best Screenplay|Best Screenplay]] for Quentin Tarantino, and [[Golden Globe Award for Best Supporting Actor \u2013 Motion Picture|Best Supporting Actor \u2013 Motion Picture]] for Brad Pitt.<ref name=\"GoldenGlobeAwards\">{{cite web |url=https://variety.com/2019/film/news/2020-golden-globes-nominations-list-nominees-1203426905/ |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20191209155146/https://variety.com/2019/film/news/2020-golden-globes-nominations-list-nominees-1203426905/ |title=Golden Globes 2020: The Complete Nominations List |website=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] |date=December 9, 2019 |accessdate=December 9, 2019 |archivedate=December 9, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/films/news/golden-globes-winners-2020-list-best-actor-actress-picture-awards-a9271126.html|title=Golden Globes 2020 winners: The full list|last=Stolworthy|first=Jacob|website=[[The Independent]]|date=January 6, 2020|accessdate=January 6, 2020}}</ref> It received twelve nominations at the [[25th Critics' Choice Awards]], including [[Critics' Choice Movie Award for Best Picture|Best Picture]], [[Critics' Choice Movie Award for Best Director|Best Director]] for Tarantino, [[Critics' Choice Movie Award for Best Actor|Best Actor]] for Leonardo DiCaprio, and [[Critics' Choice Movie Award for Best Supporting Actor|Best Supporting Actor]] for Pitt.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2019/12/critics-choice-nominations-film-tv-nominees-list-1202803785/|title='The Irishman', 'Once Upon A Time In Hollywood' Lead Critics' Choice Nominations; Netflix Dominates With 61 Noms in Movies And TV|first1=Pete|last1=Hammond|work=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|date=December 8, 2019|access-date=December 9, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191208185645/https://deadline.com/2019/12/critics-choice-nominations-film-tv-nominees-list-1202803785/|archive-date=December 8, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> DiCaprio and Pitt also received nominations at the [[26th Screen Actors Guild Awards]] where it was also nominated for [[Screen Actors Guild Award for Outstanding Performance by a Cast in a Motion Picture|Outstanding Performance by a Cast in a Motion Picture]] and [[Screen Actors Guild Award for Outstanding Performance by a Stunt Ensemble in a Motion Picture|Outstanding Performance by a Stunt Ensemble in a Motion Picture]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.sagawards.org/media/news/releases/nominations-announced-26th-annual-screen-actors-guild-awards-%C2%AE |publisher=[[Screen Actors Guild Awards]]|title=NOMINATIONS ANNOUNCED FOR THE 26TH ANNUAL SCREEN ACTORS GUILD AWARDS |date=December 11, 2019 |accessdate=December 11, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191212024926/https://www.sagawards.org/media/news/releases/nominations-announced-26th-annual-screen-actors-guild-awards-%C2%AE |archive-date=December 12, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> The [[National Board of Review]] included the film as one of the [[National Board of Review Awards 2019#Top 10 Films|top 10 films of the year]] and awarded Tarantino [[National Board of Review Award for Best Director|Best Director]] and Pitt [[National Board of Review Award for Best Supporting Actor|Best Supporting Actor]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.indiewire.com/2019/12/national-board-of-review-2019-winners-irishman-1202193897/|title=National Board of Review 2019: 'The Irishman' Wins Best Film, Adam Sandler Named Best Actor|publisher=[[IndieWire]]|first1=Zack|last1=Sharf|first2=Zack|last2=Sharf|date=December 3, 2019|access-date=December 4, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191203194830/https://www.indiewire.com/2019/12/national-board-of-review-2019-winners-irishman-1202193897/|archive-date=December 3, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> The [[American Film Institute]] included it as one of the [[American Film Institute Awards 2019#Top 10 Films|top 10 films of 2019]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nextbestpicture.com/latest/the-afi-top-10-films-of-2019/|title=The AFI Top 10 Films of 2019|first1=Matt|last1=Neglia|publisher=[[American Film Institute]]|date=December 4, 2019|access-date=December 4, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191204233746/https://www.nextbestpicture.com/latest/the-afi-top-10-films-of-2019|archive-date=December 4, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n=== Top-ten lists ===\n\nThe film appeared on many critics' year-end top-ten lists, among them: \n{{div col}}\n* 1st{{snd}} [[James Berardinelli]] \u2013 ReelViews<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.reelviews.net/reelthoughts/reelthought_1577637046|title=Rewinding 2019: The Year in Review|first=James|last=Berardinelli|website=Reelviews Movie Reviews}}</ref>\n* 1st{{snd}} Bill Desowitz \u2013 [[IndieWire]]<ref name=\"auto1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.indiewire.com/feature/best-films-2019-indiewire-staff-1202198437/|title=The Best Films of 2019, According to IndieWire's Staff|publisher=[[IndieWire]]| date=December 23, 2019}}</ref>\n* 1st{{snd}}  Alison Willmore \u2013 ''[[New York (magazine)|New York]]''<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.vulture.com/article/best-movies-2019.html|title=The Best Movies of 2019|first1=David|last1=Edelstein|first2=Alison|last2=Willmore|first3=Bilge| last3=Ebiri|date=December 2, 2019|website=[[New York (magazine)#Digital expansion and blogs|Vulture]]}}</ref>\n* 1st{{snd}} Anne Thompson \u2013 IndieWire<ref name=\"auto1\"/>\n* 1st{{snd}} Christian Blauvelt \u2013 IndieWire<ref name=\"auto1\"/>\n* 1st{{snd}} Justin Kroll \u2013 ''[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]''<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://twitter.com/krolljvar/status/1209247505524772864|title=And finally my top ten of 2019: 10. Ford v Ferrari 9. May They Never Grow Old 8. 1917 7. Marriage Story 6. Waves 5. Parasite 4. Uncut Gems 3. The Irishman 2. Joker 1. Once Upon a Time...in Hollywood|first=Justin|last=Kroll|date=December 23, 2019}}</ref>\n* 1st{{snd}} Brian Tallerico \u2013 [[RogerEbert.com]]<ref name=\"auto4\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.rogerebert.com/balder-and-dash/the-individual-top-tens-of-2019|title=The Individual Top Tens of 2019 &#124; Balder and Dash &#124; Roger Ebert|website=www.rogerebert.com}}</ref>\n* 1st{{snd}} Jake Coyle \u2013 [[Associated Press]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://apnews.com/0ec356ee3fa4dcdd71683d966cb4f5ba|title='Once Upon a Time,' 'Portrait' top AP's 2019 best films list|date=December 5, 2019|website=[[Associated Press|AP News]]}}</ref>\n* 1st{{snd}} Sheila O'Malley \u2013 RogerEbert.com<ref name=\"auto4\"/>\n* 1st{{snd}} Peter Sobczynski \u2013 RogerEbert.com<ref name=\"auto4\"/>\n* 1st{{snd}} Max O'Connell \u2013 RogerEbert.com<ref name=\"auto4\"/>\n* 1st{{snd}} [[Col Needham]] \u2013 [[IMDb]]\n* 1st{{snd}} Max Weiss \u2013 ''[[Baltimore (magazine)|Baltimore]]''<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.baltimoremagazine.com/section/artsentertainment/my-favorite-films-of-2019|title=My Favorite Films of 2019|first=Max|last=Weiss|date=December 13, 2019|website=[[Baltimore (magazine)|Baltimore]]}}</ref>\n* 1st{{snd}} Jesse Hassenger \u2013 ''[[The A.V. Club]]''<ref name=\"auto3\">{{Cite web|url=https://film.avclub.com/the-best-films-of-2019-the-ballots-1840454434|title=The best films of 2019: The ballots|first=The A. V.|last=Club|website=Film}}</ref>\n* 1st{{snd}} Vikram Murthi \u2013 ''[[The A.V. Club]]''<ref name=\"auto3\"/>\n* 1st{{snd}} Sean Fennessey and Adam Nayman \u2013 [[The Ringer (website)|The Ringer]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theringer.com/movies/2019/12/5/20995826/best-movies-year-2019-once-upon-a-time-in-hollywood-irishman-marriage-story-parasite-uncut-gems|title=The Best Movies of 2019|first=Sean|last=Fennessey|date=December 5, 2019|website=The Ringer}}</ref>\n* 1st{{snd}} ''[[Consequence of Sound]]''<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://consequenceofsound.net/2019/12/top-25-films-of-2019/|title=Top 25 Films of 2019|date=December 9, 2019}}</ref>\n* 1st{{snd}} Tom Gliatto \u2013 ''[[People (magazine)|People]]''<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://people.com/movies/best-movies-of-the-year-people-critic/|title=The 10 Best Movies of the Year, According to PEOPLE's Critic|website=PEOPLE.com}}</ref>\n* 2nd{{snd}} Noel Murray \u2013 ''[[The A.V. Club]]''<ref name=\"auto3\"/>\n* 2nd{{snd}} Candice Frederick \u2013 ''[[Harper's Bazaar]]''<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.harpersbazaar.com/culture/film-tv/g25910349/best-new-movies-2019/|title=Watch the 10 Best Movies of 2019 Before the Year Is Over|date=December 18, 2019|website=Harper's BAZAAR}}</ref>\n* 2nd{{snd}} Collin Souter \u2013 RogerEbert.com<ref name=\"auto4\"/>\n* 2nd{{snd}} Michal Oleszczyk \u2013 RogerEbert.com<ref name=\"auto4\"/>\n* 2nd{{snd}} [[Richard Roeper]] \u2013 ''[[Chicago Sun-Times]]''<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://chicago.suntimes.com/2019/12/24/21034849/best-movies-of-2019-irishman-queen-slim-little-women-richard-roeper|title=Richard Roeper: The best movies of 2019|first=Richard|last=Roeper|date=December 24, 2019|website=[[Chicago Sun-Times]]}}</ref>\n* 2nd{{snd}} ''[[Flood (magazine)|Flood]]''<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://floodmagazine.com/72201/the-best-films-of-2019/|title=The Best Films of 2019|website=[[Flood Magazine]]}}</ref>\n* 2nd{{snd}} Mara Reinstein \u2013 ''[[Us Weekly]]''<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.usmagazine.com/entertainment/pictures/top-10-movies-of-2019-us-best-films-of-the-year/2-once-upon-a-time-in-hollywood/|title=Us Picks the Top 10 Movies of 2019|date=December 6, 2019}}</ref>\n* 2nd{{snd}} Sam C. Mac \u2013 ''[[Slant Magazine|Slant]]''<ref name=\"auto5\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.slantmagazine.com/film/slants-best-films-of-2019-the-runners-up-and-individual-ballots/|title=Slant's Best Films of 2019: The Runners-Up and Individual Ballots}}</ref>\n* 2nd{{snd}} Scott Feinberg \u2013 ''[[The Hollywood Reporter]]''<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://twitter.com/ScottFeinberg/status/1208579432794882049|title=My top 10 films of 2019: (1) The Two Popes (2) Once Upon a Time in Hollywood (3) Apollo 11 (4) Honey Boy (5) Parasite (6) The Last Black Man in San Francisco (7) The Irishman (8) Midsommar (9) The Biggest Little Farm (10) Wavespic.twitter.com/slvJzlzQNm|first=Scott|last=Feinberg|date=December 21, 2019}}</ref>\n* 2nd{{snd}} Niles Schwartz \u2013 ''Slant''<ref name=\"auto5\"/>\n* 2nd{{snd}} David Rooney \u2013 ''The Hollywood Reporter''<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/lists/hollywood-reporter-critics-pick-best-films-2019-1261962/item/best-films-2019-1-once-a-time-hollywood-1261963|title=1. 'Once Upon a Time in Hollywood ' - Hollywood Reporter Critics Pick the Best Films of 2019|website=The Hollywood Reporter}}</ref>\n* 2nd{{snd}} Matthew Jacobs \u2013 ''[[HuffPost]]''<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.huffpost.com/entry/best-movies-2019-list_n_5df16832e4b01e0f295975ab|title=The 16 Best Movies Of 2019|date=December 18, 2019|website=HuffPost Canada}}</ref>\n* 2nd{{snd}} Leah Greenblatt \u2013 ''[[Entertainment Weekly]]''<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://ew.com/movies/best-and-worst-movies-2019/|title=The best (and worst) movies of 2019|website=EW.com}}</ref>\n* 2nd{{snd}}  [[WatchMojo]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=JtF-x8EMMCM|title=Top 10 Best Movies of 2019|via=[[YouTube]]}}</ref>\n* 2nd{{snd}} ''[[Good Morning America]]''<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.goodmorningamerica.com/culture/story/best-films-2019-67812299|title=7 of the best films of 2019|website=[[Good Morning America]]}}</ref>\n* 3rd{{snd}} Zack Sharf \u2013 IndieWire<ref name=\"auto1\"/>\n* 3rd{{snd}} Matt Singer \u2013 ScreenCrush<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://screencrush.com/the-best-movies-of-2019/|title=The Best Movies of 2019|first=Matt|last=Singer|website=ScreenCrush}}</ref>\n* 3rd{{snd}} David Crow \u2013 [[Den of Geek]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.denofgeek.com/us/go/282640|title=10 Best Movies of 2019|website=Den of Geek}}</ref>\n* 3rd{{snd}} [[Film Comment]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.filmcomment.com/best-films-of-2019/|title=Best Films of 2019|website=Film Comment}}</ref>\n* 3rd{{snd}} [[Film School Rejects]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://filmschoolrejects.com/best-movies-2019/|title=The 50 Best Movies of 2019|date=December 31, 2019|website=Film School Rejects}}</ref>\n* 3rd{{snd}} Katie Rife \u2013 ''The A.V. Club''<ref name=\"auto3\"/>\n* 3rd{{snd}} Roxana Hadadi \u2013 ''The A.V. Club''<ref name=\"auto3\"/>\n* 3rd{{snd}} [[Stephanie Zacharek]] \u2013 ''[[Time (magazine)|Time]]''<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://time.com/5737103/best-movies-2019/|title=The 10 Best Movies of 2019|website=Time}}</ref>\n* 3rd{{snd}} Clayton Dillard \u2013 ''Slant''<ref name=\"auto5\"/>\n* 3rd{{snd}} Michael Barker \u2013 [[Film at Lincoln Center]]<ref name=\"auto2\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.indiewire.com/2019/12/best-movies-2019-indie-film-community-1202198566/|title=The Best Films of 2019, According to the Independent Film Community|first1=Eric|last1=Kohn|first2=Eric|last2=Kohn|date=December 24, 2019}}</ref>\n* 3rd{{snd}} Wes Greene \u2013 ''Slant''<ref name=\"auto5\"/>\n* 3rd{{snd}} Bob Strauss \u2013 ''[[Los Angeles Daily News]]''<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dailynews.com/2019-was-a-terrific-year-for-movies-here-are-12-films-you-have-to-see|title=2019 was a terrific year for movies. Here are 12 films you have to see|date=December 17, 2019}}</ref>\n* 3rd{{snd}} [[Online Film Critics Society]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://ofcs.org/ofcs-presents-22nd-annual-nominations-for-2018-2-2/|title=OFCS Presents: 23rd Annual Awards for 2019|first=Governing|last=Committee|date=January 7, 2020}}</ref>\n* 4th{{snd}} [[Kyle Smith]] \u2013 ''[[National Review]]''<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nationalreview.com/2019/12/movie-review-ten-best-films-2019/|title=The Ten Best Films of 2019|date=December 23, 2019}}</ref>\n* 4th{{snd}} Tomris Laffly \u2013 RogerEbert.com<ref name=\"auto4\"/>\n* 4th{{snd}} IndieWire (300+ Critics Survey)<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.indiewire.com/2019/12/best-movies-2019-critics-survey-poll-performances-parasite-adam-driver-lupita-nyongo-1202197615/|title=2019 Critics Poll: The Best Films and Performances According to Over 300 Critics From Around the World|first1=Eric|last1=Kohn|first2=Eric|last2=Kohn|date=December 16, 2019}}</ref>\n* 4th{{snd}} Ignatiy Vishnevetsky \u2013 ''The A.V. Club''<ref name=\"auto3\"/>\n* 4th{{snd}} David Sims \u2013 ''[[The Atlantic]]''<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theatlantic.com/entertainment/archive/2019/12/10-best-films-2019/602797/|title=The 10 Best Films of 2019|first=David|last=Sims|date=December 5, 2019|website=The Atlantic}}</ref>\n* 4th{{snd}} Vinnie Mancuso \u2013 [[Collider (website)|Collider]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://collider.com/best-movies-of-the-year-2019/|title=Vinnie Mancuso's Top 10 Films of 2019|first=Vinnie|last=Mancuso|date=December 10, 2019}}</ref>\n* 4th{{snd}} [[Sight & Sound]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://theplaylist.net/souvenir-parasite-sight-sounds-top-20-films-2019-20191201/|title='The Souvenir,' 'Parasite' Top Sight & Sound's Top 20 Films Of 2019|website=theplaylist.net}}</ref>\n* 4th{{snd}} ''[[Complex (magazine)|Complex]]''<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.complex.com/pop-culture/best-movies-of-2019/|title=The Best Movies of 2019'Once Upon a Time... in Hollywood'|website=Complex}}</ref>\n* 5th{{snd}} Alissa Wilkinson \u2013 [[Vox (website)|Vox]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.vox.com/2019/12/5/20983881/best-movies-2019-streaming-how-to-watch|title=The 21 best films of 2019|first=Alissa|last=Wilkinson|date=December 5, 2019|website=Vox}}</ref>\n* 5th{{snd}} Kate Erbland \u2013 IndieWire<ref name=\"auto1\"/>\n* 5th{{snd}} Christopher Gray \u2013 ''Slant''<ref name=\"auto5\"/>\n* 5th{{snd}} Keith Watson \u2013 ''Slant''<ref name=\"auto5\"/>\n* 5th{{snd}} Dan Jackson \u2013 [[Thrillist]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thrillist.com/entertainment/nation/best-movies-of-2019|title=The 50 Best Movies of 2019, Ranked|first=Dan|last=Jackson|date=January 3, 2020|website=Thrillist}}</ref>\n* 5th{{snd}} Charles Bramesco \u2013 ''The A.V. Club''<ref name=\"auto3\"/>\n* 6th{{snd}} Adam Chitwood \u2013 Collider<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://collider.com/best-2019-movies/|title=Adam Chitwood's Top 10 Films of 2019|first=Adam|last=Chitwood|date=December 13, 2019}}</ref>\n* 6th{{snd}} Chuck Bowen \u2013 ''Slant''<ref name=\"auto5\"/>\n* 6th{{snd}} Samuel R. Murian \u2013 ''[[Parade (magazine)|Parade]]''<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://parade.com/967301/samuelmurrian/best-movies-of-2019-ranked/|title=The 25 Best Movies of 2019, Ranked|first=Samuel R.|last=Murrian|date=December 18, 2019|website=Parade}}</ref>\n* 6th{{snd}} Andr\u00e9a Picard \u2013 Film at Lincoln Center<ref name=\"auto2\"/>\n* 7th{{snd}} Monica Castillo \u2013 RogerEbert.com<ref name=\"auto4\"/>\n* 7th{{snd}} Guy Lodge \u2013 ''[[The Guardian]]''<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/2019/dec/03/50-best-films-of-2019-in-the-us|title=The 50 best films of 2019 in the US: the full list|date=December 20, 2019|via=www.theguardian.com}}</ref>\n* 7th{{snd}} Derek Smith \u2013 ''Slant''<ref name=\"auto5\"/>\n* 7th{{snd}} ''[[Sydney Morning Herald]]''\n* 8th{{snd}} Mark Hughes \u2013 ''[[Forbes]]''<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/markhughes/2020/12/30/the-top-20-best-films-of-2019/|title=The Top 20 Best Films Of 2019|first=Mark|last=Hughes|website=Forbes}}</ref>\n* 8th{{snd}} Glenn Kenny \u2013 RogerEbert.com<ref name=\"auto4\"/>\n* 8th{{snd}} Matt Fagerholm \u2013 RogerEbert.com<ref name=\"auto4\"/>\n* 8th{{snd}} [[Yahoo! Entertainment]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bostonglobe.com/2019/12/20/arts/ty-burrs-best-movies-2019/|title=Ty Burr's best movies of 2019 - The Boston Globe|website=BostonGlobe.com}}</ref>\n* 8th{{snd}} [[Justin Chang]] \u2013 ''[[Los Angeles Times]]''<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.latimes.com/entertainment-arts/movies/story/2019-12-06/2019-best-movies-justin-chang|title=Justin Chang's best movies of 2019: 'Parasite,' 'Knives Out' stand at the head of the class|date=December 6, 2019|website=Los Angeles Times}}</ref>\n* 8th{{snd}} Alex Biese \u2013 ''[[Asbury Park Press]]''<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.app.com/story/entertainment/movies/2019/12/12/best-movies-2019-midsommar-irishman-parasite/4309923002/|title=Best movies of 2019: The Irishman, Parasite and Midsommar among the year's instant classics|first=Alex|last=Biese|website=Asbury Park Press}}</ref>\n* 8th{{snd}} [[Eugene Hernandez]] \u2013 Film at Lincoln Center<ref name=\"auto2\"/>\n* 9th{{snd}} Mike D'Angelo \u2013 ''The A.V. Club''<ref name=\"auto3\"/>\n* 9th{{snd}} Robert Daniels \u2013 RogerEbert.com<ref name=\"auto4\"/>\n* 9th{{snd}} Ben Kenigsberg \u2013 RogerEbert.com<ref name=\"auto4\"/>\n* 9th{{snd}} Caroline Siede \u2013 ''[[The A.V. Club]]''<ref name=\"auto3\"/>\n* 9th{{snd}} [[A. O. Scott]] \u2013 ''[[The New York Times]]''<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/12/04/movies/best-films.html|title=Best Movies of 2019|first1=A. O.|last1=Scott|first2=Manohla|last2=Dargis|date=December 4, 2019|via=NYTimes.com}}</ref>\n* 10th{{snd}} [[Tom Brook]] \u2013 ''[[Talking Movies]]''<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/av/entertainment-arts-50837255/what-are-talking-movies-top-10-films-for-2019|title=What are Talking Movies' Top 10 films for 2019?|website=BBC News}}</ref>\n* 10th{{snd}} Joshua Rothkopf \u2013 ''[[Time Out (magazine)#Time Out New York|Time Out New York]]''<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.timeout.com/newyork/movies/best-movies-of-2019|title=The 20 best movies of 2019|website=[[Time Out (magazine)#Time Out New York|Time Out New York]]}}</ref>\n{{div col end}}\n\n== Pop culture references ==\nThe title is a reference to director [[Sergio Leone]]'s second western/American trilogy, ''[[Once Upon a Time in the West]]'', ''Once Upon a Time\u2026 the Revolution'' (which producers insisted on retitling ''[[Duck, You Sucker!]]'' ), and ''[[Once Upon a Time in America]]''.<ref name=easter-eggs/>\n\nArchive footage from many films is included in ''Once Upon a Time in Hollywood'', including ''[[C.C. and Company]]'', ''[[Lady in Cement]]'', ''[[Three in the Attic]]'', and ''[[The Wrecking Crew (1968 film)|The Wrecking Crew]]'', in which [[Sharon Tate]] appears as Freya Carlson. Three scenes were digitally altered, replacing the original actors with Rick Dalton. One from an episode of ''[[The F.B.I. (TV series)|The F.B.I.]]'', entitled \"All the Streets Are Silent,\" in which Dalton appears as a character originally portrayed by [[Burt Reynolds]]. Another from ''[[Death on the Run]]'', with Dalton's face imposed over [[Ty Hardin]]'s. The third is from ''[[The Great Escape (film)|The Great Escape]]'', with Dalton appearing as Virgil Hilts, the role made famous by [[Steve McQueen]].<ref name=easter-eggs>{{cite news |url=https://screenrant.com/once-upon-time-hollywood-movie-easter-eggs-cameos/ |title=Once Upon a Time in Hollywood: Every Easter Egg, Tarantino Reference & Cameo |website=[[Screen Rant]] |last=Hunt |first=James |access-date=August 16, 2019 |date=August 16, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190816180441/https://screenrant.com/once-upon-time-hollywood-movie-easter-eggs-cameos/ |archive-date=August 16, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=FakeMovies>{{cite news |url=https://www.thewrap.com/once-upon-a-time-in-hollywood-what-real-movies-inspired-rick-daltons-fake-films/ |title='Once Upon a Time in Hollywood': What Real Movies Inspired Rick Dalton's Fake Films? |work=[[TheWrap]] |last=Welk |first=Brian |access-date=August 13, 2019 |date=July 26, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190814094933/https://www.thewrap.com/once-upon-a-time-in-hollywood-what-real-movies-inspired-rick-daltons-fake-films/ |archive-date=August 14, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"Archive footage\"/> For ''The 14 Fists of McCluskey'', a WWII film within the film starring Dalton, footage and music from ''[[Hell River]]'' is used.<ref>{{cite web |last=Tate |first=James M. |url=http://www.cultfilmfreaks.com/2019/08/hell-river.html |title=How 'Hell River' Connects 'Once Upon a Time in Hollywood' |website=cult film freak |access-date=September 4, 2019 |date=August 26, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190905020522/http://www.cultfilmfreaks.com/2019/08/hell-river.html |archive-date=September 5, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref> Additionally, Martin Abrahams, [[Brioni Farrell]], Victor Freitag, [[Nancy Kwan]], [[Dean Martin]], [[Hannes Messemer]], [[Gordon Mitchell]], [[Rod Taylor]], [[Burt Ward]], and [[Adam West]] appear via archive footage and sound.\n\nThe 1959 [[Ford Galaxie]] driven by the Manson Family is a detailed replica of the car used in the Tate\u2013LaBianca murders. Car coordinator Steven Butcher found the actual car, but after a meeting with Tarantino, they decided using it would be \"too creepy.\"<ref name=vintage-cars>{{cite news |url=https://www.thewrap.com/once-upon-a-time-in-hollywood-cars-reservoir-dogs/ |title=Quentin Tarantino used an 'Absurd Amount of Vintage Cars in 'Once Upon a Time in Hollywood'{{'}} |website=[[TheWrap]] |last=Welk |first=Brian |access-date=August 14, 2019 |date=July 31, 2019 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190814161623/https://www.thewrap.com/once-upon-a-time-in-hollywood-cars-reservoir-dogs/ |archive-date=August 14, 2019}}</ref>\n\n[[Mark Lindsay]], lead singer of [[Paul Revere & the Raiders]], whose music is featured in the film, once lived at [[10050 Cielo Drive]], the address of the Tate murders. On the poster of Dalton's film ''Red Blood Red Skin'', inspired by ''[[Land Raiders (film)|Land Raiders]]'', he appears with [[Telly Savalas]]. The posters for the two films are the same, except with Dalton replacing [[George Maharis]]. The movie Voytek Frykowski is watching is ''[[Teenage Monster]]'', presented by horror host [[Larry Vincent|Seymour]].<ref name=FakeMovies/><ref name=annotated>{{cite news |url=https://film.avclub.com/once-upon-a-time-in-hollywood-annotated-1836793225 |title=Once Upon a Time... in Hollywood... annotated |website=[[The A.V. Club]] |access-date=September 1, 2019 |date=August 2, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190804014912/https://film.avclub.com/once-upon-a-time-in-hollywood-annotated-1836793225 |archive-date=August 4, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n=== Connections to other Tarantino films ===\nCliff Booth is a reference to Brad Pitt's character in ''Inglourious Basterds'', Aldo Raine, who takes the cover of a stuntman.<ref name=easter-eggs/> Dalton stars in a Spaghetti Western directed by Antonio Margheriti which is a reference to an alias used by the Basterds.<ref>https://www.indiewire.com/2019/07/once-upon-a-time-in-hollywood-inglourious-basterds-easter-egg-explained-1202160949/</ref> When Dalton and Booth get back from Italy they walk by the blue mosaic wall in [[LAX]], the same wall that the title character in Tarantino's ''[[Jackie Brown]]'' ([[Pam Grier]]) moves past in the opening credits of that film.<ref name=39-details>{{cite news |last=Snyder |first=Chris |url=https://www.businessinsider.com/quentin-tarantino-once-upon-time-hollywood-details-you-missed-2019-7 |title=39 details you may have missed in Tarantino's \"Once Upon a Time in Hollywood\" |website=Business Insider |access-date=September 15, 2019 |date=August 2, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190803025838/https://www.businessinsider.com/quentin-tarantino-once-upon-time-hollywood-details-you-missed-2019-7 |archive-date=August 3, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn the film, Lee engages in a fight with Cliff Booth on the set of ''The Green Hornet''.<ref name=39-details/><ref name=controversial-scene/> The ''Green Hornet'' [[Flight of the Bumblebee|theme song]] is featured in Tarantino's ''[[Kill Bill: Volume 1]]''.<ref name=39-details/> The masks worn by the Crazy 88 gang in that film are the same as Lee's mask as Kato in ''The Green Hornet''.<ref>{{cite web |last=Siller |first=Alexandra |title=O-Ren Ishii: Samurai of The Underworld |url=https://medium.com/@acs58312/in-the-eyes-of-kill-bill-s-o-ren-ishii-311c7f5bffe8 |website=Medium |date=April 3, 2016 |access-date=September 28, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170113182430/https://medium.com/@acs58312/in-the-eyes-of-kill-bill-s-o-ren-ishii-311c7f5bffe8 |archive-date=January 13, 2017 |url-status=live}}</ref> The car Booth drives is a 1964 blue [[Volkswagen Karmann Ghia]] convertible. It is the same year, color, make and model of the car that [[The Bride (Kill Bill)|Beatrix \"the Bride\" Kiddo]] ([[Uma Thurman]]) drives in ''[[Kill Bill: Volume 2]]''.<ref name=geek-easter-eggs>{{cite news |last=Crow |first=David |url=https://www.denofgeek.com/us/movies/282478/once-upon-a-time-in-hollywood-easter-eggs-references |title=Once Upon a Time in Hollywood Easter Eggs Guide |website=[[Den of Geek]] |access-date=August 31, 2019 |date=August 17, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190831010250/https://www.denofgeek.com/us/movies/282478/once-upon-a-time-in-hollywood-easter-eggs-references |archive-date=August 31, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref> Similarly, Rick Dalton's 1966 [[Cadillac de Ville series|Cadillac de Ville]] is the same as the car driven by Mr. Blonde ([[Michael Madsen]]) in ''[[Reservoir Dogs]]''. It is owned by Madsen.<ref name=vintage-cars/>\n\nTarantino-invented fast food chain [[Big Kahuna Burger]] appears on a billboard. The final scene features Rick Dalton in a commercial for fictional Red Apple cigarettes, which appear in many Tarantino films.<ref name=gamespot-easter-eggs/><ref name=easter-eggs/><ref name=\"Archive footage\"/><ref name=geek-easter-eggs/>\n\n== Historical accuracy ==\nIn a scene, Sharon Tate goes into Larry Edmunds Bookshop and purchases a copy of ''[[Tess of the d'Urbervilles]]''. In real life, Tate gave a copy to Roman Polanski shortly before her death. Years later, Polanski directed the film adaptation, ''[[Tess (1979 film)|Tess]]'', dedicating it to Tate. Dalton mentions he owns his house on advice from \"[[Edmond O'Brien|Eddie O'Brien]].\" Tate and Polanski's [[Yorkie Terrier]] in the film is named \"Dr. Sapirstein,\" as was Tate's Yorkie in real life, named after the doctor portrayed by [[Ralph Bellamy]] in ''Rosemary's Baby''. The carrier she puts the dog in is the same one the real Tate actually owned. The outfit Margot Robbie wears in the Bruin Theater scene is the same one Tate wore in ''[[Eye of the Devil]]''.<ref name=geek-easter-eggs/>\n\n[[File:Fox Bruin Theater (Westwood).jpg|thumb|upright=1.2|The [[Fox Bruin Theater]]]]\n\nIn the film, Tate goes to see ''[[The Wrecking Crew (1968 film)|The Wrecking Crew]]'' at the [[Bruin Theater]]. She convinces the theater's employees that she stars in the movie after they fail to recognize her. Tarantino stated the idea came to him from an experience he had. When ''[[True Romance]]'' was released, he saw it at the same theater, where he eventually convinced its employees that he wrote the script.<ref name=cinema-blend>{{cite news |last=O'Connell |first=Sean |url=https://www.cinemablend.com/podcast/2476541/will-quentin-tarantinos-last-movie-be-star-trek-the-director-talks-about-a-loophole |title=Will Quentin Tarantino's Last Movie Be Star Trek? The Director Talks About A 'Loophole' |website=CinemaBlend |access-date=August 26, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190814190145/https://www.cinemablend.com/podcast/2476541/will-quentin-tarantinos-last-movie-be-star-trek-the-director-talks-about-a-loophole |archive-date=August 14, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn the set of ''[[Batman (TV show)|Batman]]'', for a crossover episode with ''[[The Green Hornet (TV series)|The Green Hornet]]'', a fight was scripted with Kato losing to [[Robin (character)|Robin]] ([[Burt Ward]]). When Lee received the script, he refused to do it, so it was changed to a draw. When the cameras rolled, Lee stalked Ward until Ward backed away. Lee laughed and told him he was \"lucky it is a TV show.\"<ref name=Kato-show>{{cite news |url=https://www.newsweek.com/bruce-lee-king-fu-martial-arts-390811 |title=The Kato Show: Bruce Lee as the Green Hornet's Sidekick |website=[[Newsweek]] |access-date=August 26, 2019 |date=November 20, 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190831111350/https://www.newsweek.com/bruce-lee-king-fu-martial-arts-390811 |archive-date=August 31, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref> In the film, Cliff Booth reminisces about fighting Lee on the set of ''The Green Hornet''; the imaginary fight also ends in a draw. Booth refers to Lee as \"Kato.\"<ref name=controversial-scene/>\n\nAccording to Rudolph Altobelli, who rented the house to Polanski and Tate, in March 1969, Charles Manson showed up looking for [[Terry Melcher]]. Polanski's friend Shahrokh Hatami also said he saw Manson enter the grounds. Hatami approached Manson, asking him what he wanted. He told Hatami he was looking for Melcher. Hatami responded the house was the Polanski residence and perhaps Melcher lived in the guest house. Altobelli told Manson that Melcher no longer lived there.<ref>{{cite news |last=Caldwell |first=Earl |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1970/10/22/archives/manson-put-at-tate-home-5-months-before-killings.html |title=Manson Put at Tate Home 5 Months Before Killings |website=[[The New York Times]] |access-date=August 26, 2019 |date=October 22, 1970 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190826230558/https://www.nytimes.com/1970/10/22/archives/manson-put-at-tate-home-5-months-before-killings.html |archive-date=August 26, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref> This happens in the film, with Sebring in place of Altobelli and Hatami.\n\nOn the night of August 8, 1969, Patricia Krenwinkel, Charles Watson, and Susan Atkins broke into Polanski's and Tate's house, leading to the murders of Tate (eight-and-a-half months pregnant), Sebring, Wojciech Frykowski, and Abigail Folger. In the film, they go to Tate's house to commit the murders but instead end up breaking into Dalton's house after he interrupts them.<ref name=helter-skelter/> Linda Kasabian went along that night as she was the only Family member with a valid driver's license, though she did not murder anyone and stayed outside the whole time. In the film, she also goes along but does not participate.<ref name=helter-skelter/> Watson told his victims, \"I'm the [[Devil]], and I came to do the Devil's business.\" In the film, he says it to Cliff Booth.<ref name=devils-business>{{cite news |last=Romano |first=Evan |url=https://www.menshealth.com/entertainment/a28521042/once-upon-a-time-in-hollywood-devil-line-real-tex-watson/ |title=Was that Creepy Line from Once Upon a Time...in Hollywood Real? |website=[[Men's Health]] |access-date=August 20, 2019 |date=July 26, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190820181956/https://www.menshealth.com/entertainment/a28521042/once-upon-a-time-in-hollywood-devil-line-real-tex-watson/ |archive-date=August 20, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref> In the film, Atkins convinces the others to seek revenge by killing Rick Dalton, star of a TV western. Since TV taught them to kill, it is fitting they kill the guy from TV, and \"My idea is to kill the people who taught us to kill!\"<ref name=how-true-to-life>{{cite news |last=Rao |first=Sonia |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/arts-entertainment/2019/07/29/how-true-life-is-once-upon-time-hollywood-ending/ |title=How true to life is the 'Once Upon a Time in Hollywood' ending? |website=[[The Washington Post]]|access-date=August 22, 2019 |date=July 29, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190803170857/https://www.washingtonpost.com/arts-entertainment/2019/07/29/how-true-life-is-once-upon-time-hollywood-ending/ |archive-date=August 3, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=twist-ending>{{cite news |last=Wilkinson |first=Alissa |url=https://www.vox.com/culture/2019/7/25/8906839/tarantino-once-upon-a-time-in-hollywood-spoilers-ending-manson |title=The twist ending of Quentin Tarantino's Once Upon a Time in Hollywood, explained |website=[[Vox (website)|Vox]]|access-date=August 22, 2019 |date=July 25, 2019}}</ref> In real life, Manson Family member [[Nancy Pitman]] said: \"We are what you have made us. We were brought up on your TV. We were brought up watching ''[[Gunsmoke]]'' and ''[[Have Gun \u2013 Will Travel]]''.\"<ref name=five-things>{{cite news |url=https://www.geeklygood.com/blogs/news/five-things-you-didnt-know-about-tarantinos-once-upon-a-time-in-hollywood |title=Five Things You Didn't Know About Tarantino's Once Upon a Time in Hollywood |website=geeklygoods |access-date=August 22, 2019 |date=July 29, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190823045625/https://geeklygood.com/blogs/news/five-things-you-didnt-know-about-tarantinos-once-upon-a-time-in-hollywood |archive-date=August 23, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref> [[Sandra Good]] said: \"You want to talk about devils and demonic and immorals and evil, go to Hollywood. We don't touch the evil of that world. We don't even skim it.\"<ref>{{cite news |last=Kilkenny |first=Katie |url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/manson-women-followers-recall-leaders-manipulation-1230616 |title=Former Manson Followers Debate Family's Culpability: 'How Can You Point the Finger at Us?' |website=[[The Hollywood Reporter]] |access-date=August 28, 2019 |date=August 10, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190813210823/https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/manson-women-followers-recall-leaders-manipulation-1230616 |archive-date=August 13, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nThe next night, the same four, along with Leslie Van Houten, Manson, and Steve Grogan, drove to Leno and Rosemary LaBianca's house, murdering the couple. Afterwards, Manson directed Kasabian to drive to an apartment complex to commit more murders. Once there, Manson left in the car alone, leaving the others to hitchhike back to Spahn Ranch. In the film, it is Kasabian who drives off, deserting others. Watson says they can hitchhike back.<ref name=helter-skelter/> Grogan was convicted of the murder of stuntman [[Donald Shea|Donald \"Shorty\" Shea]] on Spahn Ranch, whom he repeatedly beat with a lead pipe. In the film, Grogan is instead beaten by a stuntman, Booth.<ref name=helter-skelter>{{cite book|last1=Bugliosi|first1=Vincent|first2=Curt|last2=Gentry|title=Helter Skelter \u2013 The True Story of the Manson Murders|edition=25th Anniversary|publisher=W.W. Norton & Company|year=1994|ISBN=0-393-08700-X|url-access=registration|url=https://archive.org/details/helterskeltertru00bugl_0}}</ref>\n\n[[Boeing 747]]s are used in several airliner scenes, but they were not in commercial use until 1970 even though the film is set a year earlier in 1969.<ref name=\"Time_Jumbo-Gremlins\">[http://www.time.com/time/magazine/article/0,9171,878184,00.html \"Jumbo and the Gremlins.\"] ''TIME'', February 2, 1970. Retrieved: December 20, 2007.</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.boeing.com/commercial/747family/background.html |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121002063408/http://www.boeing.com/commercial/747family/background.html |title=Boeing: Commercial Airplanes - 747 - About the 747 Family |archivedate=October 2, 2012 |work=Boeing}}</ref>\n\n=== The Manson Family in Hollywood ===\nCharles Manson once approached [[Steve McQueen]] with a script he wrote, to get him to produce it. When McQueen turned him down, an altercation happened, in which McQueen broke Manson's nose.<ref name=mcqueen-manson>{{cite news |url=https://www.esquire.com/uk/culture/film/news/a13833/steve-mcqueen-infidelity-charles-manson-murder/ |title=Steve McQueen's Womanizing Ways Stopped Him From Being Murdered By Charles Manson |website=[[Esquire (magazine)|Esquire]] |access-date=August 18, 2019 |date=March 21, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180208003429/http://www.esquire.com/uk/culture/film/news/a13833/steve-mcqueen-infidelity-charles-manson-murder/ |archive-date=February 8, 2018 |url-status=live}}</ref> On the night of the Tate murders, Jay Sebring invited McQueen over to Tate's house; however, his date wanted to stay in.<ref>{{cite book |last=Eliot |first=Marc |title=Steve McQueen: A Biography |publisher=[[Crown Publishing Group]] |year=2011 |isbn=978-0-307-45323-5}}</ref> After the murders, it was reported that police found a Manson Family hit list with McQueen's name.<ref>{{cite book|last=Dunne|first=Dominick|title=The Way We Lived Then: Recollections of a Well Known Name Dropper|year=1999|location=New York City|publisher=[[Crown Publishing Group]]|ISBN=0-609-60388-4|url-access=registration|url=https://archive.org/details/waywelivedthenr00dunn}}</ref>\n\nBobby Beausoleil was an actor and [[porn star]]. He appeared in the documentary film ''[[Mondo Hollywood]]'', also featuring Sebring. [[Catherine Share]] met Beausoleil on the set of the [[softcore porn]] film ''Ramrodder''. Beausoleil introduced Share to Manson.<ref>{{cite book |title=Sinister Forces \u2013 The Manson Secret: A Grimoire of American Political Witchcraft |first=Peter |last=Lavenda |publisher=Trine Day |date=June 1, 2011 |isbn=978-0-9841858-3-2}}</ref> Atkins met Manson in San Francisco, where she had worked as an actress, portraying a [[vampire]] on [[Anton LaVey]]'s Witches Sabbath Club Show.<ref name=Guinn>{{cite book |last=Guinn |first=Jeff |title=Manson: The Life and Times of Charles Manson |publisher=[[Simon & Schuster]] |year=2013 |isbn=978-1-4516-4518-7}}</ref> LaVey appeared with Beausoleil in ''[[Lucifer Rising (film)|Lucifer Rising]]'',<ref name=Landis>{{cite book |last=Landis |first=Bill |title=Anger: An Unauthorized Biography of Kenneth Anger |publisher=[[Harper Collins]] |year=1995 |isbn=978-0-06-016700-4}}</ref> and claimed to have been a consultant on and appeared as the Devil in Polanski's ''Rosemary's Baby''.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://variety.com/1997/scene/people-news/anton-szandor-lavey-1116674361/ |title=Anton Szandor LaVey |website=Variety |access-date=August 28, 2019 |date=November 19, 1997 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190828233810/https://variety.com/1997/scene/people-news/anton-szandor-lavey-1116674361/ |archive-date=August 28, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Moffitt |first=Mike |url=https://www.sfchronicle.com/bayarea/article/When-the-Devil-lived-in-the-Richmond-7382271.php |title=When the Devil lived in the Richmond |website=[[San Francisco Chronicle]] |access-date=August 28, 2019 |date=May 4, 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190829002747/https://www.sfchronicle.com/bayarea/article/When-the-Devil-lived-in-the-Richmond-7382271.php |archive-date=August 29, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n== Portrayals of real-life figures==\n=== Bruce Lee ===\n[[File:Bruce Lee 1973.jpg|thumb|upright=0.84|[[Bruce Lee]], portrayed in the film by [[Mike Moh]]. The appearance of Lee in the film was criticized by Asian-Americans and former friends and family of him, who considered it offensive and inaccurate.]]Although its context is a daydream of Cliff Booth's rather than a \"real\" event in the narrative, the depiction of [[Bruce Lee]] drew criticism. Fans and contemporaries of Lee took issue with his portrayal.<ref name=daughter-saddened>{{Cite web |last=Molloy |first=Tim |url=https://www.thewrap.com/bruce-lee-daughter-mockery-once-upon-a-time-in-hollywood-shannon-lee/ |title=Bruce Lee's Daughter Saddened by 'Mockery' in Once Upon a Time...in Hollywood |work=[[TheWrap]]|accessdate=August 17, 2019 |date=July 29, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190816174854/https://www.thewrap.com/bruce-lee-daughter-mockery-once-upon-a-time-in-hollywood-shannon-lee/ |archive-date=August 16, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"shutup\">{{Cite magazine |last=Yap |first=Audrey Cleo |url=https://variety.com/2019/film/news/bruce-lee-quentin-tarantino-shannon-lee-interview-1203302850/ |magazine=Variety |title=Bruce Lee's Daughter Says Quentin Tarantino 'Could Shut Up' About Her Father's Portrayal |accessdate=August 17, 2019 |date=August 14, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190816201453/https://variety.com/2019/film/news/bruce-lee-quentin-tarantino-shannon-lee-interview-1203302850/ |archive-date=August 16, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref> Lee's daughter, [[Shannon Lee|Shannon]], stated: \"[Lee] was continuously marginalized and treated like kind of a nuisance of a human being by white Hollywood, which is how he's treated in the film by [Tarantino].\"<ref name=inosanto>{{cite magazine |last=Yap |first=Audrey Cleo |url=https://variety.com/2019/film/features/bruce-lee-once-upon-a-time-in-hollywood-dan-inosanto-1203287237/ |title=Bruce Lee's Protege Recalls His Humility Amid 'Once Upon a Time' Criticism |magazine=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] |accessdate=August 17, 2019 |date=July 31, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190816130517/https://variety.com/2019/film/features/bruce-lee-once-upon-a-time-in-hollywood-dan-inosanto-1203287237/ |archive-date=August 16, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref> [[Kareem Abdul-Jabbar]], with whom Lee trained and appeared in ''[[Game of Death]]'', stated: \"Of course, Tarantino has the artistic right to portray Bruce any way he wants. But to do so in such a sloppy and somewhat racist way is a failure both as an artist and as a human being.\"<ref>{{Cite web |last=Abdul-Jabbar |first=Kareem |url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/kareem-abdul-jabbar-bruce-lee-was-my-friend-tarantinos-movie-disrespects-him-1232544 |title=Kareem Abdul-Jabbar:Bruce Lee Was My Friend, & Tarantino's Movie Disrespects Him |accessdate=August 17, 2019 |date=August 16, 2019 |website=[[The Hollywood Reporter]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190816194616/https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/kareem-abdul-jabbar-bruce-lee-was-my-friend-tarantinos-movie-disrespects-him-1232544 |archive-date=August 16, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n[[Mike Moh]], who played Lee, said he was conflicted at first: \"Bruce in my mind was literally a god. ... Bruce didn't always have the most affection for stuntmen; he didn't respect all of them.\"<ref name=Bruce-Lee-actor>{{cite news |last=Galbraith |first=Alex |url=https://www.complex.com/pop-culture/2019/08/bruce-lee-actor-once-upon-a-time-in-hollywood-fight-scene |title=Bruce Lee Actor Defends 'Once Upon A Time In Hollywood' Fight Scene |website=[[Complex (magazine)|Complex]] |accessdate=August 17, 2019 |date=August 4, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190817182856/https://www.complex.com/pop-culture/2019/08/bruce-lee-actor-once-upon-a-time-in-hollywood-fight-scene |archive-date=August 17, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref> He stated, \"Tarantino loves Bruce Lee; he reveres him.\"<ref name=\"Mike-Moh-Bruce-Lee\">{{cite news |url=https://www.indiewire.com/2019/08/once-upon-a-time-in-hollywood-bruce-lee-mike-moh-1202163256/ |title='Once Upon a Time in Hollywood': Bruce Lee Actor Explains Why the Martial Arts King Loses to Brad Pitt |last=Lattanzio |first=Ryan |date=August 4, 2019 |access-date=August 17, 2019 |website=[[IndieWire]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190808113755/https://www.indiewire.com/2019/08/once-upon-a-time-in-hollywood-bruce-lee-mike-moh-1202163256/ |archive-date=August 8, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref> Brad Pitt objected to an extended version of the fight, stating \"It's Bruce Lee, man!\" according to stunt coordinator Robert Alonzo.<ref name=\"jacobshuffington\">{{cite news |last1=Jacobs |first1=Matthew |title=Tarantino's Secrets, Brad's Pitt And Leo's Flames: Tales From 'Once Upon A Time In Hollywood' |url=https://www.huffingtonpost.co.uk/entry/once-upon-a-time-in-hollywood-tarantino-behind-the-scenes_n_5d434018e4b0acb57fc97dfa?guccounter=1 |accessdate=March 3, 2020 |work=Huffington Post |date=August 6, 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"sharfindiewire\">{{cite news |last1=Sharf |first1=Zack |title=Brad Pitt Objected to Extended Bruce Lee Fight Scene in \u2018Once Upon a Time in Hollywood\u2019 Script |url=https://www.indiewire.com/2019/08/brad-pitt-rejected-extended-bruce-lee-fight-once-upon-a-time-in-hollywood-1202163376/ |accessdate=March 3, 2020 |work=IndieWire |date=August 5, 2019}}</ref> According to Lee's friend and ''[[The Green Hornet (TV series)|The Green Hornet]]'' stuntman [[Gene LeBell]], Lee had a reputation for \"kicking the shit out of the stuntmen. They couldn't convince him that he could go easy and it would still look great on film.\"<ref name=\"Debunking Mockery\"/> Lee biographer Matthew Polly stated, \"Bruce was very famous for being very considerate of the people below him on film sets, particularly the stuntmen. ... So in this scene, Bruce Lee is essentially calling out a stuntman and getting him fired because he's the big star.\"<ref name=\"controversial-scene\">{{cite news |last=Bruney |first=Gabrielle |url=https://www.esquire.com/entertainment/a28607548/mike-moh-bruce-lee-once-upon-a-time-in-hollywood-controversy |title=Why the Bruce Lee Fight in Once Upon a Time in Hollywood Has Become the Movie's Most Controversial Scene |website=[[Esquire (magazine)|Esquire]] |accessdate=August 18, 2019 |date=August 7, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190807002649/https://www.esquire.com/entertainment/a28607548/mike-moh-bruce-lee-once-upon-a-time-in-hollywood-controversy/ |archive-date=August 7, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nTarantino responded, saying Lee was \"kind of an arrogant guy,\" and that Lee's widow [[Linda Lee Cadwell|Linda]] wrote in ''[[Bruce Lee: The Man Only I Knew]]'' that he could beat [[Muhammad Ali]].<ref name=shutup/> However, the book in question has a quote from a film critic stating so, not Linda.<ref name=\"fuster2019\">{{cite news |last1=Fuster |first1=Jeremy |title=Quentin Tarantino Defends \u2018Hollywood\u2019 Depiction of Bruce Lee: \u2018He Was Kind of an Arrogant Guy\u2019 |url=https://www.thewrap.com/tarantino-defends-bruce-lee-portrayal/ |accessdate=March 8, 2020 |work=The Wrap |date=August 19, 2019}}</ref> In 1972, Lee himself stated: \"Everybody says I must fight Ali some day. ... Look at my hand. That's a little Chinese hand. He'd kill me.\"<ref>{{cite book |last=Clouse |first=Robert |date=1988 |title=Bruce Lee: The Biography |publisher=Unique Publications |page=112 |isbn=978-0-86568-133-0}}</ref>\n\n=== Sharon Tate ===\nTarantino gave an early script to a representative of [[Roman Polanski]], Tate's husband, to assure him that \"he didn't have anything to worry about\". Tarantino stated: \"When it comes to Polanski, we're talking about a tragedy that would be unfathomable for most human beings.\"<ref name=Polanski-contacted>{{cite news |last=Sharf |first=Zack |url=https://www.indiewire.com/2019/07/roman-polanski-tarantino-once-upon-a-time-in-hollywood-talks-1202159276/ |title=Roman Polanski Contacted Tarantino With Questions About 'Once Upon a Time in Hollywood' |website=[[Indiewire]] |accessdate=August 17, 2019 |date=July 19, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190720130648/https://www.indiewire.com/2019/07/roman-polanski-tarantino-once-upon-a-time-in-hollywood-talks-1202159276/ |archive-date=July 20, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nDebra Tate, Sharon's sister, initially opposed the film, saying it was exploitative and perpetuated mistruths: \"To celebrate the killers and the darkest portion of society as being sexy or acceptable in any way, shape or form is just perpetuating the worst of our society.\"<ref name=\"debra-tate\"/> After Tarantino contacted her and showed her the script, she withdrew opposition, saying: \"This movie is not what people would expect it to be when you combine the Tarantino and Manson names.\" She felt that Tarantino was a \"very stand-up guy\"; after visiting the set, she was especially impressed with Robbie, and lent her some of Sharon's jewelry and perfume to wear in the film.<ref name=\"debra-tate\">{{cite news |url=https://www.bustle.com/p/what-does-sharon-tates-family-think-of-once-upon-a-time-in-hollywood-her-sister-has-spoken-out-18226104 |title=What Does Sharon Tate's Family Think Of 'Once Upon a Time in Hollywood'? Her Sister Had Spoken Out |last=Brayson |first=Johnny |accessdate=August 20, 2019 |website=[[Bustle (magazine)|Bustle]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190820153629/https://www.bustle.com/p/what-does-sharon-tates-family-think-of-once-upon-a-time-in-hollywood-her-sister-has-spoken-out-18226104 |archive-date=August 20, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nAfter the premiere, a journalist mentioned to Tarantino that Robbie had few lines. Tarantino responded: \"I reject your hypothesis.\" Robbie elaborated, \"I think the moments on screen show those wonderful sides of [Tate] could be adequately done without speaking.\"<ref>{{cite news |title=Quentin Tarantino Passes on Question About Screen Treatment of Margot Robbie |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/05/22/movies/quentin-tarantino-margot-robbie.html?smtyp=cur&smid=tw-nytimes |date=May 22, 2019 |first=Farah |last=Nayeri |newspaper=[[The New York Times]] |accessdate=August 22, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/2019/may/22/once-upon-a-time-in-hollywood-tarantino-lashes-out-at-criticism-over-female-actors |title='I reject your hypothesis': Tarantino lashes out at criticism over female actors |last=Mumford |first=Gwilym |date=May 22, 2019 |work=[[The Guardian]] |access-date=August 21, 2019 |issn=0261-3077 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190821233029/https://www.theguardian.com/film/2019/may/22/once-upon-a-time-in-hollywood-tarantino-lashes-out-at-criticism-over-female-actors |archive-date=August 21, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref> Tarantino stated: \"I thought it would both be touching and pleasurable and also sad and melancholy to just spend a little time with [Tate], just existing... I wanted you to see Sharon a lot.\"<ref name=Tarantino-Deadline-Interview/>\n\n=== The Manson Family ===\nCharles Manson was convicted of the murders of Tate and four others, despite not being present, due mostly to a theory stating he was trying to instigate an [[apocalypticism|apocalyptic]] race war, in the end leaving only black Muslims and the Manson Family. The black Muslims would eventually look to Manson to lead them. According to some, Manson referred to the race war as [[Helter Skelter (scenario)|Helter Skelter]], getting the name from the [[Helter Skelter (song)|song of the same name]].<ref name=helter-skelter/><ref name=watkins>{{cite book |last=Watkins |first=Paul and Guillermo Soledad |title=My Life With Charles Manson|publisher=Bantam |year=1979 |isbn=978-0-553-12788-1}}</ref> Musician and filmmaker [[Boots Riley]] criticized the film for not portraying Helter Skelter or depicting the Family as [[white supremacy|white supremacists]].<ref>{{cite web |last=Sharf |first=Zack |url=https://www.indiewire.com/2019/08/boots-riley-calls-out-tarantino-manson-family-white-supremacists-1202168736/ |title=Boots Riley Calls Out Tarantino's Hollywood for Not Depicting Manson Family as White Supremacists |website=[[IndieWire]] |access-date=August 30, 2019 |date=August 26, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190829013429/https://www.indiewire.com/2019/08/boots-riley-calls-out-tarantino-manson-family-white-supremacists-1202168736/ |archive-date=August 29, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nHowever, according to members of the Family, the murders were not committed to start Helter Skelter but as copycat murders of [[Gary Hinman]], to convince police his killer was still at large. Bobby Beausoleil was in jail, charged with the murder. The Family was attempting to get him released.<ref>{{cite news |last=Bardach |first=Ann Louise |url=http://www.bardachreports.com/articles/oa_19811100.htm |title=Jailhouse Interview: Bobby Beausoleil |access-date=August 26, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181119004534/http://www.bardachreports.com/articles/oa_19811100.htm |archive-date=November 19, 2018 |url-status=live}}</ref> According to Jay Sebring's protege and business partner [[Jim Markham]], the murders were about a drug deal gone bad, not a race war. He believes Manson was at Tate's house the day before the murders to sell drugs to Sebring and Voytek Frykowski, which resulted in the two beating Manson up.<ref>{{cite news |last=Siegel |first=Tatiana |url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/manson-family-murder-victims-friend-posits-alternative-motive-1227729 |title=Manson Victim's Friend Posits Alternative Motive: 'I Never Bought Into the Race War Theory' |website=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|access-date=August 29, 2019 |date=July 30, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190731034053/https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/manson-family-murder-victims-friend-posits-alternative-motive-1227729 |archive-date=July 31, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref> In his interview with [[Truman Capote]], Beausoleil said, \"They burned people on dope deals. Sharon Tate and that gang.\"<ref>{{cite book |last=Capote |first=Truman |title=A Capote Reader |publisher=[[Random House]]|year=1987 |isbn=978-0-394-55647-5 |url-access=registration |url=https://archive.org/details/capotereader00trum }}</ref>\n\n== ''Bounty Law'' ==\nIn January 2020, Tarantino confirmed that he is creating a real television series titled ''Bounty Law'',<ref name=\":0\"/><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.gq.com.au/entertainment/film-tv/quentin-tarantino-plans-to-turn-fictional-western-bounty-law-into-a-real-series/news-story/a2e81c7d1d29df7e5782eb19e1f2d87b|title=Quentin Tarantino Plans To Turn Fictional Western Bounty Law Into A Real Series|last=Nash|first=Brad|date=2020-01-21|website=GQ|language=en|access-date=2020-02-13}}</ref> stating he has already written five episodes and will direct them.<ref>{{Citation|title=Quentin Tarantino Will Write and Direct Once Upon a Time in Hollywood Spin-Off TV Series Bounty Law - IGN|url=https://www.ign.com/articles/quentin-tarantino-will-write-and-direct-once-upon-a-time-in-hollywood-spin-off-tv-series-bounty-law|language=en|access-date=2020-02-13}}</ref>\n\n== Notes ==\n{{Notelist}}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|refs=\n\n<ref name=FirsReportedTHR>{{cite news |last1=Kit |first1=Borys |title=Quentin Tarantino Prepping New Movie Tackling Manson Murders (Exclusive) |url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/heat-vision/quentin-tarantino-prepping-new-movie-tackling-manson-murders-1020165 |accessdate=July 12, 2017 |website=[[The Hollywood Reporter]] |date=July 11, 2017 |language=en|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170712024235/http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/heat-vision/quentin-tarantino-prepping-new-movie-tackling-manson-murders-1020165|archive-date=July 12, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=FirsReportedDeadline>{{cite news |last1=Fleming Jr. |first1=Mike|title=Quentin Tarantino Met With Margot Robbie For Sharon Tate: Sources |url=https://deadline.com/2017/07/quentin-tarantino-margot-robbie-sharon-tate-manson-murders-brad-pitt-1202127045/ |accessdate=July 12, 2017 |website=[[Deadline Hollywood]] |date=July 11, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170712165131/http://deadline.com/2017/07/quentin-tarantino-margot-robbie-sharon-tate-manson-murders-brad-pitt-1202127045/|archive-date=July 12, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"HeymanProducer\">{{cite news |last1=Jr |first1=Mike Fleming |title=Bidding Heats on Quentin Tarantino Script As David Heyman Boards As Producer |url=https://deadline.com/2017/11/quentin-tarantino-movie-bidding-david-heyman-producer-margot-robbie-tom-cruise-brad-pitt-leonaro-dicaprio-1202208169/ |accessdate=November 15, 2017 |website=[[Deadline Hollywood]] |date=November 14, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171114232804/http://deadline.com/2017/11/quentin-tarantino-movie-bidding-david-heyman-producer-margot-robbie-tom-cruise-brad-pitt-leonaro-dicaprio-1202208169/|archive-date=November 14, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"Archive footage\">{{cite web |last=Fretts |first=Bruce |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/07/30/movies/once-upon-a-time-in-hollywood-glossary.html |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190731040507/https://www.nytimes.com/2019/07/30/movies/once-upon-a-time-in-hollywood-glossary.html |title=A Pop-Culture Glossary for 'Once Upon a Time ... in Hollywood' |website=[[The New York Times]] |date=July 30, 2019 |archivedate=July 31, 2019 |accessdate=August 2, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"True story characters\">{{cite web |url=https://www.vulture.com/2019/08/the-true-story-of-once-upon-a-time-in-hollywood-characters.html |title=Who's Who in Once Upon a Time in Hollywood: A Character Guide |last=Alter |first=Rebecca |date=August 2, 2019 |website=[[New York (magazine)#Digital expansion and blogs|Vulture]] |access-date= |quote=|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190802193255/https://www.vulture.com/2019/08/the-true-story-of-once-upon-a-time-in-hollywood-characters.html |archive-date=August 2, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{wikiquote}}\n* {{official website}}\n* {{IMDb title|7131622}}\n\n{{Quentin Tarantino}}\n{{Navboxes\n|title = [[List of accolades received by Once Upon a Time in Hollywood|Awards for ''Once Upon a Time in Hollywood'']]\n|list =\n{{Broadcast Film Critics Association Award for Best Film}}\n{{Golden Globe Award Best Motion Picture Musical or Comedy}}\n{{Satellite Award Best Motion Picture}}\n}}\n{{Manson Family}}\n\n[[Category:2019 films]]\n[[Category:2010s serial killer films]]\n[[Category:2010s comedy-drama films]]\n[[Category:American films]]\n[[Category:American alternate history films]]\n[[Category:American black comedy films]]\n[[Category:American comedy-drama films]]\n[[Category:BAFTA winners (films)]]\n[[Category:Best Musical or Comedy Picture Golden Globe winners]]\n[[Category:Bipolar disorder in fiction]]\n[[Category:British films]]\n[[Category:British alternative history films]]\n[[Category:British black comedy films]]\n[[Category:British comedy-drama films]]\n[[Category:Columbia Pictures films]]\n[[Category:Cultural depictions of actors]]\n[[Category:Cultural depictions of Bruce Lee]]\n[[Category:Cultural depictions of Charles Manson]]\n[[Category:English-language films]]\n[[Category:Films about actors]]\n[[Category:Films about cults]]\n[[Category:Films about Hollywood]]\n[[Category:Films about stunt performers]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Quentin Tarantino]]\n[[Category:Films featuring a Best Supporting Actor Academy Award-winning performance]]\n[[Category:Films featuring a Best Supporting Actor Golden Globe winning performance]]\n[[Category:Films produced by Quentin Tarantino]]\n[[Category:Films set in 1969]]\n[[Category:Films set in Los Angeles]]\n[[Category:Films shot in Los Angeles]]\n[[Category:Heyday Films films]]\n[[Category:Films with screenplays by Quentin Tarantino]]\n[[Category:Films whose art director won the Best Art Direction Academy Award]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|2019 film by Quentin Tarantino}}\n{{Use American English|date=October 2019}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=October 2019}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = Once Upon a Time in Hollywood\n| image          = Once Upon a Time in Hollywood poster.png\n| border         = no\n| caption        = Theatrical release poster\n| director       = [[Quentin Tarantino]]\n| producer       = {{Plainlist|\n* [[David Heyman]]\n* [[Shannon McIntosh (filmmaker)|Shannon McIntosh]]\n* Quentin Tarantino\n}}\n| writer         = Quentin Tarantino\n| starring       = <!--PER BILLING BLOCK-->{{Plainlist|\n* [[Leonardo DiCaprio]]\n* [[Brad Pitt]]\n* [[Margot Robbie]]\n* [[Emile Hirsch]]\n* [[Margaret Qualley]]\n* [[Timothy Olyphant]]\n* [[Austin Butler]]\n* [[Dakota Fanning]]\n* [[Bruce Dern]]\n* [[Al Pacino]]<!--DO NOT ADD ADDITIONAL NAMES-->\n}}\n| cinematography = [[Robert Richardson (cinematographer)|Robert Richardson]]\n| editing        = [[Fred Raskin]]\n| production companies = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Columbia Pictures]]\n* [[Polybona Films|Bona Film Group]]\n* [[Heyday Films]]\n* Visiona Romantica\n}}\n| distributor    = [[Sony Pictures Releasing]]\n| released       = {{Film date|2019|5|21|[[2019 Cannes Film Festival|Cannes]]|2019|7|26|United States|2019|8|14|United Kingdom}}\n| runtime        = 161 minutes<ref>{{cite web |url=https://bbfc.co.uk/releases/once-upon-time-hollywood-2019 |title=ONCE UPON A TIME IN HOLLYWOOD (18) |website=[[British Board of Film Classification]] |date=July 11, 2019 |accessdate=July 15, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190711130452/https://bbfc.co.uk/releases/once-upon-time-hollywood-2019 |archive-date=July 11, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n| country        = {{Plainlist|\n* United States\n* United Kingdom\n* China<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bfi.org.uk/films-tv-people/5da789ea829e2|title=Once Upon a Time\u2026 in Hollywood (2019)|publisher=[[British Film Institute]]|access-date=February 26, 2020}}</ref>\n}}\n| language       = English\n| budget         = $90\u201396 million<ref name=\"opening\"/>\n| gross          = $374.3 million<ref name=\"BOM\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=untitledtarantino.htm |title=Once Upon a Time in Hollywood (2019) |website=[[Box Office Mojo]] |publisher=[[IMDb]] |access-date=February 14, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190830125636/https://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=untitledtarantino.htm |archive-date=August 30, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n}}\n\n'''''Once Upon a Time in Hollywood'''''{{efn|name=stylized|Stylized onscreen as '''''Once Upon a Time...in Hollywood''''' and in promotional materials as '''''Once Upon a Time in... Hollywood'''''}} is a 2019 <!-- DO NOT ADD OR CHANGE MORE GENRES. The film is a comedy drama film. Not crime, action or more so. Period Drama doesn't count from the reason it's an alternative history --> [[comedy-drama]] film written and directed by [[Quentin Tarantino]]. Produced by [[Columbia Pictures]], [[Bona Film Group]], [[Heyday Films]], and Visiona Romantica and distributed by [[Sony Pictures Releasing]], it is a co-production between the United States, United Kingdom and China. It features a large [[ensemble cast]] led by [[Leonardo DiCaprio]], [[Brad Pitt]], and [[Margot Robbie]]. Set in 1969 Los Angeles, the film follows an actor and his stunt double, as they navigate the changing film industry, and features \"multiple storylines in a modern fairy tale tribute to the final moments of [[Classical Hollywood cinema|Hollywood's golden age]].\"<ref name=\"synopis\">{{cite news |title=Once Upon a Time In... Hollywood Movie Synopsis {{!}} Official Website {{!}} Sony Pictures |url=https://www.onceuponatimeinhollywood.movie/synopsis/ |accessdate=March 22, 2019 |work=Once Upon a Time In... Hollywood |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190322054919/https://www.onceuponatimeinhollywood.movie/synopsis/ |archive-date=March 22, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Olson |first1=Matthew |url=http://digg.com/2019/once-upon-a-time-in-hollywood-reviews-is-it-good-tarantino-dicaprio-robbie-pitt |title=Does Quentin Tarantino's 'Once Upon A Time In Hollywood' Live Up To The Hype? Here's What Critics Say |publisher=Digg.com |accessdate=July 25, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190724215302/http://digg.com/2019/once-upon-a-time-in-hollywood-reviews-is-it-good-tarantino-dicaprio-robbie-pitt |archive-date=July 24, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.vanityfair.com/hollywood/2017/11/quentin-tarantino-harvey-weinstein-sony-manson-movie |title=Quentin Tarantino Is Ditching Weinstein for Sony |last=Sperling |first=Nicole |date=November 17, 2017 |website=[[Vanity Fair (magazine)|Vanity Fair]] |accessdate=June 18, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180225160449/https://www.vanityfair.com/hollywood/2017/11/quentin-tarantino-harvey-weinstein-sony-manson-movie|archive-date=February 25, 2018}}</ref>\n\nAnnounced in July 2017, it is the first Tarantino film to not involve [[Bob Weinstein|Bob]] and [[Harvey Weinstein]], as Tarantino ended his partnership with the brothers following the [[Harvey Weinstein sexual abuse cases|sexual abuse allegations against the latter]]. After a bidding war, the film was distributed by [[Sony Pictures]], which met Tarantino's demands including [[final cut privilege]]. Pitt, DiCaprio, Robbie, [[Zo\u00eb Bell]], [[Kurt Russell]], and others joined the cast between January and June 2018. [[Principal photography]] lasted from June through November around Los Angeles. It is the last film to feature [[Luke Perry]], who died in March 2019.\n\n''Once Upon a Time in Hollywood'' premiered at the [[2019 Cannes Film Festival|Cannes Film Festival]] on May 21, 2019, and was theatrically released in the United States on July 26, 2019 and in the United Kingdom on August 14. The film has grossed $374 million worldwide and received praise from critics for Tarantino's screenplay and direction, acting, cinematography, costume design, production values, and soundtrack, though it received criticism for its pacing and running time. Among its [[List of accolades received by Once Upon a Time in Hollywood|various accolades]], the film was chosen by the [[American Film Institute]] and the [[National Board of Review]] as one of the top ten films of the year. It received 10 nominations at the [[92nd Academy Awards]], including [[Academy Award for Best Picture|Best Picture]], and won [[Academy Award for Best Supporting Actor|Best Supporting Actor]] (Pitt) and [[Academy Award for Best Production Design|Best Production Design]]. It also won [[Golden Globe Award for Best Motion Picture \u2013 Musical or Comedy|Best Motion Picture \u2013 Musical or Comedy]] at the [[77th Golden Globe Awards]].\n\nA television series of ''Bounty Law'' depicted in the film is being developed by Tarantino, who has written five episodes of the series.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.esquireme.com/content/42823-quentin-tarantino-is-making-a-real-life-bounty-law-tv-show|title=Quentin Tarantino is making a real-life bounty law TV show|website=Esquire Middle East|language=en|access-date=2020-02-13}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.gq.com.au/entertainment/film-tv/quentin-tarantino-plans-to-turn-fictional-western-bounty-law-into-a-real-series/news-story/a2e81c7d1d29df7e5782eb19e1f2d87b|title=Quentin Tarantino Plans To Turn Fictional Western Bounty Law Into A Real Series|last=Nash|first=Brad|date=2020-01-21|website=GQ|language=en|access-date=2020-02-13}}</ref>\n\n== Plot ==\n<!-- Per WP:FILMPLOT, plot summaries for feature films should be between 400 to 700 words only. -->\nIn February 1969, veteran [[Cinema of the United States|Hollywood]] actor Rick Dalton (DiCaprio), star of 1950s [[Western (genre)|Western]] television series ''Bounty Law'', fears his career is waning. Casting agent Marvin Schwarz (Pacino) recommends he make [[Spaghetti Western]]s in Italy, which Dalton feels are beneath him. Dalton's best friend and [[stunt double]], Cliff Booth (Pitt)\u2014a war [[veteran]] skilled in hand-to-hand combat<ref>{{citation |title=Quentin Tarantino defends Bruce Lee scene in 'Once Upon a Time in Hollywood' |url=https://us.blastingnews.com/showbiz-tv/2019/08/quentin-tarantino-defends-bruce-lee-scene-in-once-upon-a-time-in-hollywood-002965405.html |accessdate=January 6, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191104220815/https://us.blastingnews.com/showbiz-tv/2019/08/quentin-tarantino-defends-bruce-lee-scene-in-once-upon-a-time-in-hollywood-002965405.html |archive-date=November 4, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> who lives in a tiny trailer with his [[pit bull]], Brandy\u2014drives Dalton around Los Angeles because Dalton's driver's license has been suspended due to [[DUI]]. Booth struggles to find stunt work in Hollywood because of rumors he murdered his wife. Actress [[Sharon Tate]] (Robbie) and her husband, director [[Roman Polanski]] (Zawierucha), have moved [[10050 Cielo Drive|next door to Dalton]]. He dreams of befriending them to revive his declining acting career. That night, Tate and Polanski attend a celebrity-filled party at the [[Playboy Mansion]].\n\nThe next day, while repairing Dalton's TV antenna, Booth reminisces about a [[sparring]] contest he had with [[Bruce Lee]] on the set of ''[[The Green Hornet (TV series)|The Green Hornet]]'' which resulted in Booth being fired. Meanwhile, [[Charles Manson]] (Herriman) stops by the Polanski residence looking for [[Record producer|music producer]] [[Terry Melcher]], who used to live there, but is turned away by [[Jay Sebring]] (Hirsch). Tate goes out for errands and stops at a movie theater to watch herself in the film ''[[The Wrecking Crew (1968 film)|The Wrecking Crew]]''.\n\nDalton is cast to play the villain in the pilot of ''[[Lancer (TV series)|Lancer]]'', and strikes up a conversation with his eight-year-old co-star, Trudi Fraser. Dalton struggles to remember his lines and later suffers a breakdown in his trailer. He subsequently delivers a performance that impresses Fraser and the director, [[Sam Wanamaker]], bolstering his confidence. \n\nWhile driving Dalton's car, Booth picks up a female hitchhiker named Pussycat, whom he takes to [[Spahn Ranch]], where Booth once worked on the set of ''Bounty Law.'' He takes notice of the many [[hippie]]s living there (the [[Manson Family]]). Suspecting they may be taking advantage of the ranch's owner, [[George Spahn]] (Dern), Booth insists on checking on him despite [[Lynette Fromme|\"Squeaky\" Fromme]]'s (Fanning) objections. Booth finally speaks with Spahn, who dismisses his concerns. Upon leaving, Booth discovers that [[Steve \"Clem\" Grogan]] has slashed a tire on Dalton's car; Booth beats him and forces him to change the tire. [[Tex Watson]] is summoned to deal with the situation but he arrives as Booth is driving away.\n\nAfter watching Dalton's guest performance on an episode of ''[[The F.B.I. (TV series)|The F.B.I.]]'', Schwarz books him as the lead in [[Sergio Corbucci]]'s next Spaghetti Western, ''Nebraska Jim''. Dalton takes Booth with him for a six-month stint in Italy, during which he appears in two additional Westerns and a [[Eurospy film|Eurospy]] comedy, and marries Italian starlet Francesca Capucci. With a new wife, Dalton informs Booth he can no longer afford his services.\n\nOn the evening of August 8, 1969, their first day back in Los Angeles, Dalton and Booth go out for drinks to commemorate their time working together and then return to Dalton's house. Tate and Sebring go out for dinner with friends and then return to Tate's house. Booth smokes an [[Lysergic acid diethylamide|acid]]-laced cigarette given to him by Pussycat and takes Brandy for a walk while Dalton prepares drinks. Manson Family members Tex, [[Susan Atkins|Sadie]], [[Linda Kasabian|Flower Child]], and [[Patricia Krenwinkel|Katie]] arrive outside in preparation to [[Tate\u2013LaBianca murders|murder everyone in Tate's house]]. Dalton hears the car and orders them to get off his street. [[Alternate history|Changing their plans]], the Manson Family members decide to instead kill Dalton after Sadie reasons that Hollywood has \"taught them to murder.\" Flower Child deserts the group, speeding off with their car. They break into Dalton's house and confront Capucci and Booth, who recognizes them from his visit to Spahn Ranch. Booth orders Brandy to attack, and together they kill Katie and Tex and injure Sadie, though Booth is stabbed and knocked unconscious in the altercation. Sadie stumbles outside, alarming Dalton, who is in his pool listening to music on headphones, oblivious to the mayhem. Dalton retrieves a flamethrower that he had previously used in a movie and incinerates Sadie. After Booth is taken to the hospital to treat his injuries, Sebring engages Dalton in conversation outside and Dalton receives an invitation to have a drink with Tate and her friends at her house, which he accepts.\n\n== Cast ==\n{{cast list|\n* [[Leonardo DiCaprio]] as Rick Dalton\n* [[Brad Pitt]] as Cliff Booth\n* [[Margot Robbie]] as [[Sharon Tate]]\n* [[Emile Hirsch]] as [[Jay Sebring]]\n* [[Margaret Qualley]] as \"Pussycat\"\n* [[Timothy Olyphant]] as [[James Stacy]]\n* [[Julia Butters]] as Trudi Fraser\n* [[Austin Butler]] as \"[[Tex Watson|Tex]]\"\n* [[Dakota Fanning]] as \"[[Lynette Fromme|Squeaky]]\"\n* [[Bruce Dern]] as [[George Spahn]]\n* [[Mike Moh]] as [[Bruce Lee]]\n* [[Luke Perry]] as [[Wayne Maunder]]\n* [[Damian Lewis]] as [[Steve McQueen]]\n* [[Al Pacino]] as Marvin Schwarz\n* [[Nicholas Hammond]] as [[Sam Wanamaker]]\n* [[Samantha Robinson (American actress)|Samantha Robinson]] as [[Abigail Folger]]\n* [[Rafa\u0142 Zawierucha]] as [[Roman Polanski]]\n* [[Lorenza Izzo]] as Francesca Capucci\n* [[Costa Ronin]] as [[Wojciech Frykowski]]\n* [[Damon Herriman]] as [[Charles Manson|Charlie]]\n* [[Lena Dunham]] as \"[[Catherine Share|Gypsy]]\"\n* [[Madisen Beaty]] as \"[[Patricia Krenwinkel|Katie]]\"\n* [[Mikey Madison]] as \"[[Susan Atkins|Sadie]]\"\n* James Landry H\u00e9bert as \"[[Steve \"Clem\" Grogan|Clem]]\"\n* [[Maya Hawke]] as \"[[Linda Kasabian|Flower Child]]\"\n* [[Victoria Pedretti]] as \"[[Leslie Van Houten|Lulu]]\"\n* [[Sydney Sweeney]] as \"[[:de:Diane Lake|Snake]]\"\n* [[Harley Quinn Smith]] as \"Froggie\"\n* Dallas Jay Hunter as \"Delilah\"\n* [[Kansas Bowling]] as \"[[Sandra Good|Blue]]\"\n* Parker Love Bowling as \"Tadpole\"\n* Cassidy Vick Hice as \"Sundance\"\n* Ruby Rose Skotchdopole as \"Butterfly\"\n* [[Danielle Harris]] as \"Angel\"\n* Josephine Valentina Clark as \"Happy Cappy\"\n* [[Scoot McNairy]] as \"Business\" Bob Gilbert on ''[[Lancer (TV series)|Lancer]]''\n* [[Clifton Collins Jr.]] as Ernesto \"The Mexican\" Vaquero on ''Lancer''\n* [[Marco Rodr\u00edguez (actor)|Marco Rodr\u00edguez]] as the [[bartender]] on ''Lancer''\n* [[Ram\u00f3n Franco (actor)|Ram\u00f3n Franco]] as a Land Pirate on ''Lancer'' and Rub\u00e9n, the [[Bruin Theater]] manager\n* Raul Cardona as \"Bad Guy\" Delgado on ''Lancer''\n* Courtney Hoffman as Rebekka\n* [[Dreama Walker]] as [[Connie Stevens]]\n* Rachel Redleaf as [[Cass Elliot|Mama Cass]]\n* [[Rebecca Rittenhouse]] as [[Michelle Phillips]]\n* [[Rumer Willis]] as [[Joanna Pettet]]\n* [[Spencer Garrett]] as Allen Kincade\n* [[Clu Gulager]] as the Larry Edmunds Bookshop owner\n* [[Martin Kove]] as a ''Bounty Law'' Sheriff\n* [[Rebecca Gayheart]] as Billie Booth\n* [[Kurt Russell]] as Randy Miller and the narrator\n* [[Zo\u00eb Bell]] as Janet Miller\n* [[Michael Madsen]] as Sheriff Hackett on ''Bounty Law''\n* [[Perla Haney-Jardine]] as a hippie drug dealer\n* [[James Remar]] as \"Ugly Owl\" Hoot on ''Bounty Law''\n* [[Monica Staggs]] as Connie\n* [[Omar Doom]] as Donnie\n* [[Kate Berlant]] as the Bruin Theater ticket booth attendant\n* [[Brenda Vaccaro]] as Mary Alice Schwarz\n* [[Daniella Pick]] as Daphna Ben-Cobo\n* Tom Hartig as [[Altamont Free Concert|Bill \"Sweet William\" Fritsch]]\n* [[David Steen (actor)|David Steen]] as Straight Satan David\n* [[Corey Burton]] as the ''Bounty Law'' promo announcer\n* [[Toni Basil]] as a dancer on the plane during the opening credits sequence<ref name=toni-basil>{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/08/06/arts/dance/once-upon-a-time-in-hollywood-tarantino-toni-basil.html |title=Quentin Tarantino's Goddess of Go-Go |first=Debra |last=Levine |work=[[The New York Times]] |date=August 6, 2019 |accessdate=August 6, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190806163003/https://www.nytimes.com/2019/08/06/arts/dance/once-upon-a-time-in-hollywood-tarantino-toni-basil.html |archive-date=August 6, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n* Rage Stewart as [[KHJ (AM)|Harvey \"Humble Harve\" Miller]]\n* [[Quentin Tarantino]] as the offscreen director of the Red Apple cigarettes TV commercial. He can be heard announcing the title of ''Bounty Law''.<ref>{{cite web |last=Rybov |first=Eugene |url=https://invidious.13ad.de/watch?v=Ec5em1mqJtQ |title=Special interview with Quentin Tarantino for OK about 'Once Upon a Time in Hollywood' |website=invidious |access-date=August 26, 2019 |date=August 11, 2019}}</ref>\n* [[Maurice Compte]], [[Vincent Laresca]], [[Lew Temple]], Craig Stark, [[JLouis Mills]], Eddie Perez, Gilbert Saldivar, and Keith Jefferson as the other Land Pirates on ''Lancer''.\n* [[James Marsden]] as [[Burt Reynolds]] (extended release)\n* [[Walton Goggins]] as the voice of Old Chattanooga Beer (extended release)\n}}\n\n== Character background ==\n=== Fictional characters ===\nRick Dalton is an actor who starred in the fictitious [[Westerns on television|television western]] series ''Bounty Law'', based on the real-life series ''[[Wanted Dead or Alive (TV series)|Wanted Dead or Alive]],'' starring [[Steve McQueen]].<ref name=\"Bounty Law Wasnt a Real TV Show\">{{cite news |last=Lachenal |first=Jessica |url=https://www.bustle.com/p/bounty-law-wasnt-a-real-tv-show-but-once-upon-a-time-in-hollywood-borrowed-from-this-classic-series-18180457 |title=\"Bounty Law\" Wasn't A Real TV Show, But 'Once Upon A Time In Hollywood' Borrowed From This Classic Series |work=[[Bustle (magazine)|Bustle]] |access-date=August 11, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190812040954/https://www.bustle.com/p/bounty-law-wasnt-a-real-tv-show-but-once-upon-a-time-in-hollywood-borrowed-from-this-classic-series-18180457 |archive-date=August 12, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref> Dalton's relationship with Cliff Booth is based on [[Burt Reynolds]]' with his longtime [[stunt double]] [[Hal Needham]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Langmann |first=Brady |url=https://www.esquire.com/entertainment/movies/a28504994/brad-pitt-once-upon-a-time-in-hollywood-character-true-story-stuntman-hal-needham/ |title=The Stuntman Who Inspired Brad Pitt's ''Once Upon a Time in Hollywood'' Character Is More Badass In Real Life |work=[[Esquire (magazine)|Esquire]] |date=July 25, 2019 |accessdate=July 26, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190727174410/https://www.esquire.com/entertainment/movies/a28504994/brad-pitt-once-upon-a-time-in-hollywood-character-true-story-stuntman-hal-needham/ |archive-date=July 27, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref> Dalton was inspired by actors whose careers began in [[Classical Hollywood cinema|Classical Hollywood]] but faltered in the 1960s, such as [[Ty Hardin|Ty Hardin,]] who went from starring in a successful TV western to making [[Spaghetti Western|spaghetti westerns]], as well as by [[Ralph Meeker]].<ref>{{cite podcast|url=http://thenewbev.com/blog/2019/07/pure-cinema-podcast-july-2019-with-quentin-tarantino/|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190722142805/http://thenewbev.com/blog/2019/07/pure-cinema-podcast-july-2019-with-quentin-tarantino/ |archivedate=July 22, 2019|date=July 3, 2019|website=Pure Cinema Podcast|title=New Beverly Calendar: July, 2019 (with Quentin Tarantino)|publisher=The New Bev|minutes=13}}</ref><ref name=\"True story characters\"/><ref name=recut>{{cite web |last=Thompson |first=May |url=https://www.indiewire.com/2019/05/quentin-tarantino-once-upon-a-time-in-hollywood-recut-longer-cannes-1202143936/ |title=Quentin Tarantino Says He May Recut 'Once Upon a Time in Hollywood' to Make it Longer |website=[[IndieWire]] |access-date=September 9, 2019 |date=May 23, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190529175013/https://www.indiewire.com/2019/05/quentin-tarantino-once-upon-a-time-in-hollywood-recut-longer-cannes-1202143936/ |archive-date=May 29, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=Meeker>{{cite news |last=Hellerman |first=Jason |url=https://nofilmschool.com/Tarantino-breakdowns-character |title=How Tarantino and DiCaprio Crafted his 'Hollywood' Character |website=nofilmschool |access-date=August 28, 2019 |date=August 2, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190829012156/https://nofilmschool.com/Tarantino-breakdowns-character |archive-date=August 29, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref> Though not mentioned in the film, Dalton apparently suffers from undiagnosed [[bipolar disorder]], inspired by [[Pete Duel]].<ref name=Bipolar>{{cite news |last=Galbraith |first=Alex |url=https://www.complex.com/pop-culture/2019/08/rick-dalton-once-upon-a-time-in-hollywood-quentin-tarantino-bipolar |title=Tarantino on DiCaprio's 'OUATIH' Character Rick Dalton Being Bipolar: 'We Never Say the Words' |website=Complex |access-date=August 19, 2019 |date=August 1, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190819155028/https://www.complex.com/pop-culture/2019/08/rick-dalton-once-upon-a-time-in-hollywood-quentin-tarantino-bipolar |archive-date=August 19, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nCliff Booth, Dalton's stunt double and best friend, is a [[World War II]] veteran, [[Green Berets|Green Beret]] and \"one of deadliest guys alive.\"<ref name=\"character-details\">{{cite news |last=Sharf |first=Zack |url=https://www.indiewire.com/2019/04/quentin-tarantino-details-once-upon-a-time-in-hollywood-characters-1202060562/ |title=Quentin Tarantino Drops New Details About His 'Once Upon a Time in Hollywood' Characters |website=[[Indiewire]] |access-date=August 15, 2019 |date=April 19, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190426032417/https://www.indiewire.com/2019/04/quentin-tarantino-details-once-upon-a-time-in-hollywood-characters-1202060562/ |archive-date=April 26, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"Brad-Pitt-Fight-Ready\">{{cite news |last=Thorp |first=Charlie |url=https://www.msn.com/en-us/health/agingwell/how-brad-pitt-got-fight-ready-for-once-upon-a-time-in-hollywood/ar-AAENYaD |title=How Brad Pitt Got Fight Ready For 'Once Upon a Time in Hollywood' |website=[[Men's Journal]] |access-date=August 15, 2019 |date=July 24, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190811031736/https://www.msn.com/en-us/health/agingwell/how-brad-pitt-got-fight-ready-for-once-upon-a-time-in-hollywood/ar-AAENYaD |archive-date=August 11, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref> [[Quentin Tarantino]] and [[Brad Pitt]] modeled Booth after [[Tom Laughlin]]'s portrayal of [[Billy Jack]].<ref name=\"Crazy Coincidence\">{{cite news |last=Sharf |first=Zack |url=https://www.indiewire.com/2019/07/quentin-tarantino-brad-pitt-coincidence-hollywood-meeting-1202156536/ |title=The Crazy Coincidence that Brought Tarantino and Brad Pitt back together for 'Hollywood' |website=[[IndieWire]] |access-date=August 11, 2019 |date=July 9, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190720172844/https://www.indiewire.com/2019/07/quentin-tarantino-brad-pitt-coincidence-hollywood-meeting-1202156536/ |archive-date=July 20, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref> Booth is inspired by [[Gary Kent]], a stuntman for a film made at the [[Spahn Ranch]] while the [[Manson Family]] lived there,<ref name=\"Meet the Stuntman\">{{cite news |last=Orange |first=B. Alan |url=https://www.movieweb.com/danger-god-trailer/ |title=Danger God Trailer: Meet the Stuntman Who Helped Inspire Tarantino's Once Upon a Time |work=Movieweb |access-date=August 11, 2019 |date=August 6, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190812001613/https://movieweb.com/danger-god-trailer/ |archive-date=August 12, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref> and [[Gene LeBell]], who worked on [[The Green Hornet (TV series)|''The Green Hornet'']] after complaints by other stuntmen that [[Bruce Lee]] was \"kicking the shit out of the stuntmen.\"<ref name=\"Debunking Mockery\">{{cite news |last=Robinson |first=Eugene S. |url=https://www.ozy.com/true/story/debunking-quentin-tarantinos-mockery-of-bruce-lee/95956 |title=Debunking Quentin Tarantino's 'Mockery' of Bruce Lee |work=[[Ozy (magazine)|Ozy]] |access-date=August 11, 2019 |date=August 9, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190812002649/https://www.ozy.com/true/story/debunking-quentin-tarantinos-mockery-of-bruce-lee/95956 |archive-date=August 12, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nTrudi Fraser, the precocious child actor working on ''[[Lancer (TV series)|Lancer]]'', is inspired by an actual character from that series.<ref name=gamespot-easter-eggs>{{cite news |last=Rougeau |first=Michael |url=https://www.gamespot.com/gallery/once-upon-a-time-in-hollywood-42-easter-eggs-and-r/2900-2951/ |title=Once Upon A Time In Hollywood: 42 Easter Eggs & References You Might Have Missed |website=[[GameSpot]] |access-date=August 21, 2019 |date=July 31, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190822002658/https://www.gamespot.com/gallery/once-upon-a-time-in-hollywood-42-easter-eggs-and-r/2900-2951/ |archive-date=August 22, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref><!-- She was not inspired by [[Meryl Streep]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.vanityfair.com/hollywood/2019/07/once-upon-a-time-in-hollywood-julia-butters-interview |title=Once Upon a Time...in Hollywood: Meet the 10-Year-Old Leo Compared to a Young Meryl Streep |work=Vanity Fair}}</ref> --> Marvin Schwarz is Dalton's agent, a role that Tarantino wrote specifically for [[Al Pacino]].<ref name=al-pacino>{{cite news |last=Collis |first=Clark |url=https://ew.com/movies/2019/07/26/once-upon-a-time-in-hollywood-quentin-tarantino-al-pacino/ |title=Quentin Tarantino was \"nervous\" about directing Al Pacino in Once Upon a Time in Hollywood |website=[[Entertainment Weekly]] |access-date=August 25, 2019 |date=July 26, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190729035225/https://ew.com/movies/2019/07/26/once-upon-a-time-in-hollywood-quentin-tarantino-al-pacino/ |archive-date=July 29, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref> Francesca Capucci, a starlet who marries Dalton, is influenced by 1960s Italian actresses [[Sophia Loren]] and [[Claudia Cardinale]].<ref name=\"True story characters\"/><ref name=\"lorenza izzo talks\">{{cite web |url=https://www.nbcnews.com/news/latino/lorenza-izzo-talks-cross-cultural-connections-once-upon-time-hollywood-n1034561 |title=Lorenza Izzo talks cross-cultural connections in 'Once Upon A Time ... In Hollywood' |last=Conde |first=Arturo |date=July 26, 2019 |website=[[NBC News]] |access-date=August 11, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190806075706/https://www.nbcnews.com/news/latino/lorenza-izzo-talks-cross-cultural-connections-once-upon-time-hollywood-n1034561 |archive-date=August 6, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref> Billie Booth is Cliff's wife, whose death echoes [[Natalie Wood]]'s.<ref name=\"True story characters\"/> Some roles, such as [[Zo\u00eb Bell]]'s stunt coordinator and Heba Thorisdottir's makeup artist, were portrayed by individuals who performed those jobs for the film.\n\n=== Historical characters ===\n*[[File:Sharon Tate Valley of the Dolls 1967.jpg|thumb|upright|[[Sharon Tate]], portrayed in the film by [[Margot Robbie]] and shown in a publicity photo from ''[[The Wrecking Crew (1968 film)|The Wrecking Crew]]'' (1968)|alt=]][[Sharon Tate]] was an actress married to film director [[Roman Polanski]], and is Dalton's neighbor in the film. [[Margot Robbie]] read Polanski's autobiography ''Roman by Polanski'' in preparation for the role.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Sharf |first=Zack |title=Margot Robbie Didn't Consult Roman Polanski for Her Portrayal of Sharon Tate |work=[[IndieWire]] |date=December 3, 2018 |accessdate=January 6, 2019 |url=https://www.indiewire.com/2018/12/margot-robbie-sharon-tate-prep-once-upon-a-time-in-hollywood-tarantino-1202024791/|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181205193423/https://www.indiewire.com/2018/12/margot-robbie-sharon-tate-prep-once-upon-a-time-in-hollywood-tarantino-1202024791/|archive-date=December 5, 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"Filmoria\">{{cite web |url=https://www.filmoria.co.uk/once-upon-a-time-in-hollywood-the-9th-film-from-quentin-tarantino-brand-new-poster/ |title=Margot Robbie as Sharon Tate in Quentin Tarantino's Once Upon A Time... in Hollywood. |website=Filmoria |date= |accessdate=March 20, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190322180023/https://www.filmoria.co.uk/once-upon-a-time-in-hollywood-the-9th-film-from-quentin-tarantino-brand-new-poster/|archive-date=March 22, 2019}}</ref> Polanski's credits include ''[[Rosemary's Baby (film)|Rosemary's Baby]]'' and ''[[The Fearless Vampire Killers]]'', where he first met Tate.<ref>{{cite news |last=Alter |first=Ethan |url=https://www.yahoo.com/entertainment/once-upon-a-time-in-hollywood-whats-real-and-fake-sharon-tate-bruce-lee-charlie-manson-230411013.html |title=From Sharon Tate and Bruce Lee to Rick Dalton and Cliff Booth, here's what's real and what's fake in 'Once Upon a Time in Hollywood' |website=Yahoo |access-date=August 29, 2019 |date=July 26, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190829020022/https://www.yahoo.com/entertainment/once-upon-a-time-in-hollywood-whats-real-and-fake-sharon-tate-bruce-lee-charlie-manson-230411013.html |archive-date=August 29, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n*[[Jay Sebring]] was Tate's friend and ex-boyfriend, and friend of Bruce Lee (whom he had helped get started in Hollywood) and [[Steve McQueen]].<ref name=\"True story characters\"/><ref name=hairdresser-bruce-lee/> Sebring and Tate attended a party at [[Mama Cass]]' house at which [[Charles Manson]] was also in attendance.<ref>{{cite news |last=Williams |first=Alex |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/11/21/style/charles-manson-annoying-hipster.html |title=How Charles Manson Nearly Made It in Hollywood |website=[[The New York Times]] |access-date=August 31, 2019 |date=November 21, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190901045635/https://www.nytimes.com/2017/11/21/style/charles-manson-annoying-hipster.html |archive-date=September 1, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n*Abigail Folger, heir to the [[Folgers]] coffee fortune, and her boyfriend Wojciech Frykowski were Tate's friends.\n\n*[[James Stacy]] and Wayne Maunder were actors who starred on ''Lancer''.<ref name=\"Esq\">{{cite news |last=Coates |first=Tyler |url=https://www.esquire.com/entertainment/movies/g26888375/once-upon-a-time-in-hollywood-cast-photos/ |title=The Real-Life People Portrayed in Once Upon a Time in Hollywood |work=[[Esquire (magazine)|Esquire]]|access-date=March 23, 2019 |date=March 21, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190322215648/https://www.esquire.com/entertainment/movies/g26888375/once-upon-a-time-in-hollywood-cast-photos/ |archive-date=March 22, 2019}}</ref> Stacy is last shown in the film leaving the show's set on a motorcycle; Stacy was in a motorcycle accident that resulted in the death of his passenger and the loss of his arm and leg. His ex-wife, actress [[Connie Stevens]], also portrayed in the film, organized a fundraiser for his recovery.<ref name=hitting-bottom>{{cite magazine |url=http://www.people.com/people/archive/article/0,,20141272,00.html |title=Hitting Bottom |work=[[People (magazine)|People]] |volume=45 |issue=19 |page=62 |issn=0093-7673 |access-date=August 20, 2019 |date=May 13, 1996 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160923221426/http://www.people.com/people/archive/article/0,,20141272,00.html |archive-date=September 23, 2016 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"True story characters\"/> Maunder died during the filming of the movie and [[Luke Perry]], who portrays him in his last screen appearance, died shortly afterward.<ref name=luke-perry>{{cite news |last=Lawrence |first=Derek |url=https://ew.com/movies/2019/03/04/luke-perry-once-upon-a-time-in-hollywood/ |title=Luke Perry's final role will be in Quentin Tarantino's 'Once Upon a Time in Hollywood' |website=[[Entertainment Weekly]] |access-date=August 17, 2019 |date=March 4, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190626213157/https://ew.com/movies/2019/03/04/luke-perry-once-upon-a-time-in-hollywood/ |archive-date=June 26, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref> Luke's son, Jack Perry, appears with him in the film.<ref name=Luke-Perry's-son>{{cite news |last=Fernandez |first=Alexia |url=https://people.com/movies/luke-perry-son-jack-appearing-once-upon-time-hollywood/ |title=Luke Perry's Son Jack Will Appear with His Father in ''Once Upon a Time in Hollywood'' |website=[[People (magazine)|People]] |access-date=August 17, 2019 |date=May 8, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190510055802/https://people.com/movies/luke-perry-son-jack-appearing-once-upon-time-hollywood/ |archive-date=May 10, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref> [[Sam Wanamaker]] directed the real pilot of ''Lancer'', in which the Land Pirates were actual characters.<ref name=Lancer>{{cite web |url=http://www.westernclippings.com/remember/lancer_doyouremember.shtml |title=Lancer |website=westernclippings |access-date=August 31, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190831213244/http://www.westernclippings.com/remember/lancer_doyouremember.shtml |archive-date=August 31, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n*Bruce Lee was an actor and martial artist who starred as [[Kato (The Green Hornet)|Kato]] on ''The Green Hornet''. He taught Tate martial arts for ''The Wrecking Crew'', and also trained Sebring, Polanski and McQueen.<ref name=hairdresser-bruce-lee>{{cite news |url=https://www.scmp.com/culture/film-tv/article/2154838/bruce-lee-steve-mcqueen-and-hairdresser-killed-manson-family-who |title=Bruce Lee, Steve McQueen, and the hairdresser killed by the Manson Family who introduced the pair |website=[[South China Morning Post]] |access-date=August 18, 2019 |date=July 11, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190818160155/https://www.scmp.com/culture/film-tv/article/2154838/bruce-lee-steve-mcqueen-and-hairdresser-killed-manson-family-who |archive-date=August 18, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n*\"Mama Cass\" Elliot and [[Michelle Phillips]] were members of [[the Mamas and the Papas]]. The sheet music for their song \"Straight Shooter\" was found on the piano at the murder scene inside the Tate/Polanski residence, and it is also used in the film's trailer.<ref name=straight-shooter>{{cite news |last=Runtagh |first=Jordan |url=https://people.com/music/once-upon-a-time-in-hollywood-trailer-chilling-musical-secret/ |title=The Once Upon a Time in Hollywood Trailer Makes a Chilling Secret Reference to Charles Manson |website=[[People (magazine)|People]] |access-date=August 19, 2019 |date=March 21, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190727192158/https://people.com/music/once-upon-a-time-in-hollywood-trailer-chilling-musical-secret/ |archive-date=July 27, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref> Polanski had an affair with Phillips while he was married to Sharon Tate.<ref name=polanski-phillips>{{cite news |last=Birmingham |first=John |url=https://purpleclover.littlethings.com/entertainment/7303-hollywood-one-night-stands/item/michelle-phillips-and-roman-polanski/ |title=15 Celebrity One-Night Stands |website=purple clover |access-date=August 17, 2019 |date=November 16, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190818032501/https://purpleclover.littlethings.com/entertainment/7303-hollywood-one-night-stands/item/michelle-phillips-and-roman-polanski/ |archive-date=August 18, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n*Harvey \"Humble Harve\" Miller was a Los Angeles [[radio personality|radio DJ]] who was convicted of killing his wife.<ref name=\"Humble Harve\">{{cite news |last=Lewis |first=Randy |url=https://www.latimes.com/entertainment/music/la-me-humble-harve-miller-dead-20190606-story.html |title='Humble Harve,' former KHJ 'Boss Radio' DJ who killed wife dies at 84 |work=[[Los Angeles Times]] |access-date=August 12, 2019 |date=June 6, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190716202421/https://www.latimes.com/entertainment/music/la-me-humble-harve-miller-dead-20190606-story.html |archive-date=July 16, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n*[[Tim Roth]] and [[Danny Strong]] shot scenes that were cut. Strong portrayed [[Dean Martin]] and Roth portrayed Amos Russell, Sebring's English butler.<ref name=How-Stars-Compare-to-Real-Life-Players>{{cite news |url=https://www.eonline.com/news/1059735/margot-robbie-luke-perry-and-more-see-how-the-stars-of-once-upon-a-time-in-hollywood-compare-to-the-real-life-players#photo-1020682 |title=Margot Robbie, Luke Perry, and More: See How the Stars of Once Upon a Time in Hollywood Compare to the Real-Life Players |website=[[E! News]] |last=Nilles |first=Billy |access-date=August 13, 2019 |date=July 26, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190813203358/https://www.eonline.com/news/1059735/margot-robbie-luke-perry-and-more-see-how-the-stars-of-once-upon-a-time-in-hollywood-compare-to-the-real-life-players#photo-1020682 |archive-date=August 13, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=Tarantino-Deadline-Interview>{{cite news |url=https://deadline.com/2019/07/quentin-tarantino-once-upon-a-time-interview-leonardo-dicaprio-bradd-pitt-margot-robbie-star-trek-pulp-fiction-1202647835/ |title=Quentin Tarantino On 'Once Upon a Time,' His Vision of 'Star Trek' As 'Pulp Fiction' In Space, And Hopes To Turn Leo DiCaprio 50s Western 'Bounty Law' Into Series |website=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|last=Fleming Jr. |first=Mike|access-date=August 13, 2019 |date=July 17, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.indiewire.com/2019/07/james-marsden-cut-role-once-upon-a-time-in-hollywood-revealed-1202160319/ |title=James Marsden's Cut Role in 'Once Upon a Time in Hollywood' Revealed as Meta Surprise |website=[[IndieWire]] |first=Zack |last=Sharf |date=July 23, 2019 |accessdate=August 3, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190803140109/https://www.indiewire.com/2019/07/james-marsden-cut-role-once-upon-a-time-in-hollywood-revealed-1202160319/ |archive-date=August 3, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.indiewire.com/2019/07/once-upon-a-time-in-hollywood-quentin-tarantino-brad-pitt-leonardo-dicaprio-brandy-1202160975/ |title=The Making of 'Once Upon a Time in Hollywood' Was a Throwback to Studios' Pre-Franchise Glory Days |website=[[IndieWire]] |first=Anne |last=Thompson |date=July 26, 2019 |accessdate=August 3, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190727215334/https://www.indiewire.com/2019/07/once-upon-a-time-in-hollywood-quentin-tarantino-brad-pitt-leonardo-dicaprio-brandy-1202160975/ |archive-date=July 27, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==== The Manson Family ====\n*[[George Spahn]] was an 80-year-old nearly blind man who rented his [[Spahn Ranch|ranch]] out for westerns. The Manson Family lived on the ranch. [[Burt Reynolds]] was cast, but died before filming.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Galuppo |first1=Mia |title=Burt Reynolds Did Not Shoot Role in Quentin Tarantino's New Movie |url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/burt-reynolds-did-not-shoot-role-quentin-tarantinos-new-movie-1140534 |accessdate=September 6, 2018 |work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]] |date=September 6, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180906235502/https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/burt-reynolds-did-not-shoot-role-quentin-tarantinos-new-movie-1140534|archive-date=September 6, 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"Dern\">{{cite news |last1=Fleming Jr. |first1=Mike |title=Bruce Dern Replaces His Friend Burt Reynolds in Quentin Tarantino's 'Once Upon A Time in Hollywood' |url=https://deadline.com/2018/09/bruce-dern-replaces-burt-reynolds-quentin-tarantino-once-upon-a-time-in-hollywood-1202471986/ |work=[[Deadline Hollywood]] |date=September 27, 2018 |accessdate=October 30, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181004011620/https://deadline.com/2018/09/bruce-dern-replaces-burt-reynolds-quentin-tarantino-once-upon-a-time-in-hollywood-1202471986/ |archive-date=October 4, 2018}}</ref> Reynolds did a rehearsal and script reading, his last performance. After reading the script and learning that Pitt would be portraying Booth, Reynolds told Tarantino, \"You gotta have somebody say, 'You're pretty for a stunt guy.'\" The line appears in the movie, but is spoken to Booth by Bruce Lee.<ref>{{cite news |last=Fernandez |first=Alexia |url=https://people.com/movies/burt-reynolds-funny-line-brad-pitt-once-upon-a-time-in-hollywood |title=Burt Reynolds Came Up with Funny 'Once Upon a Time in Hollywood' Line About Brad Pitt Before Death |website=[[People (magazine)|People]] |access-date=August 27, 2019 |date=August 9, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190816001211/https://people.com/movies/burt-reynolds-funny-line-brad-pitt-once-upon-a-time-in-hollywood/ |archive-date=August 16, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n*[[Charles Manson|Charles \"Charlie\" Manson]] was a criminal and [[cult]] leader of the [[Manson Family]], a [[commune]] based in California. Members of the Family committed nine murders in 1969.<ref name=helter-skelter/> [[Damon Herriman]], who portrays Manson, also portrays him in ''[[Mindhunter (TV series)|Mindhunter]]''.\n\n*\"Pussycat\" is a [[composite character]], with her nickname based on Kathryn Lutesinger's \"Kitty Kat\" yet modeled after [[Ruth Ann Moorehouse]]. Manson frequently sent Moorehouse into the city to lure men with money back to Spahn Ranch.<ref name=\"About the Manson Family\">{{cite news |last=Romain |first=Lindsey |url=https://www.nerdist.com/article/once-upon-a-time-in-hollywood-manson-family-fact-check/ |title=What Once Upon a Time...in Hollywood Gets Right About the Manson Family |work=[[Nerdist Industries|Nerdist]] |access-date=August 11, 2019 |date=July 29, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190812003254/https://nerdist.com/article/once-upon-a-time-in-hollywood-manson-family-fact-check/ |archive-date=August 12, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref> Lutesinger met Manson through her boyfriend, [[Bobby Beausoleil]].<ref>{{cite web |last=Cipriani |first=Casey |url=https://www.bustle.com/p/was-pussycat-a-real-person-once-upon-a-time-in-hollywood-takes-some-liberties-with-the-manson-family-18200242 |title=Was Pussycat A Real Person? 'Once Upon a Time In Hollywood' Takes Some Liberties With The Manson Family |website=[[Bustle (magazine)|Bustle]] |access-date=September 17, 2019 |date=July 24, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190725164451/https://www.bustle.com/p/was-pussycat-a-real-person-once-upon-a-time-in-hollywood-takes-some-liberties-with-the-manson-family-18200242 |archive-date=July 25, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref> There is someone only called Pussycat in ''The Family'' by [[Ed Sanders]]. According to those interviewed, Pussycat underwent an [[exorcism]] with Manson present. The real identity of Pussycat is never revealed.<ref name=Pussycat>{{cite book |last=Sanders |first=Ed |url=https://archive.org/details/family00sand |url-access=registration |quote=Pussycat. |title=The Family: The Story of Charles Manson's Dune Buggy Attack Battalion|access-date=August 13, 2019 |date=1971 |isbn=1-56025-396-7}}</ref>\n\n*\"Squeaky\" was [[Lynette Fromme]]'s nickname, given to her by Spahn because of the sound she made when he touched her.<ref name=nicknames/> She was Spahn's main caretaker, tending to his needs, sexual or otherwise.<ref name=\"About the Manson Family\"/>\n\n*\"Straight Satan David\" is a member of the Straight Satans Motorcycle Club, associates of the Family, who acted as their security.<ref name=helter-skelter/>\n\n*Bill \"Sweet William Tumbleweed\" Fritsch was a member of the [[Hells Angels]] and [[Diggers (theater)|Diggers]], and Manson Family associate.{{citation needed|date=September 2019}}\n\n*Connie is a [[Equestrianism|horseback-riding]] customer at Spahn Ranch. As one way of earning their keep, the Family gave horseback riding tours to people visiting the ranch.<ref name=\"About the Manson Family\"/>\n*Sean Baker, Daniel Callister, Sami Henry, Tea Jo, Riley Lucente, Harold Smith, Sarah May Sommers and Zack Whyel also play members of the Manson Family.\n*\"Tex\" was [[Tex Watson|Charles Watson]]'s nickname. Spahn gave it to him because of his Texas accent.\n*\"Sadie\" was [[Susan Atkins]]' nickname. Manson gave everyone fake IDs, and the name on Atkins' was \"Sadie Mae Glutz\". Atkins was called \"Sexy Sadie\" after a [[Sexy Sadie|track]] on [[the Beatles]]' [[The Beatles (album)|self-titled album]]<!-- The album was titled \"The Beatles\", not \"The White Album\" despite the common reference. --> that some of the Family members may have believed was about her.<ref name=helter-skelter/>\n*\"Katie\" was [[Patricia Krenwinkel]]'s nickname because of the name on her ID.<ref name=nicknames/> [[Madisen Beaty]], who portrays Krenwinkel, previously portrayed her on ''[[Aquarius (American TV series)|Aquarius]]''.\n*\"[[flower child|Flower Child]]\" was not the nickname of any member. However, the character in the film is [[Linda Kasabian]], as she was the fourth member to go to Tate's house.<ref name=\"About the Manson Family\"/>\n*\"Snake\" was [[:de:Diane Lake|Dianne Lake]]'s nickname, given to her by Manson because she rolled around in grass pretending to be a snake.\n*\"Blue\" was [[Sandra Good]]'s nickname. Manson told her, \"Woman, you're earth. I'm naming you Blue. Fix the air and the water. It's your job.\"\n*\"Gypsy\" was [[Catherine Share]]'s nickname, which she gave herself after meeting a man named Gypsy with whom she shared a birthday and whom she thought was her cosmic twin.<ref name=nicknames>{{cite web |last=Sederstrom |first=Jill |url=https://www.oxygen.com/manson-the-women/crime-time/squeaky-fromme-catherine-gypsy-share-manson-family-nicknames |title=Why Did The Manson Family Members Have Nicknames? |website=[[Oxygen (TV channel)|Oxygen]] |access-date=September 12, 2019 |date=August 12, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190813234706/https://www.oxygen.com/manson-the-women/crime-time/squeaky-fromme-catherine-gypsy-share-manson-family-nicknames |archive-date=August 13, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n*Catherine Gillies was nicknamed \"Capistrano\" by Spahn, but called \"Cappy\" for short.<ref name=helter-skelter/> In the film, her name is \"Happy Cappy\".\n*\"Lulu\" was one of [[Leslie Van Houten]]'s nicknames, and \"Clem\" one of [[Steve \"Clem\" Grogan|Steve Grogan]]'s.<ref name=\"About the Manson Family\"/>\n*\"Tophat\" was an alias of Bobby Beausoleil. In his book ''[[Turn Off Your Mind]]'', [[Gary Lachman]] mentions that, \"Beausoleil had a style; a [[top hat]] that set him apart from the usual hippie fare.\"<ref>{{cite book |last=Lachman |first=Gary |title=Turn Off Your Mind: The Mystic Sixties and the Dark Side of the Age of Aquarius |publisher=Red Wheel Weiser |date=June 1, 2003 |isbn=1-934708-65-8}}</ref> Beausoleil wrote, \"I spied a felt top hat in the window of a... shop... I couldn't afford (it)... but it felt like it had been made for me... I couldn't resist the temptation to buy it.\" Beausoleil claimed that as soon as he put on the hat, ideas floating in his head came together.<ref>{{cite web |last=BeauSoleil |first=Bobby |url=http://bobbybeausoleil.com/the-orkustra-notes-from-the-psychedelic-underground.html |title=The Orkusta: Notes from the Psychedelic Underground |website=bobbybeausoleil |access-date=September 12, 2019 |year=2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190828203557/http://www.bobbybeausoleil.com/the-orkustra-notes-from-the-psychedelic-underground.html |archive-date=August 28, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n*The character of \"Sundance\" was named by Cassidy Hice, the actress who portrays her. She wrote, \"I was asked to name my character by Quentin himself.\"<ref>{{cite web |last=Hice |first=Cassidy |url=https://www.instagram.com/p/B0Z_X_DJV4V/ |title=Spahn Ranch |website=[[Instagram]]| access-date=September 12, 2019 |date=July 26, 2019}}</ref>\n\n== Production ==\n=== Writing and development ===\nThe work that would become the screenplay for ''Once Upon a Time in Hollywood'' was developed slowly over several years by Tarantino. While he knew he wanted the work to be titled ''Once Upon a Time in Hollywood'', evoking the idea of a fairy tale set in 1960s Hollywood, he publicly referred to the project as ''Magnum Opus''.<ref name=\"esquire may2019\">{{cite magazine | url = https://www.esquire.com/entertainment/movies/a27458589/once-upon-a-time-in-hollywood-leonardo-dicaprio-brad-pitt-quentin-tarantino-interview/ | title = Quentin Tarantino, Brad Pitt, and Leonardo DiCaprio Take You Inside 'Once Upon a Time...In Hollywood' | first = Michael | last = Hainey | date = May 21, 2019 | accessdate = January 19, 2020 | magazine = [[Esquire (magazine)|Esquire]] }}</ref> The life of the work for the first five years was as a novel,<ref name=\"esquire may2019\"/> which Tarantino considered to be an exploratory approach to the story he wanted to tell, not yet having decided if it would be a screenplay. Tarantino tried other writing approaches: the early scene between DiCaprio's Dalton and Pacino's Marvin Schwarz was originally written as a one-act play as part of this exploratory work.<ref name=\"gamespot inspiration\"/>\n\nTarantino discovered the centerpiece for the work in 2009 while filming a movie with an actor that had the same stunt double for 20 years. Even though there was nothing but a small bit for the stuntman to do, Tarantino was asked to use him, and he agreed. The relationship fascinated Tarantino and inspired him to make a film about Hollywood.<ref name=recut/> Tarantino said that while the stuntman may have been a perfect double for the actor years earlier, at the time he had come to meet them, \"this was maybe the last or second-to-last thing they'd be doing together\".<ref name=\"gamespot inspiration\">{{cite web | url = https://www.gamespot.com/articles/quentin-tarantino-reveals-inspiration-behind-once-/1100-6472880/ | title =Quentin Tarantino Reveals Inspiration Behind Once Upon A Time In Hollywood | first = James | last = O'Conner | date = January 19, 2020 | accessdate = January 19, 2020 | work = [[GameSpot]] }}</ref>\n\nTarantino first created Cliff Booth, giving him a massive backstory. Then, the actor Booth was the stunt double for Rick Dalton. Tarantino decided to have them be [[Sharon Tate]]'s next-door neighbors in 1969. The first plot point he developed was the ending, then moved backwards from there, this being the first time Tarantino had worked this way. He thought of doing an [[Elmore Leonard]]-type story, but realized he was confident enough in his characters to let them drive the film and let it be a day in the life of Booth, Dalton, and Tate. He would use sequences from Dalton's films for the action, inspired by [[Richard Rush (director)|Richard Rush]]'s ''[[The Stunt Man]]'', which used the scenes from the [[WWI]] movie they were making within the film as the action.<ref>{{cite podcast |last=Lattanzio |first=Ryan |url=https://www.indiewire.com/2019/08/quentin-tarantino-paul-thomas-anderson-once-upon-a-time-in-hollywood-podcast-1202168301 |title=Listen to Quentin Tarantino and Paul Thomas Anderson Talk 'Once Upon a Time in Hollywood' |website=[[IndieWire]] |access-date=September 5, 2019 |date=August 24, 2019 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190829013436/https://www.indiewire.com/2019/08/quentin-tarantino-paul-thomas-anderson-once-upon-a-time-in-hollywood-podcast-1202168301/ |archivedate=August 29, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref> Further, to get his mind into the Dalton character, Tarantino wrote out five hypothetical episodes of the fictional television show ''Bounty Law'', in which Dalton had starred, having become fascinated with the amount of story crammed into half-hour episodes of 1950s western shows. Tarantino has expressed interest in turning these five scripts, as well as ideas for three more, into an actual ''Bounty Law'' television series in the future.<ref name=Tarantino-Deadline-Interview/>\n\n=== Pre-production ===\nOn July 11, 2017, it was announced that [[Quentin Tarantino]]'s next film would be about the [[Manson Family]] murders. [[Harvey Weinstein|Harvey]] and [[Bob Weinstein]] would be involved, but it was not known whether [[The Weinstein Company]] would distribute the film, as Tarantino sought to cast before sending out a package to studios. Tarantino approached [[Brad Pitt]] and [[Jennifer Lawrence]] to star in the film. It was reported that [[Margot Robbie]] was being considered for [[Sharon Tate]].<ref name=\"FirsReportedTHR\"/> [[Samuel L. Jackson]] was in talks for a major role, and Pitt was in talks for the detective investigating the murders.<ref name=\"FirsReportedDeadline\"/>\n\nAfter the [[Harvey Weinstein sexual abuse allegations]], Tarantino cut ties with Weinstein and sought a new distributor, after having worked with Weinstein for his entire career. At this point, [[Leonardo DiCaprio]] was revealed to be among a short list of actors Tarantino was considering for the film.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Fleming Jr |first1=Mike |title=Quentin Tarantino Seeking New Movie Home: Studios Reading #9 This Week |url=https://deadline.com/2017/11/quentin-tarantino-new-home-studios-reading-number-9-harvey-weinstein-1202199806/ |work=[[Deadline Hollywood]] |accessdate=November 8, 2017 |date=November 1, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171108094853/http://deadline.com/2017/11/quentin-tarantino-new-home-studios-reading-number-9-harvey-weinstein-1202199806/|archive-date=November 8, 2017}}</ref> A short time later, reports circulated that studios were bidding for the film set in Los Angeles in the late 1960s, that [[Tom Cruise]] was in talks for one of the leads, and that [[David Heyman]] had joined as a producer, along with Tarantino and [[Shannon McIntosh (filmmaker)|Shannon McIntosh]].<ref name=\"HeymanProducer\"/>\n\nOn November 11, 2017, [[Sony Pictures]] announced they would distribute the film, beating [[Warner Bros.]], [[Universal Pictures]], [[Paramount Pictures]], [[Annapurna Pictures]] and [[Lionsgate]].<ref name=\"SonyWins\">{{cite web |url=https://deadline.com/2017/11/quentin-tarantino-sony-pictures-wins-auction-charles-manson-margot-robbie-tom-cruise-brad-pitt-leonardo-dicaprio-1202210597/ |title=Sony Pictures Confirms Quentin Tarantino Deal; Margot Robbie, Tom Cruise, Brad Pitt, Leonardo DiCaprio Circling |last=Fleming Jr. |first=Mike |date=November 17, 2017 |work=[[Deadline Hollywood]] |accessdate=June 18, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180618152249/https://deadline.com/2017/11/quentin-tarantino-sony-pictures-wins-auction-charles-manson-margot-robbie-tom-cruise-brad-pitt-leonardo-dicaprio-1202210597/|archive-date=June 18, 2018}}</ref> Tarantino's demands included a $95&nbsp;million budget, [[final cut privilege]], \"extraordinary creative controls\", 25% of [[first-dollar gross]],<ref name=\"auto\">{{cite web |url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/how-sony-nabbed-quentin-tarantinos-manson-movie-1059742 |title=How Sony Nabbed Quentin Tarantino's Manson Movie |last=Kit |first=Borys |date=November 18, 2017 |work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]] |accessdate=June 18, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180616205706/https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/how-sony-nabbed-quentin-tarantinos-manson-movie-1059742|archive-date=June 16, 2018}}</ref> and the stipulation that the rights revert to him after 10 to 20 years.<ref name=\"auto\"/>\n\n=== Casting ===\nIn January 2018, DiCaprio signed on, taking a pay cut to collaborate with Tarantino again.<ref name=\"DiCaprioCast\">{{cite web |url=https://deadline.com/2018/01/leonardo-dicaprio-quentin-tarantino-manson-movie-casting-1202241971/ |title=Leonardo DiCaprio To Star in Quentin Tarantino's New Movie |last=Fleming Jr. |first=Mike |date=January 12, 2018 |work=[[Deadline Hollywood]] |accessdate=June 18, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180618175345/https://deadline.com/2018/01/leonardo-dicaprio-quentin-tarantino-manson-movie-casting-1202241971/|archive-date=June 18, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://variety.com/2018/film/news/celebrity-salaries-daniel-craig-jennifer-lawrence-leonardo-dicaprio-1202801717/ |title=Leonardo DiCaprio, Jennifer Lawrence and Other Star Salaries Revealed |last1=Lang |first1=Brent |last2=Kroll |first2=Justin |date=May 8, 2018 |work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] |accessdate=June 18, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180618152314/https://variety.com/2018/film/news/celebrity-salaries-daniel-craig-jennifer-lawrence-leonardo-dicaprio-1202801717/|archive-date=June 18, 2018}}</ref> [[Al Pacino]] was being considered for a role.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://variety.com/2018/film/news/leonardo-dicaprio-charles-manson-movie-quentin-tarantino-1202663081/ |title=Leonardo DiCaprio to Star in Quentin Tarantino's Manson Movie |last=Kroll |first=Justin |date=January 12, 2018 |work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] |accessdate=June 18, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180618175635/https://variety.com/2018/film/news/leonardo-dicaprio-charles-manson-movie-quentin-tarantino-1202663081/|archive-date=June 18, 2018}}</ref> On February 28, 2018, the film was titled ''Once Upon a Time in Hollywood'', with Pitt cast in the role Cruise was also up for.<ref name=\"PittCast\">{{cite web |url=https://deadline.com/2018/02/quentin-tarantino-brad-pitt-leonardo-dicaprio-once-upon-a-time-in-hollywood-1202306448/ |title=Quentin Tarantino Taps Brad Pitt To Join Leonardo DiCaprio In 'Once Upon A Time in Hollywood' |last=Fleming Jr. |first=Mike |date=February 28, 2018 |work=[[Deadline Hollywood]] |accessdate=June 18, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180620171241/https://deadline.com/2018/02/quentin-tarantino-brad-pitt-leonardo-dicaprio-once-upon-a-time-in-hollywood-1202306448/|archive-date=June 20, 2018}}</ref> DiCaprio and Pitt were each paid $10&nbsp;million.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://variety.com/2019/film/news/celebrity-salaries-leonardo-dicaprio-margot-robbie-dwayne-johnson-will-smith-1203200508/ |title=Leonardo DiCaprio, Margot Robbie and More 2019 Star Salaries Revealed |website=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]| access-date=April 30, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190501003157/https://variety.com/2019/film/news/celebrity-salaries-leonardo-dicaprio-margot-robbie-dwayne-johnson-will-smith-1203200508/ |archive-date=May 1, 2019|date=April 30, 2019 }}</ref> In March 2018, Robbie, who had expressed interest in working with Tarantino,<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/features/margot-robbie-reliving-tonya-hardings-abuse-her-superhero-stalker-fears-1071169 |title=Margot Robbie on Reliving Tonya Harding's 'Abuse' and Her Superhero Stalker Fears |last=Rose |first=Lacey |date=January 4, 2018 |work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180618130057/https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/features/margot-robbie-reliving-tonya-hardings-abuse-her-superhero-stalker-fears-1071169|archive-date=June 18, 2018 |accessdate=June 18, 2018}}</ref> signed to co-star as Sharon Tate, while [[Zo\u00eb Bell]] confirmed she would appear.<ref name=\"RobbieCast\">{{cite web |url=https://deadline.com/2018/03/margot-robbie-sharon-tate-quentin-tarantino-film-leonardo-dicaprio-brad-pitt-once-upon-a-time-in-hollywood-1202336947/ |title=Margot Robbie Now in Negotiations To Play Sharon Tate in Quentin Tarantino Film |last=Fleming Jr. |first=Mike |date=March 13, 2018 |work=[[Deadline Hollywood]] |accessdate=June 18, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180618152319/https://deadline.com/2018/03/margot-robbie-sharon-tate-quentin-tarantino-film-leonardo-dicaprio-brad-pitt-once-upon-a-time-in-hollywood-1202336947/|archive-date=June 18, 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"BellCast\">{{cite web |url=https://www.indiewire.com/2018/03/zoe-bell-quentin-tarantino-once-upon-a-time-in-hollywood-pitt-dicaprio-1201937156/ |title=Zo\u00eb Bell on Quentin Tarantino's New Movie: The World Is Going to Implode 'With So Much Genius in One Space' |last=Sharf |first=Zack |date=March 8, 2018 |work=[[IndieWire]] |accessdate=June 18, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180618125944/http://www.indiewire.com/2018/03/zoe-bell-quentin-tarantino-once-upon-a-time-in-hollywood-pitt-dicaprio-1201937156/|archive-date=June 18, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.thewrap.com/quentin-tarantinos-longtime-stuntwoman-says-shell-work-on-his-next-film-in-some-capacity-video/ |title=Zoe Bell to Work on Quentin Tarantino's 'Once upon a Time in Hollywood' |first=Jeremy |last=Fuster |date=March 7, 2018 |work=[[The Wrap]] |accessdate=March 7, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180308030601/https://www.thewrap.com/quentin-tarantinos-longtime-stuntwoman-says-shell-work-on-his-next-film-in-some-capacity-video/|archive-date=March 8, 2018}}</ref> In April 2018, [[Jessica Lange]] was in talks to play Mary Alice Schwarzs, but dropped out and [[Brenda Vaccaro]] replaced her. In May 2018, [[Burt Reynolds]], [[Tim Roth]], [[Kurt Russell]], and [[Michael Madsen]] joined the cast.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://deadline.com/2018/05/quentin-tarantino-burt-reynolds-george-spahn-manson-ranch-owner-tim-roth-kurt-russell-michael-madsen-once-upon-a-time-in-hollywood-sony-1202385014/ |title=Quentin Tarantino Cast Thickens: Burt Reynolds To Star, Roth, Russell, Madsen Play Small Roles; Margot Robbie Confirmed As Sharon Tate |last=Fleming Jr. |first=Mike |date=May 8, 2018 |work=[[Deadline Hollywood]] |accessdate=June 18, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180615114939/https://deadline.com/2018/05/quentin-tarantino-burt-reynolds-george-spahn-manson-ranch-owner-tim-roth-kurt-russell-michael-madsen-once-upon-a-time-in-hollywood-sony-1202385014/|archive-date=June 15, 2018}}</ref> [[Timothy Olyphant]] was also cast.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://deadline.com/2018/05/timothy-olyphant-quentin-tarantino-once-upon-a-time-in-hollywood-1202388439/ |title=Timothy Olyphant Negotiating Lead Role in Quentin Tarantino's 'Once Upon A Time in Hollywood' |last=Fleming Jr. |first=Mike |date=May 11, 2018 |work=[[Deadline Hollywood]] |accessdate=June 18, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180618175226/https://deadline.com/2018/05/timothy-olyphant-quentin-tarantino-once-upon-a-time-in-hollywood-1202388439/|archive-date=June 18, 2018}}</ref> In June 2018, [[Damian Lewis]], [[Luke Perry]], [[Emile Hirsch]], [[Dakota Fanning]], [[Clifton Collins Jr.]], Keith Jefferson, [[Nicholas Hammond]], Pacino, and [[Scoot McNairy]] joined the cast.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://deadline.com/2018/06/once-upon-a-time-in-hollywood-damian-lewis-luke-perry-dakota-fanning-cast-1202405007/ |title=Quentin Tarantino's 'Once Upon A Time in Hollywood' Adds Luke Perry, Damian Lewis, Dakota Fanning, More |last=Fleming Jr. |first=Mike |date=June 6, 2018 |work=[[Deadline Hollywood]] |accessdate=June 18, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180614011100/https://deadline.com/2018/06/once-upon-a-time-in-hollywood-damian-lewis-luke-perry-dakota-fanning-cast-1202405007/|archive-date=June 14, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://variety.com/2018/film/news/al-pacino-quentin-tarantino-manson-movie-1202826780/ |title=Al Pacino Joins Quentin Tarantino's Manson Movie (Exclusive) |last=Kroll |first=Justin |date=June 7, 2018 |work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] |accessdate=June 18, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180618103114/https://variety.com/2018/film/news/al-pacino-quentin-tarantino-manson-movie-1202826780/|archive-date=June 18, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://deadline.com/2018/06/scoot-mcnairy-quentin-tarantino-once-upon-a-time-in-hollywood-leonardo-dicaprio-brad-pitt-margot-robbie-1202415237/ |title=Scoot McNairy Joins Quentin Tarantino's 'Once Upon A Time in Hollywood' |website=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|access-date=June 21, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180621221411/https://deadline.com/2018/06/scoot-mcnairy-quentin-tarantino-once-upon-a-time-in-hollywood-leonardo-dicaprio-brad-pitt-margot-robbie-1202415237/ |archive-date=June 21, 2018|date=June 21, 2018 }}</ref> [[Spencer Garrett]], [[James Remar]], Brenda Vaccaro, and [[Mike Moh]] were announced in July.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://deadline.com/2018/07/quentin-tarantino-rounds-out-cast-with-spencer-garrett-martin-kove-james-remar-brenda-vaccaro-1202424049/ |title=Quentin Tarantino Rounds Out Cast With Spencer Garrett, Martin Kove, James Remar, Brenda Vaccaro |website=[[Deadline Hollywood]]| access-date=July 10, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180711035552/https://deadline.com/2018/07/quentin-tarantino-rounds-out-cast-with-spencer-garrett-martin-kove-james-remar-brenda-vaccaro-1202424049/ |archive-date=July 11, 2018|date=July 10, 2018}}</ref> In August 2018, [[Damon Herriman]] as [[Charles Manson]], and [[Lena Dunham]], [[Austin Butler]], [[Danny Strong]], [[Rumer Willis]], [[Dreama Walker]], and [[Margaret Qualley]] were cast.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://deadline.com/2018/08/lena-dunham-austin-butler-maya-hawke-lorenza-izzo-quentin-tarantino-once-upon-a-time-in-hollywood-1202450671/ |title=Lena Dunham, Austin Butler, Maya Hawke, Lorenza Izzo Board Quentin Tarantino's 'Once Upon A Time in Hollywood' |website=[[Deadline Hollywood]] |first=Amanda |last=N'Duka |date=August 22, 2018 |accessdate=August 22, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180823042113/https://deadline.com/2018/08/lena-dunham-austin-butler-maya-hawke-lorenza-izzo-quentin-tarantino-once-upon-a-time-in-hollywood-1202450671/|archive-date=August 23, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://ew.com/movies/2018/08/22/lena-dunham-quentin-tarantino-once-upon-a-time-in-hollywood/ |title=Lena Dunham to play Manson disciple in Tarantino's Once Upon A Time in Hollywood |website=[[Entertainment Weekly]] |first=Piya |last=Sinha-Roy |date=August 22, 2018 |accessdate=August 22, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180823031438/https://ew.com/movies/2018/08/22/lena-dunham-quentin-tarantino-once-upon-a-time-in-hollywood/|archive-date=August 23, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/danny-strong-sydney-sweeney-join-once-a-time-hollywood-1129521 |title=Danny Strong, Sydney Sweeney Join 'Once Upon a Time in Hollywood' (Exclusive) |website=[[The Hollywood Reporter]] |first=Mia |last=Galuppo |date=August 27, 2018 |accessdate=August 27, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180828035848/https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/danny-strong-sydney-sweeney-join-once-a-time-hollywood-1129521|archive-date=August 28, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.thewrap.com/charles-manson-damon-herriman-quentin-tarantino-once-upon-time-hollywood-rumer-willis/ |title='Once Upon a Time in Hollywood' Adds Rumer Willis, Margaret Qualley and Damon Herriman (Exclusive) |access-date=August 29, 2018 |website=[[TheWrap]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180829110013/https://www.thewrap.com/charles-manson-damon-herriman-quentin-tarantino-once-upon-time-hollywood-rumer-willis/ |archive-date=August 29, 2018|date=August 29, 2018 }}</ref>\n\nWhen casting the leads, Tarantino invited Pitt, DiCaprio, and Robbie to his house to read the only copy of the full script, to prevent leaks. When Butler auditioned, he did not know which character it was for. Tarantino told him it was for a villain or a hero on ''Lancer'', when in fact it was for [[Tex Watson|\"Tex\" Watson]]. To prepare for her audition, [[Maya Hawke]] practiced with her father, [[Ethan Hawke]]. She said the process was unlike any other except maybe auditioning for drama school, and during it they worked on the scene in many different ways, with different combinations of people. Willis auditioned for two roles, neither of which she got, then was offered the part of [[Joanna Pettet]]. [[Sydney Sweeney]] said everyone she auditioned with did so for the same character, then were told they could do extra credit. Some did artwork, and she wrote a letter in character. [[Julia Butters]] says her sitcom ''[[American Housewife]]'' was on while Tarantino was writing her character, Trudi Fraser. He looked up and said, \"Maybe she can try this.\"<ref>{{cite web |last=Gardner |first=Chris |url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/rambling-reporter/quentin-tarantinos-once-a-time-hollywood-manson-family-actors-detail-unconventional-audition-process-1226543 |title=\"Once Upon a Time in Hollywood\" Actors Detail Quentin Tarantino's \"Unconventional\" Prcoess |website=[[The Hollywood Reporter]] |access-date=September 4, 2019 |date=July 26, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190731051119/https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/rambling-reporter/quentin-tarantinos-once-a-time-hollywood-manson-family-actors-detail-unconventional-audition-process-1226543 |archive-date=July 31, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n=== Filming and design ===\n[[Principal photography]] began on June 18, 2018, in Los Angeles, California, and [[Wrap (filmmaking)|wrapped]] on November 1, 2018.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://omegaunderground.com/2018/05/24/tarantinos-once-upon-a-time-in-hollywood-begins-filming-on-june-18th-in-la/ |title=Tarantino's 'Once Upon A Time in Hollywood' Begins Filming on June 18th in LA |last=Marc |first=Christopher |date=May 24, 2018 |website=Omega Underground |accessdate=June 18, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180618125719/https://omegaunderground.com/2018/05/24/tarantinos-once-upon-a-time-in-hollywood-begins-filming-on-june-18th-in-la/|archive-date=June 18, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.backstage.com/resources/detail/productionlisting/once-upon-a-time-in-hollywood-86666/ |title=Once Upon a Time in Hollywood |website=[[Backstage (magazine)|Backstage]] |accessdate=November 1, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190322012929/https://www.backstage.com/resources/detail/productionlisting/once-upon-a-time-in-hollywood-86666/|archive-date=March 22, 2019}}</ref> Reynolds died in September 2018 before filming any of his scenes; [[Bruce Dern]] was cast as [[George Spahn]] in his place.<ref name=\"Dern\"/>\n\nTarantino's directive was to turn Los Angeles of 2018 into Los Angeles of 1969 without [[Computer-generated imagery|CGI]].<ref name=\"afar\"/> For this, Tarantino tapped into previous collaborators for production: editor [[Fred Raskin]], cinematographer [[Robert Richardson (cinematographer)|Robert Richardson]], sound editor [[Wylie Stateman]] and makeup artist Heba Thorisdottir. He also brought first-time collaborators production designer Barbara Ling based on her work in recreating historical settings in ''[[The Doors (film)|The Doors]]'', and costume designer [[Arianne Phillips]], who had a strong client list to her name including [[Tom Ford]], [[James Mangold]] and [[Madonna (entertainer)|Madonna]].<ref name=\"variety making 60s\">{{cite web | url = https://variety.com/2020/artisans/production/quentin-tarantino-once-upon-a-time-in-hollywood-2-1203484354/ | title = Quentin Tarantino on Re-Creating 1960s L.A. for 'Once Upon a Time in Hollywood' | first = Jazz | last = Tangcay | date = January 29, 2020 | accessdate = January 29, 2020 | work = [[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] }}</ref> Production and filming required months of collaboration with city planners, business owners, set decorators, and construction crews. While filming at [[Musso & Frank Grill]], the owners brought out the original plates.\n\nTo film at the Pussycat Theater, production designer Barbara Ling and her team covered the building's [[LED]] signage and reattached the theater's iconic logo, rebuilding the letters and neon. Ling said the lettering on every marquee in the film is historically accurate. To restore Larry Edmund's Bookshop, she reproduced the original storefront sign and tracked down period-appropriate merchandise, even recreating book covers. For the Bruin and Fox Village theaters Ling's team restored the theaters, their marquees, and the storefronts around them. Stan's Donuts, across the street from the Bruin got a complete makeover.<ref name=\"afar\">{{cite news |last=Wakim |first=Marielle |url=https://www.afar.com/magazine/once-upon-a-time-in-hollywood-filming-locations-you-can-visit-in-los-angeles |title='Once Upon a Time... in Hollywood' Filming Locations You Can Visit in Los Angeles |website=[[Afar (magazine)|Afar]] |access-date=September 2, 2019 |date=July 26, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190903051130/https://www.afar.com/magazine/once-upon-a-time-in-hollywood-filming-locations-you-can-visit-in-los-angeles |archive-date=September 3, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref> \n\nTarantino was adamant about filming at the real [[Playboy Mansion]], but it took a long time to obtain permission since by the time of pre-production the mansion had been sold to a private owner following [[Hugh Hefner]]'s death. Tarantino and Ling met with the new owner to discuss their plans and the parts of the property which they wanted to use. After long negotiations the owner agreed, and Ling was able to dress the vacant mansion, front courtyard, and backyard for the party scene, evoking as much of the 1960s appearance of the mansion as possible.<ref name=recreating-hollywood>\n\nFor ''Bounty Law'', Ling went for a dusty, dirty, early ''[[Deadwood (TV series)|Deadwood]]'' look. Ling's team found one of the last great living Italian artists to do two of the film's posters. Other posters used and the mugs, are part of Tarantino's personal collection. Movie poster artist [[Steven Chorney]] created the poster for the film, as a reference to ''[[The Mod Squad]]''. He also created the posters for ''Nebraska Jim'', ''Operation Dyn-O-Mite'', ''Uccidimi Subito Ringo Disse il Gringo'', ''Hell-Fire Texas'', and ''Comanche Uprising'', which was reprinted for Dalton's home parking spot. [[Mad (magazine)|''Mad'']] magazine caricaturist [[Tom Richmond (illustrator)|Tom Richmond]] created the covers of ''Mad'' and ''[[TV Guide]]'' featuring Dalton's Jake Cahill. Spahn Ranch was recreated in detail over about a three-month period. The [[Playboy Mansion]] scene was shot at the actual mansion.<ref name=recreating-hollywood/><ref>{{cite web |last=Combemale |first=Leslie |url=https://www.mpaa.org/2019/08/artist-steve-chorney-on-crafting-once-upon-a-time-in-hollywoods-poster-more/ |title=Artist Steve Chorney on Crafting ''Once Upon a Time in Hollywood''{{'}}s Poster & More |website=[[Motion Picture Association of America]]| access-date=September 8, 2019 |date=August 12, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last=Minow |first=Nell |url=https://www.mpaa.org/2019/08/meet-the-caricaturist-who-created-once-upon-a-time-in-hollywoods-classic-mad-magazine-cover/ |title=Meet the Caricaturist who Created 'Once Upon a Time in... Hollywood's' Classic MAD Magazine Cover |website=[[Motion Picture Association of America]]| access-date=September 8, 2019 |date=August 1, 2019}}</ref>\n\nTarantino told cinematographer [[Robert Richardson (cinematographer)|Robert Richardson]], \"I want it to feel retro but I want it to be contemporary.\" Richardson shot in [[Kodak]] [[35 mm movie film|35mm]] with [[Panavision]] cameras and lenses, in order to weave time periods. For ''Bounty Law'' they shot in black and white, and brief sequences in [[Super 8 film|Super 8]] and [[16mm]] [[Ektachrome]]. In the film, ''[[Lancer (TV series)|Lancer]]'' was shot on a retrofitted Western Street backlot at [[Universal Studios]], designed by Ling. Richardson crossed ''Lancer'' with ''[[Alias Smith and Jones]]'' for the retro-future look Tarantino wanted. The way they filmed ''Lancer'' was not possible in 1969, but Tarantino wanted his personal touch on it. Richardson said that filming the movie touched him personally, \"The film speaks to all of us... We are all fragile beings with a limited time to achieve whatever it is we desire... that at any moment that place will shift... So take stock in life and have the courage to believe in yourself.\"<ref name=recreating-hollywood>{{cite web |last=Han |first=Karen |url=https://www.polygon.com/2019/7/28/8932339/once-upon-a-time-in-hollywood-quentin-tarantino-playboy-mansion |title=What it took to get the Playboy Mansion for Once Upon a Time... in Hollywood |website=[[Polygon (website)|Polygon]] |access-date=September 3, 2019 |date=July 28, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190906142247/https://www.polygon.com/2019/7/28/8932339/once-upon-a-time-in-hollywood-quentin-tarantino-playboy-mansion |archive-date=September 6, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last=Desowitz |first=Bill |url=https://www.indiewire.com/2019/07/once-upon-a-time-in-hollywood-cinematographer-robert-richardson-quentin-tarantino-1969-1202159937/ |title=\"Once Upon a Time in Hollywood\": How Cinematographer Robert Richardson captured 1969 in 2019 |website=[[IndieWire]] |access-date=September 3, 2019 |date=July 22, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190723131120/https://www.indiewire.com/2019/07/once-upon-a-time-in-hollywood-cinematographer-robert-richardson-quentin-tarantino-1969-1202159937/ |archive-date=July 23, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nThe exterior of the Van Nuys drive-in scene was filmed at the Paramount Theater since the Van Nuys Theater no longer exists. As the camera rises up over the theater, the shot transitions to a miniature set with toy cars.<ref>{{Cite web| url=https://www.cinemablend.com/news/2477166/cool-tricks-quentin-tarantino-used-to-recreate-1969-la-for-once-upon-a-time-in-hollywood| title=Cool Tricks Quentin Tarantino Used to Recreate 1969 L.A. For Once Upon a Time in Hollywood| date=July 26, 2019| access-date=November 9, 2019|publisher=CinemaBlend| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191109202340/https://www.cinemablend.com/news/2477166/cool-tricks-quentin-tarantino-used-to-recreate-1969-la-for-once-upon-a-time-in-hollywood| archive-date=November 9, 2019| url-status=live}}</ref> For some of the driving scenes, Los Angeles freeways were shut down for hours in order to fill them with vintage cars.<ref name=cinema-blend/>\n\n== Music ==\n=== Soundtrack ===\n{{Infobox album\n| name         = Once Upon a Time in Hollywood (soundtrack)\n| type         = Soundtrack\n| artist       = Various Artists\n| cover        = \n| alt          = \n| released     = 2019\n| recorded     = \n| studio       = \n| genre        = [[Rock and roll]]\n| length       = \n| label        = [[Columbia Records]]\n| producer     = \n| prev_title   = [[The Hateful Eight (soundtrack)|The Hateful Eight]]\n| prev_year    = 2015\n| next_title   = \n| next_year    = \n| chronology   = [[Quentin Tarantino]] film soundtrack\n}}\n'''''Once Upon a Time in Hollywood''''' is also the name of the soundtrack. [[Pitchfork (website)|''Pitchfork'']] said the music was \"a highlight\" and an \"oft-disquieting mixtape of golden-age [[rock n' roll]], radio DJ patter, and period-specific commercials.\"<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://pitchfork.com/reviews/albums/various-artists-once-upon-a-time-in-hollywood-original-motion-picture-soundtrack/ |title=Various Artists: Once Upon a Time in ... Hollywood (Original Motion Picture Soundtrack) |website=Pitchfork |language=en |access-date=August 15, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190815202640/https://pitchfork.com/reviews/albums/various-artists-once-upon-a-time-in-hollywood-original-motion-picture-soundtrack/ |archive-date=August 15, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.radiotimes.com/news/film/2019-08-14/once-upon-a-time-in-hollywood-soundtrack-here-are-all-the-1960s-tunes-featured-in-the-movie/ |title=Once Upon A Time In Hollywood soundtrack: All the 1960s tunes featured in the movie |website=[[Radio Times]] |language=en |access-date=August 15, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190815202637/https://www.radiotimes.com/news/film/2019-08-14/once-upon-a-time-in-hollywood-soundtrack-here-are-all-the-1960s-tunes-featured-in-the-movie/ |archive-date=August 15, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref>[[File:Paul Revere and the Raiders 1967.JPG|thumb|upright|The soundtrack includes three songs by [[Paul Revere & the Raiders]]]]\n\n==== Track listing ====\n# \"[[Treat Her Right (Roy Head song)|Treat Her Right]]\" \u2013 [[Roy Head]] and the Traits\n# \"[[Ramblin' Gamblin' Man (song)|Ramblin' Gamblin' Man]]\" \u2013 [[Bob Seger]] System\n# \"[[Hush (Deep Purple song)|Hush]]\" \u2013 [[Deep Purple]]\n# \"Hector\" \u2013 The Village Callers\n# \"Son of a Lovin' Man\" \u2013 [[Buchanan Brothers]]\n# \"Paxton Quigley's Had the Course\" \u2013 [[Chad & Jeremy]]\n# \"Hungry\" \u2013 [[Paul Revere & the Raiders]]\n# \"Good Thing\" \u2013 Paul Revere & the Raiders\n# \"Choo Choo Train\" \u2013 [[The Box Tops]]\n# \"Jenny Take a Ride\" \u2013 [[Mitch Ryder]] & [[the Detroit Wheels]]\n# \"[[Kentucky Woman#Deep Purple cover|Kentucky Woman]]\" \u2013 Deep Purple\n# \"The Circle Game\" \u2013 [[Buffy Sainte-Marie]]\n# \"[[Mrs. Robinson]]\" \u2013 [[Simon & Garfunkel]]\n# \"[[Bring a Little Lovin'#In popular culture|Bring a Little Lovin']]\" \u2013 [[Los Bravos]]\n# \"Hey Little Girl\" \u2013 [[Dee Clark]]\n# \"[[Brother Love's Travelling Salvation Show (song)|Brother Love's Traveling Salvation Show]]\" \u2013 [[Neil Diamond]]\n# \"Don't Chase Me Around\" \u2013 [[Robert Corff]]\n# \"[[Mr. Sun, Mr. Moon]]\" (feat. [[Mark Lindsay]]) \u2013 Paul Revere & the Raiders\n# \"[[California Dreamin'#Lesser-known versions|California Dreamin']]\" \u2013 [[Jos\u00e9 Feliciano]]\n# \"Dinamite Jim\" \u2013 I Cantori Moderni Di Alessandroni\n# \"[[You Keep Me Hangin' On#Vanilla Fudge version|You Keep Me Hangin' On]]\" \u2013 [[Vanilla Fudge]]\n# \"Miss Lily Langtry\" \u2013 [[Maurice Jarre]]\n\n[[File:1967 Mamas and Papas.JPG|thumb|upright=1.36|[[The Mamas and the Papas]], whose female members are portrayed in the film and songs are featured, including a cover by [[Jos\u00e9 Feliciano]]]]\n\n==== Charts ====\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n|-\n! scope=\"col\"| Chart (2019)\n! scope=\"col\"| Peak<br/>position\n|-\n{{album chart|Australia|14|artist=Soundtrack|album=Quentin Tarantino's Once Upon a Time in Hollywood|rowheader=true|accessdate=August 24, 2019}}\n|-\n{{album chart|Austria|18|artist=Soundtrack|album=Quentin Tarantino's Once Upon a Time in Hollywood|rowheader=true|accessdate=August 29, 2019}}\n|-\n{{album chart|Flanders|17|artist=Soundtrack|album=Quentin Tarantino's Once Upon a Time in Hollywood|rowheader=true|accessdate=August 23, 2019}}\n|-\n{{album chart|Wallonia|98|artist=Soundtrack|album=Quentin Tarantino's Once Upon a Time in Hollywood|rowheader=true|accessdate=August 23, 2019}}\n|-\n{{album chart|Czech|35|date=201934|rowheader=true|accessdate=August 27, 2019}}\n|-\n{{album chart|Netherlands|68|artist=Soundtrack|album=Quentin Tarantino's Once Upon a Time in Hollywood|rowheader=true|accessdate=August 24, 2019}}\n|-\n{{album chart|France|49|artist=Soundtrack|album=Quentin Tarantino's Once Upon a Time in Hollywood|rowheader=true|accessdate=September 3, 2019}}\n|-\n{{album chart|Germany4|18|id=389153|artist=Soundtrack|album=Quentin Tarantino's Once Upon a Time in Hollywood|rowheader=true|accessdate=November 2, 2019}}\n|-\n{{album chart|Hungary|35|year=2019|week=35|artist=Filmzene|album=Once Upon a Time in Hollywood|rowheader=true|accessdate=September 6, 2019}}\n|-\n{{album chart|Poland|13|id=1228|rowheader=true|accessdate=September 5, 2019}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| Spanish Albums ([[Productores de M\u00fasica de Espa\u00f1a|PROMUSICAE]])<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.promusicae.es/listas/semana/4170-%C3%81lbumes-semana-37-2019 |title=Top 100 Albumes \u2013 Semana 37: del 6 September 2019 al 12.9.2019 |publisher=[[Productores de M\u00fasica de Espa\u00f1a]] |language=Spanish |accessdate=September 18, 2019}}</ref>\n| 15\n|-\n{{album chart|Switzerland|16|artist=Soundtrack|album=Quentin Tarantino's Once Upon a Time in Hollywood|rowheader=true|accessdate=August 28, 2019}}\n|}\n\n=== Additional music ===\nOther songs in the film include \"[[The Letter (Box Tops song)|The Letter]]\" by [[Joe Cocker]], \"[[Summertime (George Gershwin song)|Summertime]]\" by [[Billy Stewart]], \"Victorville Blues\" by The Harley Hatcher Combo, \"Ready for Action\" by [[Syd Dale]], \"[[Funky Fanfare]]\" by [[Keith Mansfield]], \"[[The House That Jack Built (song)|The House That Jack Built]]\" by [[Aretha Franklin]], \"Time for Livin'\" by [[The Association]], \"[[I Can't Turn You Loose]]\" by [[Otis Redding]], \"[[Soul Serenade (King Curtis song)|Soul Serenade]]\" by [[Willie Mitchell (musician)|Willie Mitchell]], \"[[Out of Time (The Rolling Stones song)|Out of Time]]\" by [[the Rolling Stones]], \"[[Twelve Thirty (Young Girls Are Coming to the Canyon)]]\" by [[the Mamas and the Papas]], \"[[Snoopy vs. the Red Baron (song)|Snoopy vs. the Red Baron]]\" by [[The Royal Guardsmen]], \"Straight Shooter\" by the Mamas and the Papas, also performed by [[Samantha Robinson (American actress)|Samantha Robinson]] as [[Abigail Folger]], and \"[[The Green Door]]\" performed by [[Leonardo DiCaprio]] as Rick Dalton.<ref name=every-song>{{cite news |last=Moran |first=Sarah |url=https://screenrant.com/once-upon-time-hollywood-movie-soundtrack-songs/ |title=Every Song in Once Upon a Time in Hollywood |website=[[Screen Rant]] |access-date=August 25, 2019 |date=July 26, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190727133005/https://screenrant.com/once-upon-time-hollywood-movie-soundtrack-songs/ |archive-date=July 27, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=soundtrack/>\n\nMusic by [[Bernard Herrmann]] created for ''[[Torn Curtain]]'' is used in the Spahn Ranch scene.<ref>{{cite web |last=Chow |first=Andrew R. |url=https://time.com/5637336/once-upon-a-time-in-hollywood-soundtrack/ |title=Breaking Down the Hidden Meanings and Historical References in the Once Upon a Time... in Hollywood Soundtrack |website=Time |access-date=September 2, 2019 |date=July 29, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190731021716/https://time.com/5637336/once-upon-a-time-in-hollywood-soundtrack/ |archive-date=July 31, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref> Herrman's music from that film included in ''Once Upon a Time in Hollywood'' is \"The Killing\", and \"The Radiogram\". Other music of his used is \"The Rocks\", and \"The Return\" (from ''[[Have Gun Will Travel]]''). Also used are the themes from ''[[Hell River]]'' by Vojislav Borisavljevic, ''[[Against a Crooked Sky]]'' by Alexis de Azevedo, ''[[:it: Un uomo chiamato Apocalisse Joe|Apocalypse Joe]]'' by [[Bruno Nicolai]], and ''[[Mannix]]'' by [[Lalo Schifrin]]. Also, \"Paxton Quigley's Had the Course\" (from ''[[Three in the Attic]]''), \"The Bed\" by [[Ennio Morricone]] (from ''[[Danger: Diabolik]]''), \"Ecce Homo\" (from ''[[:it: Sartana non perdona|Sartana Does Not Forgive]]'') and \"Mexican Western\" (from ''[[Any Gun Can Play]]'') by [[Francesco De Masi]], \"Cooler\" by [[Elmer Bernstein]] (from ''[[The Great Escape (film)|The Great Escape]]''), \"Freya Bangs\", \"Freya\", \"Karate Dance\", and \"TV Screen\" (from ''[[The Wrecking Crew (1968 film)|The Wrecking Crew]]''), \"Theme from ''[[It's Happening]]''\" by [[Paul Revere & the Raiders]], \"Dalton Gang Ride Entrance\" performed by Tom Slocum, John Bird, and the Cattle Annie Band (from ''[[Cattle Annie and Little Britches]]''), the \"Batman Theme\" (from ''[[Batman (TV series)|Batman]])'', the \"FBI Theme and Score Cues\" (from ''[[The F.B.I. (TV series)|The F.B.I.]]''), and \"Miss Lilly Langtry\" and \"Judge Roy Bean's Theme\" by [[Maurice Jarre]] (from ''[[The Life and Times of Judge Roy Bean]]'').<ref name=soundtrack>{{cite web |last=Gorber |first=Jason |url=https://www.slashfilm.com/once-upon-a-time-in-hollywood-soundtrack-deep-dive/3/ |title=How the 'Once Upon a Time in Hollywood' Soundtrack Helps Quentin Tarantino Shape His Version of 1969 Los Angeles |website=[[/Film]] |access-date=September 4, 2019 |date=August 1, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190802231046/https://www.slashfilm.com/once-upon-a-time-in-hollywood-soundtrack-deep-dive/3/ |archive-date=August 2, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n== Release ==\n[[File:Tarantino and Robbie at 2019 Cannes (cropped).jpg|thumb|upright=0.8|Tarantino and Robbie at the [[2019 Cannes Film Festival]]]]\n''Once Upon a Time in Hollywood'' premiered at the [[Cannes Film Festival]] on May 21, 2019.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://variety.com/2019/film/news/once-upon-a-time-in-hollywood-cannes-competition-quentin-tarantino-1203201142/ |title='Once Upon a Time in Hollywood' Joins Cannes' Competition Roster |date=May 2, 2019 |website=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] |accessdate=May 2, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190502132152/https://variety.com/2019/film/news/once-upon-a-time-in-hollywood-cannes-competition-quentin-tarantino-1203201142/|archive-date=May 2, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.festival-cannes.com/en/press/press-articles/communique/articles/the-screenings-guide-2019 |title=The Screenings Guide 2019 |date=May 9, 2019 |website=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] |accessdate=May 9, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190509101313/https://www.festival-cannes.com/en/press/press-articles/communique/articles/the-screenings-guide-2019|archive-date=May 9, 2019}}</ref> It was released theatrically in the United States on July 26, 2019 by [[Sony Pictures Releasing]] under its [[Columbia Pictures]] label.<ref>{{cite web |last1=McClintock |first1=Pamela |title=Quentin Tarantino's Manson Movie Shifts Off Sharon Tate Murder Anniversary Date |url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/quentin-tarantinos-manson-movie-will-hit-theaters-two-weeks-early-1128206 |website=[[The Hollywood Reporter]] |accessdate=July 18, 2018 |date=July 18, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180719024659/https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/quentin-tarantinos-manson-movie-will-hit-theaters-two-weeks-early-1128206|archive-date=July 19, 2018}}</ref> The film was originally scheduled for release on August 9 to coincide with the 50th anniversary of the [[Tate\u2013LaBianca murders]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://deadline.com/2017/12/sony-dates-quentin-tarantinos-9-for-1202218496/ |title=Quentin Tarantino's Manson Movie Set For Release on 50th Anniversary of Sharon Tate's Death |last=D'Alessandro |first=Anthony |date=December 1, 2017 |website=[[Deadline Hollywood]] |accessdate=June 18, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180618175501/https://deadline.com/2017/12/sony-dates-quentin-tarantinos-9-for-1202218496/|archive-date=June 18, 2018}}</ref>\n\nA [[teaser campaign|teaser trailer]] was released on March 20, 2019, featuring 1960s music by [[the Mamas and the Papas]] (\"Straight Shooter\") and by [[Los Bravos]] (\"[[Bring a Little Lovin']]\").<ref>{{cite news |last1=Singer |first1=Matt |title=What Are the Songs in the Once Upon a Time in Hollywood Trailer? |url=https://screencrush.com/what-are-the-songs-in-the-once-upon-a-time-in-hollywood-trailer/ |accessdate=March 21, 2019 |website=[[Townsquare Media#Web publications and services|ScreenCrush]] |date=March 20, 2019 |language=en |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190321175233/https://screencrush.com/what-are-the-songs-in-the-once-upon-a-time-in-hollywood-trailer/ |archive-date=March 21, 2019}}</ref> The official trailer was released on May 21, 2019 featuring the songs \"[[Good Thing (Paul Revere & The Raiders song)|Good Thing]]\" by [[Paul Revere & the Raiders]], and \"[[Brother Love's Travelling Salvation Show (song)|Brother Love's Travelling Salvation Show]]\" by [[Neil Diamond]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.tunefind.com/movie/once-upon-a-time-in-hollywood-2019 |title=Songs and music featured in Once Upon a Time in Hollywood |last= |first= |date=July 2019 |website=[[Tunefind]] |access-date= |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190724142756/https://www.tunefind.com/movie/once-upon-a-time-in-hollywood-2019 |archive-date=July 24, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref> The studio spent around $110 million marketing the film.<ref name=opening/>\n\nAn extended cut of the film featuring four additional scenes was released in theaters on October 25, 2019.<ref name=extended-cut>{{cite news| url=https://www.rollingstone.com/movies/movie-news/quentin-tarantino-once-upon-a-time-in-hollywood-rerelease-new-footage-902715/| title=Quentin Tarantino Re-Releasing \"Once Upon a Time in Hollywood\" With Unseen Footage| last=Reed| first=Ryan| website=RollingStone| access-date=October 24, 2019| date=October 23, 2019| url-status=live| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191024011955/https://www.rollingstone.com/movies/movie-news/quentin-tarantino-once-upon-a-time-in-hollywood-rerelease-new-footage-902715/| archive-date=October 24, 2019}}</ref>\n\n=== Home media ===\nThe film was released on digital and [[Movies Anywhere]] on November 22, 2019, and on [[Blu-ray]], [[Ultra HD Blu-ray|4K Ultra HD]], and [[DVD-Video|DVD]] on December 10. The 4K version is available as a regular version and collector's edition.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Evangelista |first1=Chris |title='Once Upon a Time in Hollywood' Blu-ray Releasing in December With Special Collector's Edition |url=https://www.slashfilm.com/once-upon-a-time-in-hollywood-blu-ray/ |accessdate=October 28, 2019 |work=[[/Film]] |date=October 28, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191029003843/https://www.slashfilm.com/once-upon-a-time-in-hollywood-blu-ray/ |archive-date=October 29, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n== Reception ==\n=== Box office ===\n{{As of|2020|2|13|df=US}}, ''Once Upon a Time in Hollywood'' has grossed $142.5 million in the United States and Canada, and $231.8 million in other territories, for a worldwide total of $374.3 million.<ref name=\"BOM\"/> By some estimates, the film needed to gross around $250 million worldwide in order to [[break-even]],<ref>{{cite web |last=Lee |first=Chris |url=https://www.vulture.com/2019/08/once-upon-a-time-in-hollywood-box-office-bet-pays-off.html |title=The Bet on ''Once Upon a Time in Hollywood'' Is Paying Off |website=[[New York (magazine)#Digital expansion and blogs|Vulture]] |access-date=September 6, 2019 |date=August 5, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190805145753/https://www.vulture.com/2019/08/once-upon-a-time-in-hollywood-box-office-bet-pays-off.html |archive-date=August 5, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref> with others estimating it would need to make $400 million in order to turn a profit.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/heat-vision/once-a-time-hollywood-debut-doesnt-guarantee-a-happy-ending-1227512 |title=Box Office: Why 'Once Upon a Time in Hollywood's' $40M Debut Doesn't Guarantee a Fairy Tale Ending |date=July 29, 2019 |first=Pamela|last= McClintock |work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]] |accessdate=August 28, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190809094907/https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/heat-vision/once-a-time-hollywood-debut-doesnt-guarantee-a-happy-ending-1227512 |archive-date=August 9, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn the United States and Canada, the film was projected to gross $30\u201340 million from 3,659 theaters in its opening weekend, with some projections having it as high as $50 million or as low as $25 million.<ref name=EarlyProjections>{{Cite web |url=https://deadline.com/2019/07/quentin-tarantinos-once-upon-a-time-in-hollywood-eyes-30m-opening-1202641601/ |title=Quentin Tarantino's 'Once Upon A Time In Hollywood' Eyes $30M Opening |last=D'Alessandro |first=Anthony |website=[[Deadline Hollywood]] |date=July 3, 2019 |access-date=July 3, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190703161646/https://deadline.com/2019/07/quentin-tarantinos-once-upon-a-time-in-hollywood-eyes-30m-opening-1202641601/ |archive-date=July 3, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.thewrap.com/once-upon-a-time-in-hollywood-quentin-tarantino-box-office/ |title=Once Upon a Time in Hollywood': Will Sony's Bet on Quentin Tarantino Pay Off? |last=Fuster |first=Jeremy |website=[[TheWrap]] |date=July 23, 2019 |access-date=July 24, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190724035722/https://www.thewrap.com/once-upon-a-time-in-hollywood-quentin-tarantino-box-office/ |archive-date=July 24, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref> The week of its release, [[Fandango (company)|Fandango]] reported the film was the highest pre-seller of any Tarantino film.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://deadline.com/2019/07/once-upon-a-time-in-hollywood-quentin-tarantino-biggest-fandango-preseller-1202652829/ |title='Once Upon A Time In Hollywood' Is Quentin Tarantino's Biggest Preseller On Fandango |last=D'Alessandro |first=Anthony |website=[[Deadline Hollywood]] |date=July 24, 2019 |access-date=July 24, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190724202322/https://deadline.com/2019/07/once-upon-a-time-in-hollywood-quentin-tarantino-biggest-fandango-preseller-1202652829/ |archive-date=July 24, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref> The film made $16.9 million on its first day, including $5.8 million from Thursday night previews (the highest total of Tarantino's career). It went on to debut to $41.1 million, finishing second behind holdover ''[[The Lion King (2019 film)|The Lion King]]'' and marking Tarantino's largest opening. [[Comscore]] reported that 47% of audience members went to see the film because of who the director was (compared to the typical 7%) and 37% went because of the cast (compared to normally 18%).<ref name=opening>{{Cite web |url=https://deadline.com/2019/07/once-upon-a-time-in-hollywood-quentin-tarantino-box-office-lion-king-weekend-1202654606/ |title=Hooray For 'Hollywood': Quentin Tarantino Sees His Biggest B.O. Opening Of All-Time With $40M+ As 'Lion King' Still Lords With $76M+ \u2013 Sunday Update |last=D'Alessandro |first=Anthony |website=[[Deadline Hollywood]] |date=July 27, 2019 |access-date=July 27, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190726232213/https://deadline.com/2019/07/once-upon-a-time-in-hollywood-quentin-tarantino-box-office-lion-king-weekend-1202654606/ |archive-date=July 26, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref> The film grossed $20 million in its second weekend, representing a \"nice\" drop of just 51% and finishing third, and then made $11.6 million and $7.6 million the subsequent weekends.<ref>{{cite news |last1=D'Alessandro |first1=Anthony |title='Hobbs & Shaw' West Coast Business Driving Pic To $60M, But Looks To Overseas For More Muscle |url=https://deadline.com/2019/08/hobbs-shaw-targeting-4-5m-thursday-night-early-b-o-read-1202659422/ |accessdate=August 4, 2019 |website=[[Deadline Hollywood]] |date=August 4, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190803004918/https://deadline.com/2019/08/hobbs-shaw-targeting-4-5m-thursday-night-early-b-o-read-1202659422/ |archive-date=August 3, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://deadline.com/2019/08/dora-and-the-lost-city-of-gold-hobbs-shaw-the-kitchen-box-office-weekend-1202665153/ |title='Hobbs' Hauls $25M; 'Scary Stories' Frighten 'Dora'; 'Kitchen' Sinks Melissa McCarthy & Tiffany Haddish To Career B.O. Lows \u2013 Saturday AM Update |last=D'Alessandro |first=Anthony |website=[[Deadline Hollywood]] |date=August 11, 2019 |access-date=August 11, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190810145835/https://deadline.com/2019/08/dora-and-the-lost-city-of-gold-hobbs-shaw-the-kitchen-box-office-weekend-1202665153/ |archive-date=August 10, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://deadline.com/2019/08/good-boys-hobbs-shaw-47-meters-down-uncaged-scary-stories-weekend-box-office-1202669605/ |title=How Universal Is Reviving The R-Rated Comedy & Making 'Good Boys' Great At The B.O. With A $21M Opening |last=D'Alessandro |first=Anthony |website=[[Deadline Hollywood]] |date=August 18, 2019 |access-date=August 18, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190816181043/https://deadline.com/2019/08/good-boys-hobbs-shaw-47-meters-down-uncaged-scary-stories-weekend-box-office-1202669605/ |archive-date=August 16, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref> In its fourth weekend the film made $5 million, bringing its running domestic total to $123.1 million, becoming the second-highest of Tarantino's career behind ''[[Django Unchained]]''.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://deadline.com/2019/08/ready-or-not-angel-has-fallen-good-boys-box-office-weekend-1202701545/ |title='Angel Has Fallen' Still Ascending Close To 'London' With $20M; Tarantino's 'Hollywood' Beating 'Basterds' \u2013 Saturday AM B.O. |last=D'Alessandro |first=Anthony |website=[[Deadline Hollywood]] |date=August 25, 2019 |access-date=August 28, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190822231242/https://deadline.com/2019/08/ready-or-not-angel-has-fallen-good-boys-box-office-weekend-1202701545/ |archive-date=August 22, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref> In its ninth weekend, its global total earnings reached $329.4 million, surpassing ''[[Inglourious Basterds]]'' to become Tarantino's second-highest global grosser behind ''Django Unchained''.<ref>{{cite news |last=Mendelson |first=Scott |url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/scottmendelson/2019/09/15/box-office-quentin-tarantino-leonardo-dicaprio-brad-pitt-margot-robbie-dwayne-johnson-jason-statham-john-wick-keanu-reeves-peanut-butter-falcon-shia-labeouf-dakota-johnson-farwell-awkwafina-lion-king-rogue-one-dark-knight/ |title=Box Office: 'Hollywood' Tops 'Basterds' As 'Lion King' Nears 'Dark Knight' And 'Hobbs & Shaw' Nears 'John Wick 3' |website=[[Forbes]] |access-date=September 15, 2019 |date=September 15, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190916044551/https://www.forbes.com/sites/scottmendelson/2019/09/15/box-office-quentin-tarantino-leonardo-dicaprio-brad-pitt-margot-robbie-dwayne-johnson-jason-statham-john-wick-keanu-reeves-peanut-butter-falcon-shia-labeouf-dakota-johnson-farwell-awkwafina-lion-king-rogue-one-dark-knight/ |archive-date=September 16, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n=== Critical response ===\nOn [[Rotten Tomatoes]], the film holds an approval rating of 85% based on 515 reviews, with an [[Weighted arithmetic mean|average rating]] of 7.83/10. The site's critical consensus reads, \"Thrillingly unrestrained yet solidly crafted, ''Once Upon a Time in Hollywood'' tempers Tarantino's provocative impulses with the clarity of a mature filmmaker's vision.\"<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/once_upon_a_time_in_hollywood |title=Once Upon a Time in Hollywood (2019) |website=[[Rotten Tomatoes]] |accessdate=December 12, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190330050307/https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/once_upon_a_time_in_hollywood |archive-date=March 30, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref> [[Metacritic]] assigned the film a [[weighted average]] score of 83 out of 100, based on 61 critics, indicating \"universal acclaim.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.metacritic.com/movie/once-upon-a-time-in-hollywood |title=Once Upon a Time in Hollywood Reviews |website=[[Metacritic]] |accessdate=September 28, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190722083158/https://www.metacritic.com/movie/once-upon-a-time-in-hollywood |archive-date=July 22, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> Audiences polled by [[CinemaScore]] gave it an average grade of \"B\" on an A+ to F scale, while those at [[PostTrak]] gave it an average of 4 out of 5 stars and a 58% \"definite recommend.\"<ref name=\"opening\"/>\n\n''[[The Hollywood Reporter]]'' said critics had \"an overall positive view,\" with some calling it \"Tarantino's love letter to '60s L.A.,\" praising its cast and setting, while others were \"divided on its ending.\"<ref name=\"beresford\">{{cite web |url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/heat-vision/once-a-time-hollywood-reviews-what-critics-are-saying-1212670 |first1=Trilby |last1=Beresford |first2=Katie |last2=Kilkenny |title='Once Upon a Time in Hollywood': What the Critics Are Saying |website=[[The Hollywood Reporter]] |date=May 21, 2019 |accessdate=May 21, 2019}}</ref> ReelViews' [[James Berardinelli]] awarded the film 3.5 stars out of 4, saying it was \"made by a movie-lover for movie-lovers. And even those who don't qualify may still enjoy the hell out of it.\"<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.reelviews.net/reelviews/once-upon-a-time-in-hollywood |title=Once Upon a Time in Hollywood (United States, 2019) |first=James |last=Berardinelli |website=reelviews.com |date=July 24, 2019 |access-date=August 18, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190818104043/http://www.reelviews.net/reelviews/once-upon-a-time-in-hollywood |archive-date=August 18, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref> [[RogerEbert.com]]'s Brian Tallerico gave it four out of four stars, calling it \"layered and ambitious, the product of a confident filmmaker working with collaborators completely in tune with his vision\".<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.rogerebert.com/reviews/once-upon-a-time-in--hollywood-2019 |title=Once Upon a Time ... in Hollywood Movie Review (2019) |last=Tallerico |first=Brian |work=[[RogerEbert.com]] |date=July 23, 2019 |accessdate=August 19, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190814182022/https://www.rogerebert.com/reviews/once-upon-a-time-in--hollywood-2019 |archive-date=August 14, 2019 |url-status=live}} {{Rating|4|4}}</ref> The ''[[Chicago Sun-Times]]'', [[Richard Roeper]] described it as \"a brilliant and sometimes outrageously fantastic mash-up of real-life events and characters with pure fiction,\" giving it full marks.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://chicago.suntimes.com/2019/7/22/20706094/once-upon-time-hollywood-review-movie-quentin-tarantino-brad-pitt-leonardo-dicaprio-richard-roeper |title='Once Upon a Time in Hollywood' review: Quentin Tarantino's colorful snapshot of an era |first=Richard |last=Roeper |author-link=Richard Roeper |work=[[Chicago Sun-Times]] |date=July 22, 2019 |accessdate=September 3, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190904035133/https://chicago.suntimes.com/2019/7/22/20706094/once-upon-time-hollywood-review-movie-quentin-tarantino-brad-pitt-leonardo-dicaprio-richard-roeper |archive-date=September 4, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref> Writing for ''[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]'', [[Owen Gleiberman]] called it a \"heady engrossing collage of a film\u2014but not, in the end, a masterpiece.\"<ref>{{cite news |url=https://variety.com/2019/film/reviews/once-upon-a-time-in-hollywood-review-quentin-tarantino-brad-pitt-leonardo-dicaprio-cannes-film-1203222012/ |title=Cannes Film Review: 'Once Upon a Time...in Hollywood' |first=Owen |last=Gleiberman |date=May 21, 2019 |access-date=July 4, 2019 |magazine=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] |publisher=[[Penske Business Media, LLC.]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190614092258/https://variety.com/2019/film/reviews/once-upon-a-time-in-hollywood-review-quentin-tarantino-brad-pitt-leonardo-dicaprio-cannes-film-1203222012/ |archive-date=June 14, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref> [[Peter Bradshaw]] of ''[[The Guardian]]'' gave it five out of five stars, praising Pitt and DiCaprio's performances and calling it \"Tarantino's dazzling LA redemption song.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/2019/may/21/once-upon-a-time-in-hollywood-review-tarantino-dazzling-dicaprio-pitt |title=Once Upon a Time ... in Hollywood review \u2013 Tarantino's dazzling LA redemption song |first=Peter |last=Bradshaw |website=[[The Guardian]] |date=May 21, 2019 |accessdate=July 4, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190703222104/https://www.theguardian.com/film/2019/may/21/once-upon-a-time-in-hollywood-review-tarantino-dazzling-dicaprio-pitt |archive-date=July 3, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref> Steve Pond of ''[[TheWrap]]'' said: \"Big, brash, ridiculous, too long, and in the end invigorating, the film is a grand playground for its director to fetishize old pop culture and bring his gleeful perversity to the craft of moviemaking.\"<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.thewrap.com/once-upon-a-time-in-hollywood-film-review-a-contemplative-quentin-tarantino-still-blows-the-roof-off-cannes/ |title='Once Upon a Time ... in Hollywood' Film Review: A Contemplative Quentin Tarantino Still Blows the Roof Off Cannes |last=Pond |first=Steve |website=[[TheWrap]] |date=May 21, 2019 |accessdate=July 4, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190704173107/https://www.thewrap.com/once-upon-a-time-in-hollywood-film-review-a-contemplative-quentin-tarantino-still-blows-the-roof-off-cannes/ |archive-date=July 4, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref> [[Peter Travers]] of ''[[Rolling Stone]]'' awarded the film 4.5 out of 5 stars, remarking that \"All the actors, in roles large and small, bring their A games to the film. Two hours and 40 minutes can feel long for some. I wouldn't change a frame.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/movies/movie-reviews/once-upon-a-time-in-hollywood-movie-review-quentin-tarantino-861778/ |title='Once Upon a Time in Hollywood' Review: Tarantino's Violent Tinseltown Valentine |authorlink=Peter Travers |last=Travers |first=Peter |work=[[Rolling Stone]] |date=July 22, 2019 |accessdate=September 10, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190907183059/https://www.rollingstone.com/movies/movie-reviews/once-upon-a-time-in-hollywood-movie-review-quentin-tarantino-861778/ |archive-date=September 7, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nKatie Rife of ''[[The A.V. Club]]'' gave it a B+, calling it Tarantino's \"wistful midlife crisis movie.\"<ref name=\"avc\">{{Cite web |url=https://film.avclub.com/once-upon-a-time-in-hollywood-is-quentin-tarantino-s-1836636382 |title='Once Upon a Time...In Hollywood' Is Quentin Tarantino's Wistful Midlife Crisis Movie |last=Rife |first=Katie |date=July 24, 2019 |accessdate=July 24, 2019 |website=[[The A.V. Club]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190724151612/https://film.avclub.com/once-upon-a-time-in-hollywood-is-quentin-tarantino-s-1836636382 |archive-date=July 24, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref> [[Richard Brody]] of ''[[The New Yorker]]'' called it an \"obscenely regressive vision of the sixties\" that \"celebrates white-male stardom (and behind-the-scenes command) at the expense of everyone else.\"<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.newyorker.com/culture/the-front-row/review-quentin-tarantinos-obscenely-regressive-vision-of-the-sixties-in-once-upon-a-time-in-hollywood |title=Review: Quentin Tarantino's Obscenely Regressive Vision of the Sixties in 'Once Upon a Time . . . in Hollywood' |last=Brody |first=Richard |date=July 27, 2019 |website=[[The New Yorker]] |access-date=August 17, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190816141803/https://www.newyorker.com/culture/the-front-row/review-quentin-tarantinos-obscenely-regressive-vision-of-the-sixties-in-once-upon-a-time-in-hollywood |archive-date=August 16, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref> In [[Little White Lies (magazine)|''Little White Lies'']], [[Christopher Hooton]] described it as \"occasionally tedious\" but \"constantly awe-inspiring,\" noting it did not seem to be a \"love letter to Hollywood\" but an \"obituary for a moment in culture that looks unlikely to ever be resurrected.\"<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://lwlies.com/articles/once-upon-a-time-in-hollywood-quentin-tarantino-love-letter-obituary/ |title=Once Upon a Time in Hollywood isn't a love letter, it's an obituary |last=Hooton |first=Christopher |date=August 26, 2019 |website=[[Little White Lies (magazine)|Little White Lies]] |access-date= |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190826112553/https://lwlies.com/articles/once-upon-a-time-in-hollywood-quentin-tarantino-love-letter-obituary/ |archive-date=August 26, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nThe film also garnered moral and theological praise. The Los Angeles Catholic Bishop [[Robert Barron]] praised the character of Cliff Booth as embodying the four [[cardinal virtues]],<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.wordonfire.org/resources/video/bishop-barron-on-once-upon-a-time-in-hollywood/24840/|title=Bishop Barron on \u201cOnce Upon A Time In Hollywood\u201d |last=Barron |first=Robert |date=August 8, 2019 |website=Wordonfire.org}}</ref> while the theologian [[David Bentley Hart]] wrote that the film \"exhibit[s] a genuine ethical pathos, one that actually brought tears to my eyes\" for its portrayal of \"cosmic justice.\" Specifically, Hart praised the revisionism when \"Tarantino's version of the story unexpectedly veered away into some other, dreamlike, better world, where the monsters inadvertently passed through the wrong door and met the end they deserved\" that \"gave glorious expression to a perfectly righteous rage\" in \"some other order of reality, if only an imaginary one, where ethereal sweetness had survived and horror had perished.\"<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/08/06/opinion/quentin-tarantino.html|title=Quentin Tarantino's Cosmic Justice|last=Hart |first=David Bentley |date=August 6, 2019 |website=[[New York Times]]}}</ref>\n\n=== Accolades ===\n{{Main|List of accolades received by Once Upon a Time in Hollywood}}\nThe film premiered at the [[2019 Cannes Film Festival]] where it won the [[Palm Dog Award]] and was nominated for the [[Palme d'Or]].<ref>{{cite web |last=Sharf |first=Zack |url=https://www.indiewire.com/2019/05/2019-cannes-winners-palme-dor-1202144785/ |title=Cannes 2019 Full Winners List: Bong Joon-ho Wins Palme d'Or for \"Parasite\" |website=indiewire |access-date=September 1, 2019 |date=May 25, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190604171148/https://www.indiewire.com/2019/05/2019-cannes-winners-palme-dor-1202144785/ |archive-date=June 4, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last=Utichi |first=Joe |url=https://deadline.com/2019/05/quentin-tarantino-wins-palm-dog-award-cannes-1202621869/ |title=Quentin Tarantino Accepts Palm Dog Award For Best Cannes Canine Performance In 'Once Upon A Time In Hollywood' |work=[[Deadline Hollywood]] |date=May 24, 2019 |access-date=August 20, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190823203020/https://deadline.com/2019/05/quentin-tarantino-wins-palm-dog-award-cannes-1202621869/ |archive-date=August 23, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref> The film received 10 nominations at the [[92nd Academy Awards]], including [[Academy Award for Best Picture|Best Picture]], [[Academy Award for Best Actor|Best Actor]], [[Academy Award for Best Supporting Actor|Best Supporting Actor]], and [[Academy Award for Best Director|Best Director]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.gq.com/story/academy-awards-oscar-nominations-2020-full-list|title=Oscar Nominations Are Here, and Yes, There Are Snubs|last=Grebey|first=James|website=[[GQ]]|language=en|access-date=2020-01-13|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200113190408/https://www.gq.com/story/academy-awards-oscar-nominations-2020-full-list|archive-date=January 13, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> It received five nominations at the [[77th Golden Globe Awards]], winning for [[Golden Globe Award for Best Motion Picture \u2013 Musical or Comedy|Best Motion Picture \u2013 Musical or Comedy]], [[Golden Globe Award for Best Screenplay|Best Screenplay]] for Quentin Tarantino, and [[Golden Globe Award for Best Supporting Actor \u2013 Motion Picture|Best Supporting Actor \u2013 Motion Picture]] for Brad Pitt.<ref name=\"GoldenGlobeAwards\">{{cite web |url=https://variety.com/2019/film/news/2020-golden-globes-nominations-list-nominees-1203426905/ |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20191209155146/https://variety.com/2019/film/news/2020-golden-globes-nominations-list-nominees-1203426905/ |title=Golden Globes 2020: The Complete Nominations List |website=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] |date=December 9, 2019 |accessdate=December 9, 2019 |archivedate=December 9, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/films/news/golden-globes-winners-2020-list-best-actor-actress-picture-awards-a9271126.html|title=Golden Globes 2020 winners: The full list|last=Stolworthy|first=Jacob|website=[[The Independent]]|date=January 6, 2020|accessdate=January 6, 2020}}</ref> It received twelve nominations at the [[25th Critics' Choice Awards]], including [[Critics' Choice Movie Award for Best Picture|Best Picture]], [[Critics' Choice Movie Award for Best Director|Best Director]] for Tarantino, [[Critics' Choice Movie Award for Best Actor|Best Actor]] for Leonardo DiCaprio, and [[Critics' Choice Movie Award for Best Supporting Actor|Best Supporting Actor]] for Pitt.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2019/12/critics-choice-nominations-film-tv-nominees-list-1202803785/|title='The Irishman', 'Once Upon A Time In Hollywood' Lead Critics' Choice Nominations; Netflix Dominates With 61 Noms in Movies And TV|first1=Pete|last1=Hammond|work=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|date=December 8, 2019|access-date=December 9, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191208185645/https://deadline.com/2019/12/critics-choice-nominations-film-tv-nominees-list-1202803785/|archive-date=December 8, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> DiCaprio and Pitt also received nominations at the [[26th Screen Actors Guild Awards]] where it was also nominated for [[Screen Actors Guild Award for Outstanding Performance by a Cast in a Motion Picture|Outstanding Performance by a Cast in a Motion Picture]] and [[Screen Actors Guild Award for Outstanding Performance by a Stunt Ensemble in a Motion Picture|Outstanding Performance by a Stunt Ensemble in a Motion Picture]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.sagawards.org/media/news/releases/nominations-announced-26th-annual-screen-actors-guild-awards-%C2%AE |publisher=[[Screen Actors Guild Awards]]|title=NOMINATIONS ANNOUNCED FOR THE 26TH ANNUAL SCREEN ACTORS GUILD AWARDS |date=December 11, 2019 |accessdate=December 11, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191212024926/https://www.sagawards.org/media/news/releases/nominations-announced-26th-annual-screen-actors-guild-awards-%C2%AE |archive-date=December 12, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> The [[National Board of Review]] included the film as one of the [[National Board of Review Awards 2019#Top 10 Films|top 10 films of the year]] and awarded Tarantino [[National Board of Review Award for Best Director|Best Director]] and Pitt [[National Board of Review Award for Best Supporting Actor|Best Supporting Actor]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.indiewire.com/2019/12/national-board-of-review-2019-winners-irishman-1202193897/|title=National Board of Review 2019: 'The Irishman' Wins Best Film, Adam Sandler Named Best Actor|publisher=[[IndieWire]]|first1=Zack|last1=Sharf|first2=Zack|last2=Sharf|date=December 3, 2019|access-date=December 4, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191203194830/https://www.indiewire.com/2019/12/national-board-of-review-2019-winners-irishman-1202193897/|archive-date=December 3, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> The [[American Film Institute]] included it as one of the [[American Film Institute Awards 2019#Top 10 Films|top 10 films of 2019]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nextbestpicture.com/latest/the-afi-top-10-films-of-2019/|title=The AFI Top 10 Films of 2019|first1=Matt|last1=Neglia|publisher=[[American Film Institute]]|date=December 4, 2019|access-date=December 4, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191204233746/https://www.nextbestpicture.com/latest/the-afi-top-10-films-of-2019|archive-date=December 4, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n=== Top-ten lists ===\n\nThe film appeared on many critics' year-end top-ten lists, among them: \n{{div col}}\n* 1st{{snd}} [[James Berardinelli]] \u2013 ReelViews<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.reelviews.net/reelthoughts/reelthought_1577637046|title=Rewinding 2019: The Year in Review|first=James|last=Berardinelli|website=Reelviews Movie Reviews}}</ref>\n* 1st{{snd}} Bill Desowitz \u2013 [[IndieWire]]<ref name=\"auto1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.indiewire.com/feature/best-films-2019-indiewire-staff-1202198437/|title=The Best Films of 2019, According to IndieWire's Staff|publisher=[[IndieWire]]| date=December 23, 2019}}</ref>\n* 1st{{snd}}  Alison Willmore \u2013 ''[[New York (magazine)|New York]]''<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.vulture.com/article/best-movies-2019.html|title=The Best Movies of 2019|first1=David|last1=Edelstein|first2=Alison|last2=Willmore|first3=Bilge| last3=Ebiri|date=December 2, 2019|website=[[New York (magazine)#Digital expansion and blogs|Vulture]]}}</ref>\n* 1st{{snd}} Anne Thompson \u2013 IndieWire<ref name=\"auto1\"/>\n* 1st{{snd}} Christian Blauvelt \u2013 IndieWire<ref name=\"auto1\"/>\n* 1st{{snd}} Justin Kroll \u2013 ''[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]''<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://twitter.com/krolljvar/status/1209247505524772864|title=And finally my top ten of 2019: 10. Ford v Ferrari 9. May They Never Grow Old 8. 1917 7. Marriage Story 6. Waves 5. Parasite 4. Uncut Gems 3. The Irishman 2. Joker 1. Once Upon a Time...in Hollywood|first=Justin|last=Kroll|date=December 23, 2019}}</ref>\n* 1st{{snd}} Brian Tallerico \u2013 [[RogerEbert.com]]<ref name=\"auto4\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.rogerebert.com/balder-and-dash/the-individual-top-tens-of-2019|title=The Individual Top Tens of 2019 &#124; Balder and Dash &#124;