{"title_page": "Josiah Pittman", "text_new": "'''Josiah Pittman''' (3 September 1816 \u2013 23 April 1886) was a British organist, composer of church music, music editor and accompanist at opera rehearsals.\n\n==Life==\nPittman was born on 2 September 1816, the son of a musician. He studied the organ under Goodman and [[Samuel Sebastian Wesley|S. S. Wesley]]. He later took lessons in the piano from [[Ignaz Moscheles]], and in 1836 and 1837 at [[Frankfurt am Main]] he studied composition with [[Franz Xaver Schnyder von Wartensee]]. He was organist sucessively at the parish church of [[Sydenham, London|Sydenham]] from 1831, at [[Tooting]] from 1833, and at [[Spitalfields]] from 1835 to 1847. From 1852 to 1864 he was organist at [[Lincoln's Inn]].<ref name=dnb00>{{cite DNB|first=Louisa M.|last=Middleton|wstitle=Pittman, Josiah|volume=45|page=387}}</ref><ref name=dmm>{{Cite Grove1900|first=George|last=Grove|wstitle=Pittman, Josiah}}</ref>\n\nIn 1865 he became accompanist at [[Her Majesty's Theatre|Her Majesty's Opera]], and from 1868 until his death he filled the same office at [[Royal Opera House|Covent Garden]]. The value of his musical work at the opera was best understood by those behind the scenes, while his literary abilities fitted him to assist in the translation of libretti.<ref name=dnb00/>\n\nFor several years he delivered the annual course of lectures on music at the [[London Institution]].<ref name=dmm/>\n\nPittman died suddenly, in his seventieth year, on 23 April 1886.<ref name=dnb00/>\n\n==Publications==\nA close study of the requirements of the established church with regard to congregational singing or chanting led Pittman to the conclusion that the ''[[Book of Common Prayer]]'' was made \"for song and naught else.\" He deplored the absence of music from the [[psalter]] as originally framed, and the consequent discouragement of the people from active participation in church services. In 1858 he set forth these views in ''The People in Church''. This was followed in 1859 by ''The People in the Cathedral'', mainly an historical treatise.<ref name=dnb00/>\n\nHe composed many services and much sacred music, some of which he published in 1859.<ref name=dnb00/>\n\nHe edited the series of operas in piano score published as ''The Royal Edition'' by [[Boosey & Hawkes|Messrs. Boosey]], ranging from Auber through the alphabet to Weber, and in co-operation with [[Arthur Sullivan]] he selected the operatic songs for the popular ''Royal Edition'' albums issued by the same publishers.<ref name=dnb00/>\n\nPittman also edited a volume of [[J. S. Bach|Bach]]'s Fugues, and the musical portions of theoretical works by [[Luigi Cherubini|Cherubini]], [[Adolf Bernhard Marx|Marx]], [[John Wall Callcott|Callcott]], and others. ''Songs of Scotland'', compiled by Colin Brown and Pittman, was published in 1873.<ref name=dnb00/>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n'''Attribution'''\n\n* {{DNB|first=Louisa M.|last=Middleton|wstitle=Pittman, Josiah|volume=45|page=387}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{IMSLP|author=Pittman, Josiah}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Pittman, Josiah}}\n[[Category:19th-century organists]]\n[[Category:19th-century British composers]]\n[[Category:Sacred music composers]]\n[[Category:R\u00e9p\u00e9titeurs]]\n[[Category:1816 births]]\n[[Category:1886 deaths]]\n", "text_old": "'''Josiah Pittman''' (3 September 1816 \u2013 23 April 1886) was a British organist, composer of church music, music editor and accompanist at opera rehearsals.\n\n==Life==\nPittman was born on 2 September 1816, the son of a musician. He studied the organ under Goodman and [[Samuel Sebastian Wesley|S. S. Wesley]]. He later took lessons in the piano from [[Ignaz Moscheles]], and in 1836 and 1837 at [[Frankfurt am Main]] he studied composition with {{ill|Franz Xaver Schnyder von Wartensee|de}}. He was organist sucessively at the parish church of [[Sydenham, London|Sydenham]] from 1831, at [[Tooting]] from 1833, and at [[Spitalfields]] from 1835 to 1847. From 1852 to 1864 he was organist at [[Lincoln's Inn]].<ref name=dnb00>{{cite DNB|first=Louisa M.|last=Middleton|wstitle=Pittman, Josiah|volume=45|page=387}}</ref><ref name=dmm>{{Cite Grove1900|first=George|last=Grove|wstitle=Pittman, Josiah}}</ref>\n\nIn 1865 he became accompanist at [[Her Majesty's Theatre|Her Majesty's Opera]], and from 1868 until his death he filled the same office at [[Royal Opera House|Covent Garden]]. The value of his musical work at the opera was best understood by those behind the scenes, while his literary abilities fitted him to assist in the translation of libretti.<ref name=dnb00/>\n\nFor several years he delivered the annual course of lectures on music at the [[London Institution]].<ref name=dmm/>\n\nPittman died suddenly, in his seventieth year, on 23 April 1886.<ref name=dnb00/>\n\n==Publications==\nA close study of the requirements of the established church with regard to congregational singing or chanting led Pittman to the conclusion that the ''[[Book of Common Prayer]]'' was made \"for song and naught else.\" He deplored the absence of music from the [[psalter]] as originally framed, and the consequent discouragement of the people from active participation in church services. In 1858 he set forth these views in ''The People in Church''. This was followed in 1859 by ''The People in the Cathedral'', mainly an historical treatise.<ref name=dnb00/>\n\nHe composed many services and much sacred music, some of which he published in 1859.<ref name=dnb00/>\n\nHe edited the series of operas in piano score published as ''The Royal Edition'' by [[Boosey & Hawkes|Messrs. Boosey]], ranging from Auber through the alphabet to Weber, and in co-operation with [[Arthur Sullivan]] he selected the operatic songs for the popular ''Royal Edition'' albums issued by the same publishers.<ref name=dnb00/>\n\nPittman also edited a volume of [[J. S. Bach|Bach]]'s Fugues, and the musical portions of theoretical works by [[Luigi Cherubini|Cherubini]], [[Adolf Bernhard Marx|Marx]], [[John Wall Callcott|Callcott]], and others. ''Songs of Scotland'', compiled by Colin Brown and Pittman, was published in 1873.<ref name=dnb00/>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n'''Attribution'''\n\n* {{DNB|first=Louisa M.|last=Middleton|wstitle=Pittman, Josiah|volume=45|page=387}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{IMSLP|author=Pittman, Josiah}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Pittman, Josiah}}\n[[Category:19th-century organists]]\n[[Category:19th-century British composers]]\n[[Category:Sacred music composers]]\n[[Category:R\u00e9p\u00e9titeurs]]\n[[Category:1816 births]]\n[[Category:1886 deaths]]\n", "name_user": "AtticTapestry", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eLife:Link toFranz Xaver Schnyder von Wartensee", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Josiah_Pittman"}
